title: Habıbuşağı (İzoli)
description: Habıbuşağı (İzoli) was an Urartian fortress situated near Kömürhan, at the left shore of the river Euphrates in the Elazığ Province of eastern Turkey. Today it is covered by the reservoir behind the Karakaya dam. Habıbuşağı is best known on account of a rock inscription of the Urartian king Sarduri II, son of Argišti (eighth century BCE) which reports the expedition of Sarduri to this region. Habıbuşağı is, in fact, the westernmost known fortress of the Urartian kingdom.

title: Masseria Caronella
description: A Roman villa rustica located near Taranto.

title: Via Flaminia militare
description: The Via Flaminia Militare, or Via Flaminia Minor, was a road constructed by Gaius Flaminius in 187 BCE that connected Arretium and Bononia.

title: Capitolium of Cosa
description: The so-called Capitolium temple of the Latin colony of Cosa.

title: Villa Mattonara
description: A coastal villa and associated necropolis.

title: Tell el-Hayyat
description: Village site located southwest of Pella (Tabaqat Fahl in Jordan). It was inhabited during the Early and Middle Bronze Age.

title: Cardo Maximus (Apamea)
description: The Cardo Maximus of Apamea in Syria is the site of the so-called "Great Colonnade", a portico that flanks the road for some 2 kilometers.

title: Far Wadi al Qattafi
description: The Wadi al Qattafi in Jordan's Black Desert is the site of numerous sites of occupation dating to the Neolithic period.

title: Aššur-mušalbir-palê-šarri-ēpišīšu-nāṣir-ummānīšu
description: The Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) surrounded his new capital Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") with a rectangular-shaped, 16,280-cubit-long inner and outer city wall. The name of the city wall (dūru) was Aššur-mušalbir-palê-šarri-ēpišīšu-nāṣir-ummānīšu ("The God Aššur Is the One Who Prolongs the Reign of Its Royal Builder (and) Protects His Troops") according to some Akkadian royal inscriptions, but Aššur-mulabbir-palê-šarri-ēpišīšu-nāṣir-perʾīšu ("The God Aššur Is the One Who Prolongs the Reign of Its Royal Builder (and) Protects His Offspring") according to other texts written in the name of Sargon II.

title: Khorsabad Gate 4
description: This undecorated gate is the southernmost city gate of the southeast wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

title: Khorsabad Citadel Gate B
description: This decorated gate was the principal entrance to the citadel of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

title: Šamaš Gate
description: The Šamaš Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Šamaš-mušakšid-ernittīya ("The God Šamaš Is the One Who Makes Me Triumph"), is the first of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the first of the east-facing entrances to the city.

title: Enlil Gate
description: The Enlil Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Enlil-mukīn-išdī-alīya ("The God Enlil Is the One Who Establishes the Foundation of My City"), is the third of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the first of the north-facing entrances to the city.

title: Ea Gate
description: The Ea Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Ea-muštēšir-nagbīšu ("The God Ea Is the One Who Keeps Its Spring(s) in Good Order"), is the seventh of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the first of the south-facing entrances to the city, but its precise location remains unknown.

title: Bēlet-ilī Gate
description: The Bēlet-ilī Gate, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Bēlet-ilī-murappišat-talittīšu ("The Goddess Bēlet-ilī Is the One Who Increases Its (Animals’) Offspring"), is the eighth of the eight city gates of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon") listed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) in inscriptions recording the construction of his new capital. This gate is the second of the south-facing entrances to the city, but its precise location remains unknown.

title: Fosso Marangone
description: A small stream that flows into the Tyrrhenian Sea. It now lies in the territory of the municipalities of Allumiere, Civitavecchia, and Santa Marinella and forms the geographical boundary between the latter two. The watercourse originates at Poggio Ombricolo.

title: Khorsabad Residence M
description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) had several royal residences constructed in the citadel of his new capital, Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad). Residence M, which has constructed on the western side of the citadel, is presumed to have been for one of the highest officials of the Assyrian Empire. Since no inscriptions were discovered in the ruins of the building, the owner/principal occupant of the this Assyrian palace is not known.

title: Khorsabad ziggurat
description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) had a temple-tower built on the palace terrace of his new capital, Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad). The ziggurat was located at the northern end of the temple sector, which was accessible from Sargon’s palace, through the Courtyard XV.

title: Via Aemilia Scauri
description: A Roman road connecting Rome to Placentia begun by Marcus Aemilius Scaurus in 115 B.C.

title: Mithraeum
description: Temple of Mithras at Roman fort of Housesteads (Vercovicium)

title: Acquapendente
description: The modern Acquapendente was settled in pre-Roman times but is known historically from the Middle Ages onward.

title: Maes Howe
description: Maes Howe is a Neolithic chambered cairn and passage grave on Mainland, Orkney, Scotland.

title: Sublanuvium
description: Sublanuvium was an ancient station (statio) along the Via Appia, located between Aricia and Ad Sponsas. While its precise location is unknown, the site is located at the twentieth milestone of the Appia.

title: Unnamed Pass
description: An unnamed pass in the Alpes Cottiae near Vesulus Mons

title: Zvartnots Cathedral
description: A seventh century AD church built by Catholicos Nerses the Builder (AD 641-653) and located in the Armavir Province of Armenia. The ruins of the church were listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000.

title: Saint Gayane Church
description: A seventh century AD church located in Vagharshapat (Etchmiadzin), Armenia and built by Catholicos Ezra I. The church was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000.

title: Hagia Sophia
description: A major paleochristian, then Byzantine, church in Istanbul; subsequently an Islamic mosque, and today a museum.

title: Roman villa of Ammaia
description: The Roman villa of Ammaia dates to the first century.

title: Bañuela (peak)
description: Bañuela is the highest peak of the Sierra Morena (Spain), measuring 1,332 m (4,370 ft) above sea level.

title: Cisterns of La Maalga
description: A group of 15 large cisterns constructed during the late Punic era as a water supply for the city of Carthage.

title: Santuario di Fondo Patturelli
description: A Samnite sanctuary of ancient Capua that was initially discovered in 1845. Active from the sixth century B.C. until the first century B.C., the Santuario di Fondo Patturelli is noted for its architectural terracotta as well as for the presence of a sacred maternal cult.

title: Samnite House
description: The so-called "Samnite House" is a domus in Herculaneum that originally dates to the second century B.C., making it one of the oldest buildings discovered at the site.

title: Tomb of Cuccumella
description: An archaic tumulus-type tomb at Vulci.

title: Tomb of the Dolphin
description: An early Hellenistic painted tomb at Vulci.

title: Tino (island)
description: An island in the Ligurian Sea designated as part of a UNESCO World Heritage Site, Tino is connected with the life of the seventh century AD Christian Saint Venerius.

title: Nuraghe la Prisciona
description: A nuragic site of northeast Sardinia, occupied from the fourteenth until the ninth century BC. At its height the complex covers ca. five hectares.

title: Lucus Furrinae
description: The Lucus Furrinae or Syrian Sanctuary is a sanctuary site on the Janiculum Hill in Rome. The first known construction at the site took place during the late first century CE and it remained in use until the mid-fourth century CE.

title: Library of Celsus
description: The Library of Celsus is a library and monumental tomb in Ephesus which was constructed ca. 110-120 CE.

title: Temple of Artemis at Ephesus
description: The Temple of Artemis, the central element of the extramural sanctuary of Artemis at Ephesus, was considered one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.

title: Roman cistern at Largo Zucchi
description: The Roman cistern at Largo Zucchi dates to the second century A.D. It was discovered in 1957 and had an original diameter of ca. 6.90 meters.

title: Odeon at Kom el-Dikka
description: The Odeon at Kom el-Dikka, used both for entertainment and academic functions, was built in the center of ancient Alexandria in the fourth century CE and rebuilt between the end of the fifth and beginning of the sixth century CE.

title: Arch of Septimius Severus
description: The Arch of Septimius Severus is situated at the northwest corner of the Forum Romanum. It was dedicated in A.D. 203 and serves to commemorate the Parthian victories of Emperor Septimius Severus and his two sons against the Parthians (194/195 and 197–199).

title: Temple district at Hattusa
description: An area of the upper city of Hattusha with the remains of up to 30 temples.

title: Theater of Sagalassos
description: The Theater of Sagalassos dates to the later second century.

title: Odeion at Sagalassos
description: The Odeion at Sagalassos occupies a terrace that is north of the Lower Agora and downslope from the Upper Agora.

title: Roman theater at Herakleia
description: The Roman theater at Herakleia dates to the time of Hadrian and remained in use until the fourth century. Its remains came to light in 1968.

title: Forum and basilica at Venta
description: The forum-basilica at Venta date to the first and second centuries A.D. and are of the so-called "principia" type. The basilica measures ca. 54.6 x 20.1 m and was of the Corinthian order.

title: Roman amphitheater at Noviodunum
description: The Roman amphitheater at Noviodunum was only discovered in 1996 and likely dates to the second century A.D. The arena measures ca. 50 x 36 meters.

title: Square Castan at Besançon
description: A square containing architectural remains of the Roman city.

title: Teatro Clunia
description: A Roman theater initially constructed during the reign of Tiberius.

title: Périgueux Roman amphitheater
description: The Périgueux Roman amphitheater dates to the first century.

title: Temple of Augustus, Barcelona
description: The Temple of Augustus dates to the second century A.D.

title: Roman theater of Zaragoza
description: Dating to the first century, the Roman theater of Zaragoza accommodated about 6,000 spectators.

title: The Temple of Athena Polias at Priene
description: The temple of Athena at Priene, designed by the architect Pytheos, is an especially good example of the Late Classical form of the Ionic order.

title: Théatre Gallo-Romains
description: The so-called Théatre Gallo-Romains could accommodate some 6,600 spectators.

title: Theater at Heraclea Minoa
description: The Theater at Heraclea Minoa dates to the late fourth century B.C.

title: Pula Arena (Roman amphitheater)
description: The Pula Arena is a Roman amphitheater dating to the first century.

title: Archaeological Border complex of Hedeby and the Danevirke
description: Hedeby was a trading center located between the Frankish Empire and the Danish Kingdom. The Danevirke fortifications separated the Jutland Peninsula from the European mainland.

title: Philistia (region)
description: A region in the southern Levant inhabited by the Philistines in the Iron Age. The Philistine Pentapolis comprised Ashdod, Ashkelon, Gaza, Ekron, and Gath.

title: Tẹl Ȧviv
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Bent Pyramid
description: A pyramid built by Pharaoh Sneferu (ca. 2600 BC). Representative point location based on OpenStreetMap.

title: Red Pyramid
description: The third pyramid built by Pharaoh Sneferu.

title: Abbazia di San Vincenzo al Volturno
description: An historic Benedictine monastery located in the Province of Isernia, near the source of the river Volturno.

title: Oletandros
description: An island of the Aegean Sea mentioned only by Pliny the Elder.

title: Torcularium villa
description: A Roman villa of the early second century BC constructed in opus incertum and named because of the presence of a torcularium.

title: Via Portuensis?
description: The Via Portuensis is an ancient Roman road that connected Rome and Portus. It proceeded along the right bank of the Tiber river, starting from the Pons Aemilius. In the first part of its course it is identical to the Via Campana.

title: Izola
description: The remains of a Roman villa maritima.

title: al-Bara
description: al-Bara is one the so-called "Dead Cities" of northern Syria.

title: Ager Romanus
description: The rural hinterland of the ancient city of Rome.

title: Jerwan Aqueduct
description: The Assyrian king Sennacherib had an aqueduct constructed between 703 and 690 B.C. near the ancient city of Girmua. The structure is part of the "Khinnis [Canal] System." The identification of the structure's builder is confirmed by means of several inscriptions.

title: Diniktum
description: Tell Muhammad, as suggested by textual evidence in the form of diplomatic letters, may have been ancient Diniktum, a Middle Bronze Age settlement located in the Diyala region of Mesopotamia. One of its Old Babylonian kings was Sin-Gamil.

title: Balāwāt
description: Balāwāt is the site of the ancient Assyrian city of Imgur-Enlil. A place from the TAVO Index.

title: Biluut Petroglyph Complex
description: A region of approximately 27 square kilometers north of Lake Khoton in the Mongolian Altay. The region contains over 12,000 petroglyphs dated from the Neolithic Period to the modern era.

title: Temple G at Selinus
description: Remains of an octastyle Doric temple begun in the sixth century B.C. but left unfinished.

title: Thonis
description: The Egyptian site of Thonis, sometimes referred to as Thonis-Heracleion, was located near the Canopic Mouth of the Nile, approximately 32 km northeast of Alexandria. Its ruins are now submerged.

title: Alexandria/Rhambakia

title: Via Triumphalis
description: A road running from the Pons Neronianus toward Monte Mario, eventually joining the Via Clodia some 7 miles from Rome.

title: Tomba di Fadilla
description: A Roman tomb on the Via Flaminia at Grottarossa.

title: Roman amphitheater at Richborough
description: The earthwork remains of the Roman amphitheater associated with the Saxon Shore fort at Richborough.

title: Pons Aelius
description: The Pons Aelius or Aelian Bridge (now Ponte Sant'Angelo) was completed by Hadrian in AD 134 to span the Tiber opposite the new mausoleum of the emperor.

title: Mausoleum Hadriani
description: Mausoleum Hadriani (now Castel S. Angelo) located on the right bank of the Tiber river was an imperial mausoleum built by Hadrian in the AD 130s.

title: S'Imbalconadu Roman villa
description: A multi-phase rustic structure (fattoria) located near Olbia, Sardinia. The quadrangular structure consists of twenty-some rooms arranged around a central courtyard; the built surface covers ca 1,000 square meters.

title: Temple of Hera I (the "Basilica")
description: An Archaic Doric temple probably dedicated to Hera in the central urban sanctuary of Paestum/Poseidonia.

title: Terrace and altar of M. Nonius Balbus
description: Marcus Nonius Balbus of Nuceria was an important civic patron of Herculaneum. Balbus was a praetor and proconsul of Crete and Cyrene and served as tribune of the plebs in 32 B.C. This architectural complex near the Suburban Baths included the terrace as well as an honorific statue and altar.

title: Roman theater at Ferentium
description: The Roman theater at Ferentium dates to the early Imperial period.

title: Hellenistic theater at Dion
description: The heavily reconstructed remains of the Hellenistic theater at Dion. Parts of the ancient underground stage system are preserved.

title: Tomb of P. Numisius Ligus
description: A large ara type tomb located outside the Porta di Boiano.

title: Roman theater at Helikore/Nicaea
description: Pliny the Younger discussed the restoration of the theater in a letter sent to the Roman emperor Trajan.

title: Amphitheater of the Three Gauls
description: The Sanctuary of the Three Gauls (Tres Galliae) was a late first century B.C. sanctuary in Lugdunum; the amphitheater dates to 19 B.C.

title: Sopka-2
description: A burial site on the banks of the Om River in western Siberia containing a number of non-contemporaneous Bronze Age tombs.

title: Roman theater at Ostia
description: The Roman theater at Ostia was built under the patronage of Marcus Agrippa.

title: Roman theater at Iguvium
description: The Roman theater at Iguvium is located within the Guastuglia archaeological area and dates to the late republican period.

title: Villa di Nerone
description: Nero built a villa and a port at Antium. The villa was subsequently expanded under Domitian and other later emperors.

title: Roman amphitheater at Teate
description: The Roman amphitheater at Teate dates to the first century.

title: Arch of Septimius Severus
description: The Arch of Septimius Severus dates to 205.

title: Chatby Necropolis
description: Understood to be the oldest necropolis in Alexandria that dates back to the Ptolemaic period and is located in the modern Chatby area of Alexandria.

title: Pompey's pillar
description: A Roman triumphal column in Alexandria, Egypt.

title: Catacombs of Kom el Shoqafa
description: The Catacombs of Kom el Shoqafa contain Roman period tombs, second to fourth centuries A.D.

title: Roman amphitheater at Vindonissa
description: The Roman amphitheater at Vindonissa was built under the reign of Tiberius.

title: Roman theater at Ferentinum
description: The Roman theater at Ferentinum is today poorly preserved.

title: Roman theater of Fourvière
description: A Roman theater in Lyon, France, that originally dates ca. 15 B.C.

title: Ostia Synagogue
description: The ancient synagogue located in Ostia Antica is one of the oldest known synagogues in the world. The structure's earliest phase dates to the reign of Claudius and it continued in use until the fifth century.

title: Gallo-Roman vicus at Dalheim
description: Remains of the Roman-era settlement at Dalheim.

title: Roman amphitheater at Falerio Picenus
description: The Roman amphitheater at Falerio Picenus dates to the first century A.D.

title: Roman theater at Falerio Picenus
description: The Roman theater at Falerio Picenus was completed during the reign of Tiberius.

title: Roman theater at Teate
description: The Roman theater at Teate measures 80 meters in diameter.

title: Serapeum of Alexandria
description: The Serapeum in Alexandria was a temple to Serapis erected by Ptolemy III in the third century B.C. It was destroyed in A.D. 391.

title: Acarnanian League
description: The Acarnanian League was a tribal confederation of the Acarnanians that later transformed into a league by the 5th century BCE. The league was incorporated into the Roman province of Achaea following the battle of Actium in 31 BCE.

title: Palace of Adad-nārārī III
description: The Assyrian king Adad-nārārī III (r. 810-783 BC) constructed a palace for himself at Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud). This royal residence, whose walls were covered with white plaster and painted with geometric and floral motifs, was built immediately to the south of the palace of his great-grandfather Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC).

title: Gula temple (Kalhu)
description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the goddess Gula. Although its location is not known, the Gula temple at Kalhu is thought to have been part of the Ninurta temple complex (in the northwest corner of the citadel), east of the Šarrat-niphi temple and north of the Kidmuri temple.

title: Šarrat-niphi temple (Kalhu)
description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the goddess Šarrat-niphi (an aspect of Ištar).

title: Tell Uqair
description: The archaeological site of Tell Uqair, ancient name unknown, is noted for its Uruk period architecture. This includes a small tripartite temple that stands on an irregular platform.

title: Mortuary Temple of Amenhotep III
description: Temple constructed in the Theban Necropolis during the 18th Dynasty.

title: Porta Collina
description: The Porta Collina was a gate in Rome's Servian Wall located on the Quirinal Hill. At the Porta Collina the Via Salaria and the Via Nomentana divided. Some remains of the gate were identified in 1872 on the Via Venti Settembre beneath the Italian Ministry of Finance.

title: Gaimanova Mogila
description: A Scythian burial site containing burials from the fourth to second centuries B.C.; located near the Dnieper River, southeast of the modern village of Balky.

title: Sestiae
description: A place in Adriatic Italy that is included on the Peutinger map.

title: Praedia Galbana
description: A suburban tract of land located southwest of the Aventine Hill that would come to be the location of the Horrea Galbae.

title: Qattara?/Karana?
description: Tell al-Rimah, is the site of a settlement inhabited from the third to first millennium BCE that has been identified as the site of either Qattara or Karana.

title: Caupona and Domus of L. Vetutius Placidus and Ascula
description: A thermopolium with a marble counter (I.8.8), connected to a private house (I.8.9) in Regio I, insula 8 in Pompeii. The walls of the house show extensive decoration in the Third style.

title: House of the Four Styles
description: The House of the Four Styles or Casa dei Quattro Stili (I.8.17) is noted for having examples of all four style of Pompeian wall paintings.

title: Kh., see Khirbet
description: This is not and never should have been a place resource; it was created because a cross-reference that should have been ignored in the Barrington Atlas Map-by-Map Directory was erroneously treated as place data during initial processing. It has therefore been moved from its original location to the errata section and its original URI deprecated.

title: Temple of Dakka
description: An ancient temple relocated in the 1960s before the completion of the Aswan dam.

title: Dolmen de Kerhenry
description: A Neolithic tomb.

title: Kermario alignments
description: A complex comprised of 1029 megaliths arranged in 10 rows.

title: Ménec alignments
description: A complex comprised of 11 rows of megaliths covering an area of 1,165 x 100 meters.

title: Petit-Ménec alignments
description: An alignment of megaliths located east of Kerlescan.

title: Anaktoron at Pantalika
description: The Anaktoron is an enigmatic megalithic building associated with the prehistoric Sicilian settlement of Pantalica; its polygonal blocks may date to the 12-11th c. B.C., but the current form of the building seems to be the result of Byzantine reconstruction.

title: Roman Aqueduct at Moria
description: The remains of a 26 km aqueduct that supplied Mytilene. The best preserved section measures some 170 m. long.

title: Necropolis of Pantalica
description: A large, rock-cut necropolis of over 5,000 tombs dating from the thirteenth to the seventh centuries BC.

title: Khirbet al-Batrawy
description: Settlement near the modern city of Zarqa in Jordan, inhabited during the Early Bronze Age (ca. 3000-2000 BCE).

title: Pontic rock-cut tombs
description: A number of monumental, rupestral tombs at ancient Amaseia (modern Amasya in Turkey) among which 5 large ones are mentioned by Strabo and attributed to the kings. Mount Harşena and the Rock-tombs of the Pontic Kings were submitted to the Tentative World Heritage Lists in 2005 by the Permanent Delegation of Turkey to UNESCO.

title: Monte Inici
description: A mountain of Sicily located just south of the Golfo di Castellammare.

title: Thorikos Residential and Production District
description: The residential and production district of Thorikos features the remains of a number of classical period houses and a silver refinement center.

title: Ruines Romaines de Mazelles
description: The remains of three significant Roman buildings on the river Cher.

title: Andelos reservoir
description: A reservoir that functioned as part of the water supply of Andelos.

title: Aphrodision
description: Located outside the city walls of Pergamon, this temple, according to an inscription (OGIS 273-9), was supposedly the site of a victory of Attalos I over the Tolistogi, Galatians, and Antiochus Hierax. it was likely later destroyed by Philip V.

title: Phrygia (kingdom)
description: Phrygia was an ancient kingdom of west-central Anatolia, developing around Gordion beginning in the ninth century BCE. According to Strabo, the Cimmerians defeated and overran the Phrygian kingdom in the seventh century BCE.

title: Porta Palatina
description: A surviving turreted gateway of the Roman circuit wall of Augusta Taurinorum.

title: Longthorpe
description: A Roman fortress of the mid-first century A.D.

title: Nuraghe Mannu, Olmedo
description: A single-tower nuraghe built in the later second millennium B.C.

title: Caspingium
description: A Roman settlement, now unlocated, of Germania Inferior. The Tabula Peutingeriana places it along the military road connecting Noviomagus and Lugdunum Batavorum.

title: Göbekli Tepe
description: The site of Göbekli Tepe, located in the Germuş mountains of south-eastern Anatolia, was the location of a Neolithic hilltop sanctuary. This sanctuary, thought to be a series of stone enclosures with T-shaped pillars carrying carving of wild animals, was built in the Pre-Pottery Neolithic and ranges in date from 9,600 to 8,200 B.C.

title: Mont Lassois
description: A massif that was the site of human settlement from prehistoric times onward.

title: Isthmia Fortress
description: A Byzantine fortress erected in the fifth century CE that includes three gates and 21 towers.

title: Shir as-Sanam Inscription
description: A Neo-Babylonian rock relief of Nebuchadnezzar II was found in the area of the modern city Qubbayat, close to the Wadi Oustane and the Jebel Akroum. The monument at Shir as-Sanam is about 16 Km from Qubbayat, on the road to Chambouq and Hermel. It is about located ca. 120 meters from the road, on the western side, 15 m. above the ground.

title: Mount Judi
description: Mount Judi (also al-Ǧūdiyy, Cûdî‎, Cudi), also spelled Guti and Kutu, is a mountain where Sennacherib had several monuments carved. The Neo-Assyrian name is Mount Nipur.

title: Simi
description: A Middle Minoan sanctuary located on the slopes of Mount Dikte in Crete.

title: Tell Qarqur
description: A major settlement mound along the Orontes river in Syria with over 10,000 years of occupational history from the Pre-Pottery Neolithic to the Mamluk period.

title: Castellaccio Europarco
description: A villa and a number of burials located along the Via Laurentina, dating from the fourth century BC to the second century AD.

title: Block F3
description: City block (insula) of Dura-Europos labeled according to modern excavators' scheme. The grid plan was established c. 150BCE and the site went out of use in 256 CE.

title: Talauera
description: Talauera was a Spanish village located in the west of the province of Toledo that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Talavera de la Reina.

title: Segouiola
description: Segouiola was an old Spanish village located in the west of the province of Sevilla during the kingdom of Alfonso X. Previously, the Arab population called it Boriauenzohar. Afterwards, this place assumed other names, including Torre del Guadiamar. Since the nineteenth century, Torre del Guadiamar county has been part of Benacazón.

title: Cortegana
description: A Spanish village located in the north of the province of Huelva that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Aroche
description: A Spanish village located in the north of the province of Huelva, near Portugal, that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Mora
description: A Spanish village that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Moura, and is located in the country of Portugal, across the border from the Spanish cities of Huelva and Badajoz.

title: Arslantepe (Melid)
description: Arslantepe became an important center in the Late Chalcolithic period. With the decline of the Hittite empire, the site became the center of an independent Luwian Neo-Hittite state (Kammanu). The state became a tributary of the Assyrian empire under Tiglath-Pileser I (1115-1077 BC) and it was sacked by Sargon II in 712 BC.

title: 'Ein Gedi
description: A Ghassulian public building dating ca. 3500 B.C. near the oasis of Ein Gedi on the western shore of the Dead Sea.

title: Tell Iktanu
description: An early and middle Bronze Age site in the Jordan valley.

title: Sos Höyük
description: An ancient settlement mound located within the boundaries of modern Yiğittaşı, Turkey, in eastern Anatolia.

title: Haçilar
description: An early human settlement located in southwestern Turkey. Human occupation began at the site toward the end of the eighth millennium B.C.

title: Ohalo II
description: The archaeological site of Ohalo II is located near the Sea of Galilee. It is one of the best preserved hunter-gatherer archaeological sites dating to the Last Glacial Maximum. It has been dated, via radiocarbon, to 19,400 BP.

title: Church of Saint Alexander Nevsky, Jerusalem
description: The nineteenth century Russian Orthodox church preserves within it remains of Constantine's original fourth century church of the Holy Sepulchre.

title: Prato Rosello necropolis
description: An Etruscan necropolis with a number of tumulus-type tombs dating between the eighth and sixth centuries BC.

title: Etruscan necropolis of Dometaia
description: An Etruscan necropolis dating to the sixth century B.C.

title: Nuraghe Nuraddeo
description: A Middle Bronze Age nuragic site with a central tower standing ca. 14 m. tall near Suni, Sardinia.

title: Nuraghe Sant'Imbenia
description: A nuragic complex near Alghero, Sardinia, composed of a main, central tower flanked by two minor towers and a bastion, and surrounded by a village. The complex dates from the Middle Bronze Age onwards.

title: Theatre of Apollonia
description: The theatre of the ancient city of Apollonia, situated just outside the city wall, on the east side. The construction appears to be late Hellenistic, with half of the seats cut out of the rock on the elevation of the acropolis, and the other half built up.

title: So-called West Church in Apollonia
description: A large architectural complex that includes a three-aisled church with a projecting western apse, a small atrium, a baptistery, and other structures built up against the inner face of the western stretch of the city wall of Apollonia.

title: Tunnel of Eupalinos
description: A sixth century B.C. aqueduct on Samos, the Tunnel of Eupalinos is an amphistomon, meaning it was excavated simultaneously from each terminus. The tunnel measures 1,036 m in length.

title: Gallo-Roman fanum at Recoules-Prévinquières
description: The fanum of a Gallo-Roman cult that was in use from the first century B.C. to the fourth century A.D.

title: Chastel-sur-Murat
description: Site of an Iron Age oppidum.

title: Bur-mar'ina
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources that is identified with brmrn in Aramaic texts and the modern Tell Shuyukh Fawqani.

title: Dabigu
description: An unwalled city mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources that is identified with Tell Dābiq.

title: Nichoria
description: Located in Messenia, Nichoria was a site with important Bronze Age and Iron Age phases.

title: Accu Sa Pira Nuraghe
description: A monopteral nuraghe located near Quartu Sant'Elena.

title: Treasury of Atreus
description: A Bronze Age tholos tomb with a corbeled dome and monumental ashlar facade on the Panagitsa Hill at Mycenae.

title: Domus of Vespasia Polla
description: A Roman domus traditionally associated with Vespasia Polla, mother of the emperor Vespasian.

title: Roman arch at Spoletium
description: The so-called "Arch of Drusus and Germanicus" at Spoleto.

title: Tigellio Roman villa
description: An elite villa dated to the first century B.C.

title: Roman theater at Tergeste
description: The Roman theater at Tergeste dates to the late first century A.D.

title: Roman baths at Sexi/Saxetanum
description: The Roman baths at Sexi/Saxetanum date to the first century.

title: Unnamed Aqueduct at Sexi/Saxetanum
description: One of five aqueducts known from Roman-era Sexi. This one is represented by an aqueduct bridge whose extant remains parallel the SO-02 between the Ctra. de Málaga - Velilla and the Carrera de la Concepcion in modern Almuñécar, Spain.

title: Roman amphitheater at Tipasa
description: A Roman amphitheater at Tipasa.

title: Beit Shemesh
description: City 30 km west of Jerusalem inhabited from the Bronze Age until its destruction in 701 CE.

title: Capo la Timpa
description: Capo la Timpa is an archaeological site in Maratea, Italy, with evidence for human settlement beginning in the Neolithic period.

title: Temple of Herakles, Cora
description: The Temple of Herakles at Cora was built during the 80s B.C. The temple is tetrastyle in its plan and built following the Etrusco-Italic temple tradition.

title: Abu Ballas
description: A sandstone peak approximately 200 kilometers southwest of the Dakleh Oasis containing extensive pottery remains dated from the 3rd millennium BCE through the Roman period. Abu Ballas was likely a way station along a caravan route connecting the Dakhleh Oasis with Gilf Kebir.

title: Dongola
description: The late antique capital of the Nubian state of Makuria, Dongola remained an important center of trade through the medieval period.

title: tribus Stellatina
description: The tribus Stellatina was a later rural tribe of ancient Rome which was established in 387 B.C.

title: tribus Teretina
description: Established in 299 B.C., the tribus Teretina was one of the later rural tribes of ancient Rome.

title: Sepulcrum Pansae
description: The tomb of the consul Gaius Vibius Pansa Caetronianus (43 B.C.) was located in the Campus Martius of Rome according to both literary and epigraphic testimony. Its precise location has not been determined.

title: Chiesa di Sant'Ilario a Port' Aurea
description: A sixth-, seventh-, and eighth-century Christian church located near the Port' Aurea of Benevento built during the Longobard period. The church was built atop Imperial remains and was an apsidal hall.

title: Arco del Sacramento
description: A Roman arch of the second century A.D. that faced on to the forum of Beneventum.

title: Osi
description: A tribe (perhaps Illyrian?) mentioned by Tacitus and located to the east of the Marcomanni and west of the Hercynia Silva.

title: Cairn de Barnénez
description: A Neolithic megalithic monument located near Plouezoc'h, on the Kernéléhen peninsula, in northern Finistère, Brittany, dated to ca. 4,500 BC.

title: Grange stone circle
description: Grange stone circle or Lios na Grainsi is the largest stone circle in Ireland, consisting of 113 stones and was built ca. 2100 BC.

title: Mochlos archaeological site
description: A multi-period settlement site in use by a number of civilizations dating ca. 3100 B.C. to A.D. 1200.

title: Casa della Regina Carolina
description: A domus at Pompeii partially excavated in the nineteenth century.

title: Khorsabad Gate 1
description: This decorated gate is the northernmost city gate of the northeast wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

title: Khorsabad Gate 2
description: This undecorated gate is the southernmost city gate of the northeast wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

title: Khorsabad Gate 3
description: This decorated gate is the northernmost city gate of the southeast wall of Dūr-Šarrukīn ("Fort Sargon"), the capital of the Assyrian Empire constructed by Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC).

title: Egalgabarinutukua
description: The palace of the eighth-century-BC Assyrian Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) at Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), Egalgabarinutukua ("Palace That Has No Equal"), was constructed between 717 BC and 706 BC. This royal residence was constructed on a high, mud-brick terrace located within the city’s citadel, which was located against the northwestern stretch of the city wall. This large, ornately-decorated palace complex consisted of over two hundred rooms (including chapels to the deities Ea, Sîn, Ningal, Adad, Šamaš, and Ninurta) and courtyards, as well as a ziggurat.

title: Khorsabad Residence J
description: The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) had several royal residences constructed in the citadel of his new capital, Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad). Residence J, which has constructed on the western side of the citadel, is presumed to have been for one of the highest officials of the Assyrian Empire. Since no inscriptions were discovered in the ruins of the building, the owner/principal occupant of the this Assyrian palace is not known.

title: Ningal temple (Khorsabad)
description: As part of the palatial complex of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) constructed six temples, including one to the goddess Ningal.

title: Adad temple (Khorsabad)
description: As part of the palatial complex of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) constructed six temples, including one to the god Adad.

title: Šamaš temple (Khorsabad)
description: As part of the palatial complex of Dūr-Šarrukīn (modern Khorsabad), the eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) constructed six temples, including one to the god Šamaš.

title: Theater of Orchomenus
description: A theater of the late fourth century B.C.

title: Eetioneia Hellenistic gateway
description: A fortified gateway protecting the mouth of the Piraeus harbor.

title: Castle of Bominaco
description: A castle at Bominaco in Italy that originally dates to the twelfth century.

title: Ponte Sereno
description: A bridge near Ferentinum (modern Ferentino in Italy) that is traditionally dated to A.D. 260 or after. A substructure in polygonal masonry supports the bridge.

title: Tell Um Hammad Sharqi
description: Archaeological site on the banks of the Zerqa River with signs of habitation in the Early Bronze Age I-II and IV. The eastern portion of the larger Tell Um Hammad site is called Um Hammad Sharqiya; the western section is Um Hammad al-Gharbi. The two may have been linked as a single village in the Early Bronze Age IV.

title: Necropolis of Porta Vesuvio
description: A necropolis of Pompeii located outside the so-called "Porta Vesuvio".

title: Castellum aquae
description: A building in Pompeii serving as the distribution point of water originating from the Acquedotto Serino, Claudio or Augusteo. The structure is also referred to as Castellum Divisorium.

title: Central Baths
description: A bath complex (IX, 4, 5-18) located at the intersection of the Via Stabiana and Via di Nola that was built following the earthquake of AD 62.

title: tribus Suburana (Succusana)
description: The tribus Suburana (also called Succusana) was an urban tribe of Rome, reportedly established by Servius Tullius.

title: Triangular Forum
description: A triangular plaza with an Ionic propylon that was surrounded by 95 Doric columns. A Doric order temple sits in the forum.

title: Mahabalipuram
description: This group of sanctuaries was carved out of rock along the Coromandel coast in the seventh and eighth centuries. The Group of Monuments at Mahabalipuram is a UNESCO World Heritage site.

title: Circus Gai et Neronis
description: Circus Gai et Neronis was originally built as a private race course for the emperor Caius. In the fourth century AD the north side of the circus was destroyed in order to make room for the first basilica of St. Peter.

description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Villa Aldobrandini

title: Villa di Vibio Varo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Villa di Vibio Varo

title: Villa Domitiani
description: Villa Domitiani, a large imperial villa near the Alban Lake, now the site of the Papal retreat at Castel Gandolfo.

title: Villa Esmeade
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Villa Esmeade

title: Villa Hadriani
description: The Villa of Hadrian (Villa Adriana in Italian) is a sprawling archaeological complex at Tivoli, Italy. The villa complex was designed and used by the emperor Hadrian in the second century A.D.

title: Villa Lucidi
description: A large villa complex built sometime in the first century B.C. and in use until at least the third century.

title: Villa Maxentii
description: A complex on the Via Appia constructed by Maxentius in the early fourth century A.D.

title: Villa Muti
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Villa Muti

title: Villa Neronis
description: The Villa Neronis was a rural villa of the emperor Nero, likely built early in his reign (perhaps before AD 60).

title: Villa Pamphili
description: The church of San Pancrazio was founded in the sixth century A.D. by Pope Symmachus. It stands beyond the Porta San Pancrazio on the Ianiculum. Below the church is a massive catacomb referred to as S. Pancrazio or Ottavilla.

title: Villa Torlonia
description: A Jewish catacomb discovered in 1919 on the grounds of the Villa Torlonia park in Rome.

title: Villa Torlonia
description: The extant Villa Torlonia occupies the site of an ancient Roman villa.

title: Villamagna
description: A large imperial Roman villa known from letters of Marcus Aurelius.

title: Aqua Alexandrina
description: The Aqua Alexandrina was an ancient Roman aqueduct that carried water 22.4 km from Pantano Borghese to the Baths of Alexander in the Campus Martius. It was in use from the third to the eighth century AD.

title: Aqua Alsietina
description: The Aqua Alsietina was an aqueduct built by Augustus that drew water from the lacus Alsietinus (Lago di Martignano) and conducted it to Rome.

title: Aqua Anio Novus
description: Aqua Anio Novus is an ancient aqueduct supplying the city of Rome. Begun by Caius in A.D. 38, it was completed and dedicated by Claudius in A.D. 52.

title: Aqua Anio Vetus
description: Aqua Anio Vetus, an aqueduct serving Rome and built originally during the third century BC. The Anio Vetus carried water to Rome from the Aniene near Vicovaro.

title: Aqua Antoniniana
description: The Aqua Antoniniana was a branch of the Aqua Marcia that carried water to the Baths of Caracalla.

title: Aqua Appia
description: The earliest of Rome's aqueducts, the Aqua Appia was constructed in 312 BC by the censor Appius Claudius Caecus. The aqueduct runs a course of 16.4 km, entering Rome at the Porta Maggiore. Frontinus estimated the daily volume at 75,537 cubic meters.

title: Aqua Claudia
description: The Aqua Claudia was one of the four great aqueducts of the ancient city of Rome. It was begun by Caius in A.D. 38 and completed by Claudius in A.D. 52.

title: Aqua Iulia
description: A Roman aqueduct built by Marcus Agrippa in 33 BC and expanded by Augustus between 11 and 4 BC.

title: Aqua Marcia
description: The Aqua Marcia was the longest of Rome's 11 aqueducts.

title: Aqua Tepula
description: The Aqua Tepula was an aqueduct built in 126 BC by the censors G. Servilius Caepio and L. Cassius Longinus.

title: Aqua Traiana
description: The Aqua Traiana was an aqueduct built by Trajan and inaugurated in AD 109.

title: Aqua Virgo
description: The Aqua Virgo was one of the 11 aqueducts supplying the city of Rome and was completed by Marcus Agrippa in 19 BC. The aqueduct was later revitalized by Pope Adrian I in the eighth century.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 unnamed aqueduct (Ostia)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 unnamed aqueduct (Vicus Augustanus)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 unnamed aqueduct (Lavinium)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 unnamed aqueduct (Gabii)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C4 unnamed aqueduct (Antium)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C4 unnamed aqueduct (Torre del Monumento)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 unnamed bridge (Ad Turres)

title: Pons Aemilius
description: The Pons Aemilius was the first stone bridge across the Tiber river at Rome (241 B.C.). Its remains are known today as the 'Ponte Rotto'.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 unnamed bridge (near Muraccio dell’Omo)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 unnamed bridge (Cessati Spiriti)

description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 unnamed bridge (Cora)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 unnamed bridge (Ad Sponsas)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D4 unnamed bridge (near Forum Appii)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 unnamed canal group (Portus)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 unnamed canal (SE Ostia)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 unnamed canal (Villa Domitiani, from Albanus L.)

title: Emissarium of Lake Nemi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 unnamed canal (from Nemorensis L.)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D4 unnamed canal group (SW Forum Appii)

title: Unnamed canals
description: unnamed canal group (NW Pomptinae Paludes)

title: Cemeteries around Caere
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 no. 1 (cemeteries around Caere)

title: Unnamed bridge over R. Quartaccio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 no. 2 (bridge over R. Quartaccio)

title: Roman bridge at Palidoro
description: An ancient Roman bridge along the Via Aurelia.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 4 (bridge over R. Arrone)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 5 (bridge over Fosso di Prima Porta)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 6 (bridge over Cremera fl.)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 7 (villa N Fidenae)

title: Villa delle Grotte at Grottarossa
description: A villa with beginnings in the early Republican period, continuing in use to the middle Imperial period.

title: Unnamed villas and a tomb near Pons Mulvius
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 9 (villas (2) and tomb near Pons Mulvius)

title: Unnamed bridge in the Piazza Eugenio Biffi
description: The remains of an ancient Roman bridge in the present Piazza Eugenio Biffi in Rome. This bridge is thought to have spanned the Almo river.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 11 (bridge near so-called Tomb of Geta)

title: Unnamed temple
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 12 (temple at EUR)

title: Ponte di Vallerano
description: The Ponte di Vallerano is a second century Roman bridge that carried the via Ostiensis across the fosso di Vallerano.

title: Unnamed bridge
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 14 (bridge at Mezzocamino)

title: Ponte di Malafede
description: A Roman bridge that is no longer extant. Quilici notes that the bridge was destroyed both by the Second World War and by urbanization that followed in the post-war period. Blake publishes a photo of E. B. van Deman and indicates that the bridge was built in peperino and of "indeterminate date". She compares the Ponte di Malafede with the construction of the Via Appia viaduct that lies just beyond Ariccia, a structure that was Augustan in its date.

title: Ponte Ladrone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 no. 16 (bridge (Ponte Ladrone))

title: Unnamed tuff quarry
description: A tuff quarry located at Castelporziano, to the east of Ostia Antica.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C1 no. 18 (tomb near Nomentum)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 19 (villa near S. Sinforosa)

title: Cemetery of Gordianus, Epimachus, Apronianus
description: A burial ground for the the Christian martyrs Gordianus, Epimachus, and Apronianus at the seventh mile of the Via Latina.

title: Parco delle Tombe di via Latina
description: A cluster of Roman Imperial tombs along the Via Latina excavated in the nineteenth century.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 22 (villa and aqueduct at Ponte delle Sette Miglia)

title: Villa and aqueduct at Vermicino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 23 (villa and aqueduct at Vermicino)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 24 (villa, NW Pantano Secco)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 25 (settlement and villa at Colle dello Stinco)

title: Unnamed villa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 26 (villa at Giardinetti)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 27 (bridge on Via Labicana)

title: Villa del Torraccio, Torrenova
description: The Forma Italiae notes the presence of drainage channels, foundations, and a cistern that are taken to be indicative of a Roman villa in the locale known today as Torrenova in the eastern portion of modern Rome.

title: Quarries at Aquae Albulae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 29 (quarries at Aquae Albulae)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 30 (tombs near Villa Adriana)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 31 (bridge over R. Acquoria, temple and quarries)

title: Roman bridges at Tibur
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 32 (bridges at Tibur (2))

title: Unnamed forts near Aefula
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 33 (forts near Aefula)

title: Untitled

title: Untitled
