title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 36 (bridge over Fosso di Acqua Rossa)

title: Ponte Ceccara
description: The Ponte Ceccara, also referred to as the ponte di Terra, is a Republican period bridge located on the fosso di Passerano along the Via Praenestina. It is located within the modern comune of Zagarolo, some 30.5 km southeast of the center of Rome.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 38 (bridge (Ponte dell’Acqua Nera))

title: Ponte Amato
description: The bridge known as Ponte Amato carries the Via Praenestina near Gallicano.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 40 (settlement on Colle Rasto)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 no. 41 (villa near Praeneste)

title: Mugilla?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 42 (settlement (Mugilla?))

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 43 (villas on Via Castrimeniense)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 no. 44 (villa at Vigna Spinabella)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 no. 45 (villa at Albanus L.)

title: Roman Villa at Lago di Nemi
description: A Roman Villa on the shores of Lago di Nemi.

title: So-Called Tomb of Clodius
description: The so-called Tomb of Clodius along the Via Appia near Castel Gandolfo.

title: Unnamed temple near Solforata
description: An ancient temple located near Solforata, between Lavinium and the Alban Lake in modern Italy.

title: Villas at Castelporziano
description: The 6,000 ha estate at Castelporziano has been, since antiquity, an elite seaside compound. Where a modern pleasure villa for the Italian president now sits are remains of Roman villas of the Laurentine shore; these remains have been the object of continued study since 1983.

title: Unnamed Roman villa
description: A villa rustica located near the coast, southwest of Ardea.

title: Road station at Foce del Fosso Grande
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 no. 51 (road station at Foce del Fosso Grande)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 no. 52 (temple near Ardea)

title: Ponte Loreto
description: A Roman bridge at Lanuvium.

title: Ponte di Mele
description: A Roman bridge along the Via Appia.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 no. 55 (bridge over Fosso delle Mole)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 no. 56 (temple at Algidus M.)

title: Unnamed Roman villa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 no. 57 (villa near Norba)

title: Ponte Tre Ponti
description: A Roman bridge located along the Via Amerina outside Civita Castellana.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D4 no. 59 (bridge (Ponte S. Felicità))

title: Roman villa near Setia
description: The platform, including cryptoporticus, of a republican period villa originally dating to the first century B.C. with evidence for second century A.D. renovations.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 E3 no. 61 (cult place near Trerus fl.)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 E2 no. 62 (temple NW Anagnia)

title: Untitled
description: The Salinae Romanae at Ostia were said to have been established by Ancus Marcius.

title: Abella
description: Abella was an ancient settlement of Campania of Samnite origin.

title: Abellinum
description: Abellinum was a settlement of the Hirpini in Campania.

title: Acerrae
description: Acerrae was an ancient Oscan city of Campania, perhaps originally named Akeru. The Romans granted it civitas sine suffragio in 332 BC.

title: Acherusia Palus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Acherusia Palus

title: Acqua Claudia
description: A Roman villa at Anguillara Sabazia that may have been built in order to take advantage of mineral springs. The villa dates to the Late Republican period but has only been partially excavated. A large hemicycle with ambulatio is extant; this feature may have been coordinated with the villa's garden.

title: Ad Flexum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Ad Flexum

title: Ad Medias
description: Ad Medias was a mutatio on the ancient Via Appia. It was located at the halfway point of the so-called Decennovium.

title: Ad Octavum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Ad Octavum

title: Ad Quartum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Ad Quartum

title: Ad Rotas/Rotae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F2 Ad Rotas/Rotae

title: Ad Septimum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Ad Septimum

title: Ad Teglanum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Ad Teglanum

title: Ad Turres
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D3 Ad Turres

title: Ad Turres Albas
description: Ad Turres Albas lay on the Via Severiana, midway between Circeii and Astura.

title: Aenaria/Pithekoussai (island)
description: Aenaria/Pithekoussai Ins. (modern Ischia) is a volcanic island located in the northern part of the Bay of Naples.

title: Aequana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Aequana

title: Aesernia
description: An ancient settlement (modern Isernia in Italy)

title: Afragola
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Afragola

title: Agellum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E1 Agellum

title: Agnone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F2 Agnone

title: Al(l)ifae
description: An ancient town of either Oscan or Samnite origin situated in the Volturno river valley.

title: Aletrium
description: A Hernican hill town that formed part of a sixth century B.C. defensive league against Volscian and Samnite aggression and allied itself to Tarquinius Superbus. Rome eventually took Aletrium in 306 B.C.; by the first century B.C. the site was a Roman municipium.

title: Alfaterni
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Alfaterni

title: Alfedena
description: A Samnite settlement occupying a strategic location in the valley of the Sangro river.

title: Amalfitana Civitas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Amalfitana Civitas

title: Amasenus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D3 Amasenus fl.

title: Amplero
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Amplero

title: Amyclanus Sinus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Amyclanus Sinus

title: Angitiae Lucus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D2 Angitiae Lucus

title: Antinum
description: A town of the Marsi in the valley of the Liris river.

title: Apollo et Nymphae Nitrodes, T.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E4 Apollo et Nymphae Nitrodes, T.

title: Aquae Caeretanae
description: Therapeutic springs located near Caere.

title: Aquae Sinuessanae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Aquae Sinuessanae

title: Aquae Vescinae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Aquae Vescinae

title: Aquinum
description: Aquinum was a municipium by the time of Cicero. It was thought to be the place of birth for the satirist Juvenal and the emperor Pescennius Niger.

title: Arpinum
description: An ancient center that originated as early as the seventh century B.C. that became a civitas sine suffragio in 305 B.C. Arpinum was the birthplace of Caius Marius and Marcus Tullius Cicero.

title: Arx Fregellana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Arx Fregellana

title: Astura
description: Astura was once a coastal island of Latium and is now a small peninsula at the southeastern edge of the Bay of Antium.

title: Atella (Campania)
description: A city of Campania located between Capua and Neapolis.

title: Atessa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F1 Atessa

title: Atina
description: Atina was a Samnite hill town with a polygonal masonry fortification wall.

title: Aufidena
description: A probable Samnite center, the Romans captured Aufidena in 298 BC. It only became a municipium after 49 B.C.

title: Aurunci
description: The Aurunci were an Italic tribe of south Italy. Their territory was incorporated into the Roman territory in the fourth century B.C.

title: Avernus L.
description: A volcanic crater lake located in the Phlegraean Fields, Lake Avernus served a major ritual role for ancient Romans and Greeks as they viewed it as an entrance to Hades.

title: Aversa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Aversa

title: Baiae
description: A Roman seaside community on the Bay of Naples that included thermal springs.

title: Baianus Sinus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Baianus Sinus

title: Bauli
description: Bauli (near modern Bacoli) was an ancient settlement of the Campi Phlegraei.

title: Beneventum/Maleventum
description: Beneventum/Maleventum (modern Benevento) was an ancient city of Campania of Samnite origin.

title: Boscoreale
description: A settled area of Campania that is especially well known for the Roman country villas of the first century BC that were destroyed by the eruption of Vesuvius in A.D. 79.

title: Boscotrecase
description: Located on the southern slopes of Vesuvius, Boscotrecase is a Campanian site destroyed by the eruption of Vesuvius in AD 79. Numerous opulent villas are known in the area by way of archaeological exploration.

title: Bovianum
description: Bovianum was a Samnite center and the capital of the Pentri tribe. It received Roman municipium status ca. 87 B.C. By the late first century A.D. it was occupied by veterans of Legio XI and known as the "colonia Bovianum Undecimanoruin".

title: Buca
description: Buca was an ancient settlement of the Frentani.

title: Caecubus Ager
description: A tract of Latium that bordered the Gulf of Amyclae, lying in the territory of Fundi.

title: Caedicius? Campus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Caedicius? Campus

title: Caiatia
description: A Samnite town that eventually became a Roman municipium of the tribus Falerna ca. 89 B.C.

title: Caieta
description: Caieta was a town of ancient Latium located on the Tyrrhenian Sea coast between Tarracina and Formiae.

title: Caieta Pr.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Caieta Pr.

title: Callifae?
description: A city of the Samnites that, according to Livy, was captured by the Romans in Republican times. Probably at or in the vicinity of modern Roccavecchia di Pratella in Italy.

title: Calatia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Calatia

title: Cales
description: Cales was an ancient city of Campania of Ausonian origins. The Romans captured the town in 335 B.C. and established a colony there.

title: Calor (river)
description: A river of Samnium and a major tributary of the Volturno river.

title: Campania
description: Campania was a region of southern Italy.

title: Campanus Ager
description: The Campanus Ager was the region around Capua that the Romans confiscated in 211 B.C. during the Second Punic War.

title: Campi Phlegraei
description: The Campi Phlegraei (Phlegraean Fields) is a large caldera (13 km wide) in the Bay of Naples region of Italy. In total, the the area comprises 24 craters, although a good portion of the caldera now lies under water. The area was important in Greek and Roman times; the Greeks established their first mainland colony at Cumae within the Campi Phlegraei.

title: Campobasso
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G2 Campobasso

title: Campochiaro
description: An Italic sanctuary sacred to Hercules located in località Civitella in the comune of Campochiaro. The site is to be connected with the Pentrian Samnites.

title: Campus Stellas
description: The name for a region of Campania that adjoined the Ager Falernus.

title: Capo di Sorrento
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Capo di Sorrento

title: Capreae
description: Settlement on the island of Capreae.

title: Capreae (island)
description: An island of the Bay of Naples off the Sorrentine Peninsula that has, since the time of the Roman Republic, been a popular seaside resort area. The emperor Tiberius maintained twelve villas on the island.

title: Capriati
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Capriati

title: Capua
description: An important ancient city of Campania with Villanovan and Etruscan origins.

title: Carecini Infernates
description: Carecini Infernates, one of the four ancient tribes that made up the Samnite population.

title: Carecini Supernates
description: The Carecini Supernates were a tribe of Samnites.

title: Carovilli
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F2 Carovilli

title: Carsioli
description: An ancient settlement along the Via Valeria, Carsioli was established as a Latin colony in the territory of the Aequi ca. 298 BC.

title: Cascano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Cascano

title: Casilinum
description: A settlement located in the border region between the ager Falernus and the ager Campanus, north of Capua.

title: Casinum
description: A Volscian hilltop settlement that became a Roman colony in 312 B.C.

title: Castellina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 A1 Castellina

title: Castro dei Volsci
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D3 Castro dei Volsci

title: Castropignano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G2 Castropignano

title: Castrum Novum
description: Castrum Novum was a colonia maritima established on the coast of Etruria.

title: Caudium
description: A city of Samnium located between Capua and Beneventum. In 321 B.C. the Samnites under C. Pontius encamped there before defeating the Romans at the battle of the Caudine Forks.

title: Cereatae Marianae
description: Cereatae Marianae, purported to have been the birthplace of Gaius Marius, is thought to have been located where the 13th century abbey church of Casamari now stands (in the modern province of Frosinone, Lazio, Italy).

title: Cerfennia
description: A settlement of the Marsi and a Roman road station on the Via Valeria.

title: Chiauci
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F2 Chiauci

title: Kirkaion Akron/Veneris Pr.
description: Kirkaion Akron/Veneris Pr. (Monte Circeo) is a mountainous promontory on the Tyrrhenian coast of Italy.

title: Circeii 1
description: Circeii received a Latin colony ca. 390 B.C. The remains on the site include an enclosure wall built in polygonal masonry. "Circeii 1" refers to the earlier Roman colony founded at the eastern side of Monte Circeo. The settlement eventually moved to the western side of the peninsula.

title: Circeii 2
description: A port on the Tyrrhenian coast. In myth, the site was considered to be one of the stopping points of the hero Odysseus.

title: Civitanova
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F2 Civitanova

title: Clanius (river)
description: A river of Campania that likely flowed into the Tyrrhenian Sea near Liternum.

title: Cliternia
description: A city of northern Apulia.

title: Clostra (Romana)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 C3 Clostra (Romana)

title: Cluturnum
description: Cluturnum was a site in Samnium, located near Aesernia. Its exact location cannot be determined.

title: Cocullo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E1 Cocullo

title: Colle Mitra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E1 Colle Mitra

title: Colle Sparanise
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G2 Colle Sparanise

title: Colle Tassito
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E1 Colle Tassito

title: Colles Leucogaei
description: A name for volcanic hills of a whitish hue around Puteoli.

title: Cretone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 C1 Cretone

title: Cumae/Kyme (Campanian)
description: An ancient settlement of Campania, Cumae was the first Greek colony established on the Italian mainland in the eighth century BC.

title: Cumanus Sinus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E4 Cumanus Sinus

title: Damecuta
description: An Imperial villa excavated by A. Maiuri in the 1930s, Damecuta was connected to the Iulio-Claudian emperors. The construction of later Medieval and Bourbon fortifications on the site significantly damaged the ancient remains. The Medieval Damecuta tower stands atop part of the Roman villa.

title: Decennovium
description: Decennovium refers to a 19-mile stretch of the Via Appia from the Forum Appii to Tarracina that continued through the paludes Pontinae.

title: Diana Tifatina, T.
description: The Fanum Dianae Tifatinae located on the slopes of Mt. Tifata in Campania.

title: Digentia (river)
description: A stream in the ager Sabinus.

title: Dikaiarcheia/Puteoli
description: A maritime city of Campania situated on the Phlegrean Peninsula. The settlement started as a Greek colony and became a Roman colony under the name Puteoli in 194 B.C.

title: Duronia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F2 Duronia

title: Epomeus M.
description: The highest mountain on the island of Ischia.

title: Eumorfiana? Ins.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D4 Eumorfiana? Ins.

title: Fabrateria Nova
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Fabrateria Nova

title: Fabrateria Vetus
description: Fabrateria Vetus was a Volscian settlement that surrendered to Rome in 424 B.C.

title: Fagifulae
description: Fagifulae was a center of the Pentrian Samnites.

title: Falernus Ager
description: The Ager Falernus comprised the northern portion of Campania from the Massican hills to the Vulturnus river. The area was celebrated for its fertility and, in particular, for its wines.

title: Faustianum?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Faustianum?

title: Ferentinum
description: A Hernican town along the Via Latina that the Romans captured in 364 B.C. Later in the Republican period (after 195 B.C.) the city received Roman municipal status.

title: Ferrazzano
description: A fortified ancient hilltop, Ferrazzano is usually identified as a Samnite site.

title: Fibrenus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Fibrenus fl.

title: Fonte Romito
description: A pre-Roman and Roman settlement of Samnium.

title: Formiae
description: An ancient settlement of likely Greek origin along the Via Appia. Cicero was assassinated near Formiae (now Formia) in 43 B.C.

title: Forum Popillii
description: An important town of the Ager Falernus, not to be confused with Forum Popili, the modern Polla.

title: Fratte
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Fratte

title: Fregellae
description: Fregellae was a city of Latium Adjectum that became a Roman colony in 328 B.C., but was subsequently captured by the Samnites; a Roman presence was re-established in 313 B.C. Loyal to Rome during the Second Punic War, Fregellae revolted in 125 B.C. and the site was razed.

title: Fregellanum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Fregellanum

title: Frentani
description: An Italic people of eastern Italy occupying a territory between the Apennines and the Adriatic seaboard, the Frentani had a close cultural connection with the Samnites.

title: Frosolone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F2 Frosolone

title: Frusino
description: Frusino (modern Frosinone) was a town in Latium along the Via Latina that was originally a Volscian settlement.

title: Fucinus L.
description: A lake of ancient Italy, site of a major battle of 89 BC. Flood and drainage controls were attempted by both Claudius and Hadrian. The Torlonia family drained the lake in the nineteenth century.

title: Fundanus L.
description: A brackish lake ca. 90 km southeast of Rome.

title: Fundi
description: Fundi achieved civitas sine suffragio after the Latin War in 338 B.C.

title: Furculae Caudinae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 Furculae Caudinae

title: Gallinaria Silva
description: An evergreen thicket of the area around Cumae.

title: Gaurus M.
description: An eruptive volcanic vent in the Phlegraean Fields.

title: Gianola
description: The site of a villa associated with Lucius Vitruvius Mamurra.

title: Gioia dei Marsi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Gioia dei Marsi

title: Giurlanda
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E1 Giurlanda

title: Grottacce
description: At Grottacce are the remains of a Roman seaside villa or villa maritima.

title: Hamae
description: Hamae is an ancient site of Campania located between Capua and Cumae, although its precise location is difficult to fix. The people of Capua gathered there for a solemn religious festival.

title: Herculaneum
description: An ancient Roman town of Campania destroyed by the eruption of Mt. Vesuvius in A.D. 79. Named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997.

title: ‘Herculis Rani’?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 ‘Herculis Rani’?

title: Herculis Petra
description: An islet in the Gulf of Naples.

title: Imeus (mountain)
description: Imeus Mons is the name given in the Peutinger Table to a pass that leads from the Fucine lake to the territory of the Peligni; the Via Valeria crossed the pass which is now known as the Forca Caruso.

title: Interamna Lirenas
description: A Latin colony founded ca. 312 B.C. along the Via Latina. The site was sacked by Samnites (ca. 294 B.C.) and subsequently by Hannibal (212 B.C.). It received Roman municipal status in 90 B.C.

title: ‘Invinias’
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 ‘Invinias’

title: ‘Iovis Lareni’
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F1 ‘Iovis Lareni’

title: Iuvanum
description: A Roman municipium founded in 87 BC after the Social War, Iuvanum sits on the site of a pre-existing Samnite settlement that occupies an upland plateau.

title: Iuvencus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Iuvencus fl.

title: Kupelternum/Cubulteria
description: Kupelternum/Cubulteria was an ancient Samnite settlement.

title: La Giostra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 La Giostra

title: Lactarius (mountain)
description: A mountain ridge of Campania that is a spur branching off of the Apennines. Many Roman villas in this vicinity were preserved by the eruption of Mt. Vesuvius.

title: Lago di Paola
description: A villa of the emperor Domitian located in the area of Circeii.

title: *Lavernae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E1 *Lavernae

title: Latium (region)
description: The territory of the Latins.

title: Latium Adiectum
description: A region of ancient Italy characterized as an area of Latin colonial expansion; also referred to as Latium Novum.

title: Laurinienses
description: An ancient people, tribe, or cultural group. Located: Vallo di Lauro.

title: Lautulae
description: Lautulae is a narrow pass (saltus) located above Terracina in Latium.

title: Ligures Baebiani
description: Ligures Baebiani was a Ligurian settlement in Samnium.

title: Liris/Clanis (river)
description: The Liris river (modern Liri) is one of the principal rivers of central Italy.

title: Liternum
description: An ancient city of Campania located near the mouth of the Volturnus river; a Roman colony was established at Liternum in 194 B.C. The site is most famous as the location of the villa of Scipio Africanus, as described by Seneca.

title: Lucanus? Ager
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F2 Lucanus? Ager

title: Lucrinus (lake)
description: A small lake near Lake Avernus.

title: Lucus Feroniae
description: A sanctuary of Feronia located at a spring on the via Appia near Tarracina.

title: Madonnna del Canneto
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Madonnna del Canneto

title: Malborghetto
description: The hamlet of Malborghetto, located on the ancient Via Flaminia, is traditionally linked with Constantine the Great and his visions of victory that occurred prior to the battle of Saxa Rubra on 28 October A.D. 312. The quadrifons arch, dating to the fourth century, marks the intersection of the Via Flaminia and the Via Tiberina.

title: Marcianum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Marcianum

title: Marcianus Fundus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Marcianus Fundus

title: Marica
description: Marica, an Italic goddess, was worshipped in a sacred grove located between Minturnae and the estuary of the Liris river.

title: Marruvium
description: Ancient Marruvium was the principal city of the Italic tribe of the Marsi.

title: Massicus
description: Mons Massicus, a mountain ridge of ancient Italy, in the territory of the Aurunci, at the border of Latium and Campania.

title: Matrice
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G2 Matrice

title: Melpis (river)
description: The Melfa river flows through Lazio, originating from the Monti della Meta and joining the Liri river near San Giovanni Incarico.

title: Mignano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Mignano

title: Minerva, T.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Minerva, T.

title: Minervae Pr.
description: Punta Campanella lies at the western extremity of the Sorrentine Peninsula.

title: Minori
description: Minori is the site of a major villa located on the Amalfi coast, some 11 km WSW of Salerno. Destroyed by a possible landslide, the villa was in use from the Iulio-Claudian period through to the Flavian period.

title: Minturnae
description: Originally an Ausonian town that fought against Rome in 314 B.C., Minturnae became a colony in 296 B.C. The site is located on the Garigliano river (ancient Liris) and served an important economic function. The Via Appia passes through the city.

title: Misenum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Misenum

title: Misenum (promontory)
description: A promontory that sheltered the ancient Portus Julius, the harborage of the Roman western imperial fleet. The feature takes its name from Misenus, one of the sailors aboard Aeneas' ship.

title: Monte Acero
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Monte Acero

title: Monte Annamunna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Monte Annamunna

title: Monte Castellone (Torcino)
description: A fortified center located in the comune of Ciorlano.

title: Monte Castellone 2
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Monte Castellone 2

title: Monte Cavallerizzo
description: Monte Cavallerizzo is a fortified Samnite center - perhaps dating to the fourth century B.C. - located in close proximity to the sanctuary at Vastogirardi.

title: Monte Cicoli
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Monte Cicoli

title: Monte Cila
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Monte Cila

title: Monte del Fico
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Monte del Fico

title: Monte Frascara
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Monte Frascara

title: Monte Monaco di Gioia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Monte Monaco di Gioia

title: Monte Nero
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D2 Monte Nero

title: Monte S. Angelo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Monte S. Angelo

title: Monte S. Croce
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Monte S. Croce

title: Monte S. Croce
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Monte S. Croce

title: Monte Saraceno di Cercemaggiore
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 Monte Saraceno di Cercemaggiore

title: Monte Vairano
description: At Monte Vairano are the remains of a fortified center of the Pentrian Samnites.

title: Monteverde
description: The eleventh century monastery of Santa Maria di Monteverde sits atop and reuses elements of Roman and pre-Roman settlements on the hilltop.

title: Montevetrano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Montevetrano

title: Morroni
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Morroni

title: Mura delle Fate
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Mura delle Fate

title: Mura di S. Stefano
description: A second century A.D. Roman villa built atop an earlier villa rustica.

title: Neratii
description: This site of an imperial villa, dating to the first and second centuries, covers an area of ca. 15,000 sq. m. It is located in the southern portion of the modern civic territory of San Giuliano del Sannio in the Província de Campobasso, Italy.

title: Nesis (island)
description: A volcanic islet of the Phlegraean Islands archipelago, Nesis was in antiquity the site of many elite seaside villas.

title: Nola
description: The city of Nola (Nuvlana) is considered one of the oldest in Campania. Under Augustus the settlement became a Roman colony; it was the spot where Augustus died in A.D. 14.

title: Nuceria (Alfaterna)
description: Nuceria (Alfaterna) (modern Nocera Inferiore) is an ancient settlement in Campania. In pre-Roman times this was the chief settlement of the Sarnus river valley.

title: *Nuceriola
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 *Nuceriola

title: Nymphaeus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 C3 Nymphaeus fl.

title: Oplontis
description: An ancient place (modern Torre Annunziata in Italy), lying between Pompeii and Herculaneum and buried by the eruption of Vesuvius in 79 CE. Its ancient name is known only from Peutinger's Roman Map.

title: Oratino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G2 Oratino

title: Pagus Capriculanus?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Pagus Capriculanus?

title: Pagus Meflanus
description: Pagus Meflanus was likely located in the Apennines to the northeast of Beneventum.

title: Pagus Sarclanus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Pagus Sarclanus

title: Pagus Vescinus
description: The Pagus Vescinus is only attested epigraphically.

title: Palazzo a Mare
description: The site of one of the twelve villas of Tiberius, and perhaps the largest, on the island of Capreae.

title: *Pallanum
description: An ancient settlement of the Frentani located on Monte Pallano.

title: Palmaria (island)
description: The second largest of the Pontine Islands, the modern Palmarola.

title: Paludes Minturnenses
description: The Marshes of Mintumae were located near the mouth of the river Liris.

title: Panapio/Punicum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 A1 Panapio/Punicum

title: Pandataria (island)
description: An island in the Pontine archipelago of the Tyrrhenian Sea, Pandataria is volcanic in origin and is best known, in historical terms, as the place to which Augustus banished Julia the Elder, his daughter, in 2 BC and to which Tiberius banished Agrippina the Elder in AD 29.

title: Panetelle
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Panetelle

title: Parthenope/Neapolis
description: Founded as Parthenope by Greeks in the eighth century B.C., the site eventually gave rise to Neapolis in the sixth century B.C. and was one of the most prominent cities of Magna Graecia.

title: Pentri
description: The Pentri were a major tribe of Oscan-speaking Samnites; their chief center was Bovianum Undecumanorum.

title: Pescolanciano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F2 Pescolanciano

title: Pian di Sorrento
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Pian di Sorrento

title: Piano della Civitella
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E1 Piano della Civitella

title: Picentinus Ager
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Picentinus Ager

title: Samnite Sanctuary at Pietrabbondante
description: An ancient sanctuary on the slope of Monte Saraceno in the modern Italian comune of Pietrabbondante.

title: Pithekoussai
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E4 Pithekoussai

title: Pitonia?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D2 Pitonia?

title: Pompeia Palus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Pompeia Palus

title: Pompeii
description: An ancient city of Campania destroyed by the volcanic eruption of Mt. Vesuvius in A.D. 79, Pompeii was named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1997.

title: Pomptinae Paludes
description: The Pomptinae Paludes (Pontine Marshes) is an area of former marshland in Latium.

title: Pomptinus Ager
description: Pomptinus Ager (Pomptine plain) is a region in Latium lying between Albanus M. and the Tyrrhenian coast.

title: Pons Apollinis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 A1 Pons Apollinis

title: Pons Campanus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Pons Campanus

title: Pons Auruncus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Pons Auruncus

title: Pons Tirenus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Pons Tirenus

title: Pontia
description: A settlement on Pontia Ins. The largest of the Pontine Islands, Pontia lies 33 km south of Cape Circeo on the Italian mainland.

title: Pontiae (islands)
description: An archipelago in the Tyrrhenian Sea off the west coast of Italy.

title: Porticone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G2 Porticone

title: Porto
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Porto

title: Roman villa at Positano
description: An opulent Roman villa maritima destroyed by the A.D. 79 eruption of Vesuvius. The remains of an opulent and well-decorated Roman villa have been known at Positano since at least 1758 when ruins were discovered during work on the bell tower of the church of S. Maria Assunta. Karl Weber conducted excavations there in the same year. Modern work, begun in 1999, has stabilized and consolidated the site.

title: Privernum
description: A Volscian center that Rome reportedly destroyed in the late fourth century B.C.

title: Prochyta (island)
description: Procida is one of the Flegrean Islands located between Cape Miseno and the island of Ischia.

title: Punta Chiarito
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E4 Punta Chiarito

title: Punta Eolo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D4 Punta Eolo

title: Puteolanus Sinus/Crater
description: Also called the Bay of Naples, the Puteolanus Sinus is a gulf located on the southwestern coast of Italy. It opens west to the Mediterranean Sea and is bordered on the east by Mt. Vesuvius and the south by the Sorrentine Peninsula.

title: Pyrgi
description: Pyrgi is an ancient Etruscan port city on the Tyrrhenian coast of Italy. A Roman colony was established at the site by 191 B.C. In 1964 the bi-lingual 'Pyrgi Plaques' were discovered during the course of excavations.

title: Regio Statana?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Regio Statana?

title: Roccaspromonte
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G2 Roccaspromonte

title: Rufrae
description: A Samnite settlement at the margins of Campania.

title: Saepinum
description: An ancient town of Samnium captured by the Romans in 293 B.C., located on the road between Beneventum and Corfinium.

title: Salernum
description: A city of Campania with Osco-Etruscan origins that became a Roman colony in 197 B.C.

title: Salinae Herculeae
description: An ancient people, tribe, or cultural group.

title: Saltus Vescinus/Mefineis? M.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Saltus Vescinus/Mefineis? M.

title: Samnium (region)
description: Samnium is the Latin name for a region of south and central Italy inhabited by the Samnites. The geographic limits of this region prior to sustained Roman contact are poorly defined. With the Augustan reorganization of Italy, the pre-Roman Samnium is subdivided among three of the Augustan regions.

title: S. Angelo d’Ogliara
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 S. Angelo d’Ogliara

title: S. Apollinare
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 S. Apollinare

title: S. Benedictus
description: A monastery originally established by St. Benedict of Nursia in A.D. 529/530.

title: S. Buono
description: A fortified town near Chieti in the Abruzzo, the ancient phases of S. Buono include evidence for an indigenous sacred site of the later first millennium BC. Among the finds are votive objects dedicated to Herakles.

title: S. Cornelia, Mon.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 B1 S. Cornelia, Mon.

title: S. Giacomo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G2 S. Giacomo

title: S. Giovanni in Galdo
description: Site of a small Samnitic sanctuary atop Colle Rimontato (709 m. a.s.l.)

title: S. Giovanni Lippioni
description: S. Giovanni Lippioni is the site of a pre-Roman sanctuary that was later repurposed as a Christian church.

title: S. Martinus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 S. Martinus

title: S. Marzano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 S. Marzano

title: S. Rocco
description: The San Rocco villa was built during the second quarter of the first century B.C. It was initially a simple villa rustica and it was later enlarged substantially.

title: S. Sebastianus
description: San Sebastiano in the territory of Alatri originates in the late fifth century.

title: S. Valentino Torio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 S. Valentino Torio

title: S. Vincenzo al Volturno
description: S. Vincenzo al Volturno is a multi-period settlement. In pre-Roman times a phase of Samnite occupation has been identified. By the fifth century A.D. the site was occupied by a large agricultural estate (villa) that was abandoned in the later fifth century, only to be replaced by a Christian church.

title: S. Vittore
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 S. Vittore

title: Sarno
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Sarno

title: Sarnus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Sarnus fl.

title: Sarnus (mountain)
description: A mountain mentioned in ancient sources.

title: Sarrastes
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Sarrastes

title: Saticula
description: Saticula was a Samnite site in Campania that received a Latin colony in 313 B.C.

title: Sava di Baronissi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Sava di Baronissi

title: Savo (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Savo fl.

title: Scanno
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Scanno

title: Scatebra (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Scatebra fl.

title: Scauri
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Scauri

title: Schiavi
description: Twin Italic temples located atop the Colle della Torre.

title: Sebethus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Sebethus fl.

title: Sidicini
description: The Sidicini were a people of ancient Italy; their territory bordered that of the Campani and the Samnites.

title: Simbruini (mountain)
description: A mountain mentioned in ancient sources.

title: Sinonia (island)
description: A small island that is part of the Pontine Islands.

title: Sinues(s)a/Sinope
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Sinues(s)a/Sinope

title: Sirenae, T.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Sirenae, T.

title: Sirenes/Seirenoussai Inss.
description: Sirenes/Seirenoussai Inss. (modern Le Sirenuse or Li Galli) is an archipelago off the Amalfi Coast of Italy. In Greek mythology, the islands were home to the Sirens who tempted sailors, including Odysseus.

title: Sirpium?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 Sirpium?

title: Sora
description: An ancient city of Latium located in the valley of the Liris river that likely had Volscian origins. The Romans captured the city in 345 BC and later established a colony there in 303 BC after the Second Samnite War.

title: Speluncae
description: An ancient grotto, associated with the nearby Villa Tiberii, at the modern Italian town of Sperlonga.

title: Stabiae
description: An Oscan and Roman settlement located on the bay of Naples.

title: Striano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G4 Striano

title: Suessa Aurunca
description: The ancient center of the Aurunci, Suessa Aurunca was abandoned in 337 B.C. for a more favorable site (modern Sessa) where a Latin colony was established in 313 B.C.

title: Suessula
description: Suessula was an important ancient city of Campania.

title: Sulmo
description: A chief settlement of the Peligni that was ravaged by the Carthaginians during the Second Punic War.

title: Super *Tamari Fluvium
description: Super *Tamari Fluvium is the name of a station (statio) mentioned by the Antonine Itinerary.

title: *Supinum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 *Supinum

title: Surrentum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Surrentum

title: Taburnus M.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 Taburnus M.

title: Tarracina(e)/Anxur
description: A strategic Volscian city that had come under Roman control by 509 B.C.; a Roman citizen colony was established there in 329 B.C. The site is particularly notable for the remains of the terraced sanctuary of Iuppiter Anxur.

title: Taurasinus? Ager
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 Taurasinus? Ager

title: Teanum Sidicinum
description: Teanum Sidicinum (modern Teano) was the capital of the Oscan-speaking Sidicini tribe. The city likely submitted to Rome after 334 B.C.

title: Telesia
description: An ancient Samnite city located in the valley of the Calor river.

title: Terravecchia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G3 Terravecchia

title: Terventum
description: Terventum was the site of a Roman municipium established in the territory of the Pentrian Samnites.

title: Terzigno
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F4 Terzigno

title: Tifata (mountain)
description: A mountainous region of central Italy known to be densely wooded with oak trees.

title: Tifernus (river)
description: The Tifernus (modern Biferno) is a river of Molise that flows from near Bojano to the Adriatic Sea.

title: Tifernus M.
description: Tifernus M. (Monti Matese), a mountain chain that straddles Campania and Molise in the central-southern Apennines.

title: Torre S. Limato
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Torre S. Limato

title: Treba
description: Treba (modern Trevi nel Lazio) was originally a settlement of the Aequi.

title: ‘Trebula’
description: A pre-Roman site in the valley of the Sangro river that was later converted to a Christian church.

title: Trebula Balli(ni)ensium
description: An ancient city of Campania that became enfranchised in the Roman system in the late fourth century B.C.

title: Treppete
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E3 Treppete

title: Trinius (river)
description: The Trigno river in Molise.

title: Ufens (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 D3 Ufens fl.

title: Urbana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 F3 Urbana

title: Uscosium?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 G2 Uscosium?

title: Val Fondillo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Val Fondillo

title: The Sanctuary of Vastogirardi
description: A sanctuary of the Pentrian Samnites on the flanks of Monte Capraro, north of the modern Italian village of Vastogirardi.

title: Venafrum
description: Venafrum was an ancient town of Campania.

title: Verulae
description: Verulae is an ancient city that became a Roman municipium in 90 B.C.

title: Vesuvius M.
description: A stratovolcano located in the Gulf of Naples, Vesuvius stands to an elevation of 1,281 m (4,203 ft). It is notable in historical terms for its eruption of AD 79 in which numerous settlements, including Pompeii and Herculaneum, were destroyed.

title: Vicalvi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 44 E2 Vicalvi

title: Vicus (...)staniensis

title: Roccadaspide

description: Rossano di Vaglio, a fourth century BC site dedicated to Mefitis, was a Lucanian federal sanctuary.

title: Rubi
description: Rubi was a statio in Apulia, located along the Via Minucia.

title: ‘Rudas’/‘Budas’

description: An ancient Messapic town, Rudiae was the birthplace of the poet Ennius.

title: Sal(a)pia(i)/Elpia

title: Sal(a)pia(i)/Salinae
description: Sal(a)pia(i)/Salinae was an ancient city of Daunia.

title: Salapina Palus
description: An ancient coastal lagoon on the coast of Apulia, drained in modern times.

title: Sallentini
description: Sallentini were a tribe of an ancient Apulia, the 'heel' of the booth of the Italian peninsula. They spoke the Messapian language.

title: Sallentinum/Iapygia
description: Cape Leuca, known as Sallentinum and Iapygia in ancient sources, is a headland that forms the extreme southeastern point of Italy and separates the Gulf of Tarentum from the Adriatic Sea.

title: Saltus Carminianensis?
description: The Saltus Carminianensis? is a large imperial property of northern Apulia mentioned in the Notitia Dignitatum Occidentis.

title: Aristanis
description: A Byzantine site in western Sardinia, made important by the location of a bishopric there by Torcotorio in AD 1070; now the modern city of Oristano.

title: Nuraghe Santu Antine
description: A nuragic structure dating originally ca. 1,600 to 1,450 BC.

title: Çayönü
description: Çayönü was a Neolithic settlement located in southern Turkey. Its remains date ca. 7200 to 6600 BC. The site spans the entire Pre-pottery Neolithic sequence and recent investigations suggest that Çayönü may be the site of the first domestication of the pig (Sus scrofa).

title: Mortuary Temple of Senwosret III
description: Mortuary temple constructed for Senwosret III, a pharaoh of the 12th Dynasty in Egypt.

title: Via Herdonitana
description: A Roman road connecting Herdonia and Ausculum.

title: Via Aurelia Aeclanensis?
description: A road in Apulia leading from Aeclanum toward Vibinum. The Via Aurelia Aeclanensis? intersects the Via Herculia.

title: Via Tiberina
description: An ancient Roman road.

title: Villa di Monte delle Colonnacce
description: A Roman villa located near Castel di Guido.

title: Tomb of Priscilla
description: A Roman tomb along the Via Appia that belonged to one Priscilla, wife of Titus Flavius Abascanto, a freedman of the emperor Domitian.

title: Acemhöyük
description: The settlement mound of Acemhöyük is perhaps the location of the ancient Hittite center of Purushanda.

title: Maen Castle
description: Maen Castle is an Iron Age promontory fort near Land's End in Cornwall.

title: Maiden Castle, Cheshire
description: Maiden Castle, Cheshire, is an Iron Age hillfort.

title: Villa of the Papyri
description: A suburban villa located northwest of Herculaneum that was originally owned by Lucius Calpurnius Piso Caesoninus.

title: Villa of the Mysteries
description: A Roman villa located northwest of Pompeii.

title: Gallo-Roman Structure at Moissac
description: A Gallo-Roman structure including hypocaust and other remains of a bath, located beneath the later Church of Saint Martin in modern Moissac, France. The bath may have belonged to a villa of the fourth-fifth centuries CE.

title: Unnamed Roman bridgehead
description: Ancient bridgehead west of Milecastle 27 (Hadrian's Wall), providing link to Cilurnum.

title: Sanctuary of Fortuna Primigenia
description: The Sanctuary of Fortuna Primigenia at Praeneste is a terraced sanctuary of monumental proportions. The phase visible today dates to the late second century B.C.

title: Second Temple, Jerusalem
description: The so-called "Second Temple" in Jerusalem stood on the northern edge of the Dome of the Rock and was destroyed in A.D. 70 during the Roman siege.

title: Great Mosque of the Umayyads
description: The Great Mosque of the Umayyads is located in the old city of Damascus and is one of the largest and oldest mosques in the world. It was completed in 715.

title: Roman Theatre of Orange
description: The Roman Theatre of Orange was built early in the first century A.D.

title: Theater at Xanthos
description: The Greek theater (second century BC) was renovated following a Roman design following the earthquake of A.D. 141.

title: Tyre Hippodrome
description: The Tyre Hippodrome dates to the second century.

title: Ancient Stadium of Rhodes
description: The Hellenistic Stadium on the Acropolis of Rhodes.

title: Temple of Apollo Pythios
description: The Hellenistic Temple of Apollo Pythios on the Acropolis of the city of Rhodes.

title: Temple of Zeus at Olympia
description: The Temple of Zeus at Olympia was built in the second quarter of the fifth century B.C. Libon of Elis served as architect.

title: Roman Temple of Évora
description: The Roman Temple of Évora, also referred to as the Temple of Diana, is a Roman temple of the first century A.D.

title: Roman theater at Brixia
description: The Roman theater at Brixia was built during the Flavian period.

title: San Salvatore monastery
description: A monastery founded in A.D. 753 by Desiderius, future king of the Lombards. Located in modern Brescia, Italy.

title: Tomb of Cyrus the Great
description: The Tomb of Cyrus the Great is located about 1 km southwest of the palaces at Pasargadae. It is typically dated to ca. to 559-529 B.C.

title: Gastaldaga area and the Episcopal complex
description: A Longobard complex in Cividale del Friuli.

title: Byzantine arcosolia
description: Byzantine tombs at the site belong to the sixth century when the Temple of Concordia was converted into a Christian church.

title: Lower Agora
description: The lower agora of the ancient city of Agrigentum contains shops, a sacred area, and the gymnasium complex.

title: Casmonates
description: An ancient people of Liguria.

title: Catacombs of Generosa
description: A Paleochristian catacomb located at the sixth mile of the via Portuense.

title: Nuraghe Losa
description: A nuraghe near Abbasanta, Sardinia. The original phase of the site dates to the fifteenth through thirteenth centuries B.C., while the enclosure wall dates to the thirteenth and twelfth centuries B.C. The site saw diminished activity in the Iron Age; the eighth and seventh centuries B.C. show evidence for funerary activity.

title: Gird-i Bazar
description: Archaeological site in the Peshdar Plain with remains dated to the Neo-Assyrian period. The site is part of a larger frontier settlement known as the Dinka Settlement Complex.

title: Puentecillas
description: A bridge of the sixteenth century that rests on Roman foundations.

title: Shrine of Venus Cloacina
description: The Sacrum Cloacina was a small shrine dedicated to Venus Cloacina, patron divinity of the sewer, and was located near the Tabernae novae in the Forum Romanum. The foundation of the sacellum is extant while images of its likely elevation are found on Roman coins.

title: Torre del Campo
description: A Spanish village located in the west of the province of Jaén that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today it is known as Torredelcampo.

title: Villar de don Pardo
description: A Spanish village located in the west of Jaén, near Torredelcampo, that once belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today it is known as Villardompardo.

title: Baena
description: A Spanish village located in the southeast of the province of Córdoba that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Albendin
description: Albendin, in the district of Baena, is located near Córdoba. It once belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X and is today known as Albendín.

title: Burgos
description: A Spanish city located in the north of Spain that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: tribus Voltinia
description: The tribus Voltinia (or Votinia) was an older rural tribe of ancient Rome.

title: Sardurihinili
description: An Urartian fortress constructed in the eighth century BCE and destroyed in the seventh century BCE.

title: Yiftahel
description: An archaeological site of the Lower Galilee in northern Israel, Yiftahel has evidence for occupation beginning in the Pre-Pottery Neolithic B. By the early Bronze Age the settlement consisted of approximately 20 oval structures. Excavations took place here between 1992 and 2008.

title: Skinburness
description: Milefortlet 9, Skinburness

title: Casiana
description: A fortress (phrourion) and settlement near Apamea on the Orontes river. The precise location is unknown today.

title: Porta Maggiore
description: The Porta Maggiore is the ancient Porta Praenestina, an early Imperial gate preserved in the later third century walls built by Aurelian.

title: The Great Pyramid
description: The Great Pyramid of Khufu was built ca. 2580–2560 B.C. during the 4th dynasty of ancient Egypt. It initially stood to a height of 146.5 meters (481 feet).

title: Walls
description: Approximate linear extent of the ancient city walls

title: Sebasteion
description: The Sebasteion at Aphrodisias was a temple complex dedicated to Aphrodite and the Iulio-Claudian emperors that was financed by local patrons. It was built between ca. AD 20 and 60. The complex was excavated in 1979-81.

title: Akkad
description: Akkad (Māt-Akkadî) is the name of a historical region of central Mesopotamia (northern Babylonia). During the Sargonic/Akkadian Period (ca. 2334-2113 B.C.), its capital was the city of Agade, which may have been located somewhere near the confluence of the Diyala and Tigris Rivers. In cuneiform texts of the first millennium B.C., the term Māt-Akkadî was used for the name of the region roughly comprising the northern half of Babylonia, now modern-day central Iraq.

title: Hatti (region)
description: In Assyrian and Babylonian texts of the first millennium BC, Hatti is a purely geographical term referring to North Syria, the area roughly covered by Syro-Hittite states west of the Euphrates River.

title: Ummān-manda
description: Akkadian Umman-manda, meaning “barbarian horde (lit. “army/troops of Manda”), is used in cuneiform texts composed during the first and second millennia BC as a stock of ethnographic term and as a word denoting Medes (or Cimmerians).

title: Fortified Port Settlement on Cape St. Athanasius
description: An ancient settlement with fortifications and port facilities located on the modern Cape St. Athanasius near Byala in Bulgaria.

title: Roman wall, Gijon
description: A Roman fortification wall that dates initially to the third or fourth century.

title: Khirbat Iskandar
description: A fortified site on the banks of the Wadi al-Wala in Jordan inhabited in the Early Bronze IV period.

title: Cadira del Bisbe
description: A terraced pre-Roman settlement located in Premià de Dalt. The site flourished between the fifth and third centuries B.C. and was abandoned by the first century B.C

title: Nuraghe Toscono
description: A single tower nuraghe standing ca. 7.25 meters.

title: Baqa
description: An unlocated city/town in the kingdom of Suhu, probably not far from Alu-eššu, Qaqqar-aradātu, and Ribaniš.

title: Raṣappa
description: A land (and later an Assyrian province) mentioned in first-millennium B.C. Akkadian texts from Assyria and Suhu. Scholars generally believe that this land/province is located east of the Habur River, south of Jebel Singar, and northeast of the land Bit-Halupê.

title: Nuraghe Porcarzos
description: A complex nuraghe surrounded by a quadrilobate bastion.

title: Gallabu
description: An unlocated well presumably in the middle Euphrates region, in or near the kingdom of Suhu.

title: Bukrê
description: An unlocated well presumably in the middle Euphrates region, in or near the kingdom of Suhu.

title: Hazī
description: A town presumably located in or near the kingdom of Suhu, in the middle Euphrates region.

title: Tu'manu
description: An Aramean tribe living in the middle Euphrates region and in Babylonia, and possibly the same group as the Tu'muna tribe, who are mentioned in Assyrian texts of the 8th and 7th centuries B.C.

title: Aramu
description: A general designation for Arameans in Akkadian texts.

title: Atabuli
description: A tribe of ancient Ethiopia mentioned by Pliny the Elder as occupying lands beyond Egypt. Their territory likely lies between Napata and Meroë.

title: Santa Maria dell'Orto
description: The church of Santa Maria dell'Orto is a Roman Catholic church located in Rome's Trastevere district. Its foundation is traced to 508.

title: Esagila
description: The temple of the god Marduk at Babylon. The Sumerian ceremonial name Esagil(a) means "House, Whose Top is High."

title: Murgaual (castle)
description: A Spanish castle and village located in the north of the province of Córdoba that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Today it's known as Castillo de Murgabal or Castillo de Almogábar. It is part of the village of Torrecampo and the region of Fuencaliente.

title: Guadarmes (river)
description: Today is known as the Guadalmez, the Guadarmes is a river located in the south of the province of Ciudad Real, Spain.

title: Agudo
description: A Spanish village located in the west of the province of Ciudad Real that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Dos Barrios
description: A Spanish village located in the east of the province of Toledo that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Dosbarrios.

title: Lucena
description: A Spanish village located in the south of the province of Córdoba that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Matrera castle
description: Castillo de Matrera is a Spanish castle that originally dates to the ninth century and is located in the northeast of the province of Cádiz. It belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X (in the thirteenth century). Today it is located in the municipality of Villamartín.

title: Panjakent
description: The easternmost city of Sogdiana, inhabited from the fifth-ninth centuries CE.

title: Bukhara
description: Bukhara began as part of the Persian empire in the sixth century B.C. The site is especially important as an example of an Islamic city of central Asia. The city center was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1993.

title: Ishkhani (monastery)
description: A church and monastery in Tao-Klarjeti, first constructed in the 7th century.

title: Kars
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Toprak Kala
description: The site of a walled Chorasmian city, inhabited from the first to sixth centuries CE, located approximately 40 kilometers north of the Afrighid capital city of Kath.

title: Tell el-'Oueili
description: Tell el-'Oueili is an archaeological site located in the Dhi Qar Governorate of southern Iraq. Occupation at the site predates the occupation levels of Eridu, making Tell el-'Oueili one of the earliest known human settlements of southern Mesopotamia.

title: Archaeological Sites of Bat, Al-Khutm and Al-Ayn
description: Located in modern Oman, the protohistoric site of Bat and its neighbouring sites forms the most complete collection of settlements and necropoleis from the third millennium BC in the world.

title: Sarissa
description: Sarissa was a Hititite site of the second millennium BC. Its remains are located at Kuşaklı, Turkey. Excavations have recovered a substantial archive of Hittite texts.

title: Podere Pievina
description: A farm site with a least two occupation phases - one dating between the second century BC and early first century AD and the second between the fourth and fifth centuries AD.

title: Pauli Stincus
description: A Punic farm site occupied from the fourth to the second century B.C.

title: Aeolis
description: Sometimes defined as covering the entrance of the Hellespont to the mouth of the Hermus river, Aeolis was region centered on the North West coast of Asia Minor and some islands, notably Lesbos. Herodotus lists the eleven ancient cities of Aeolis as Cyme, Lerisae, Neon Teichos, Temnos, Cilla, Notion, Aegiroessa, Pitane, Aegaeae, Myrina, and Gryneia. He also claims that Smyrna was once an Aeolian city, but was taken by the Ionians at an unspecified date.

title: Crypta Balbi
description: The Crypta Balbi, mentioned by name only in the Regionary Catalogues, most likely refers to a vaulted passageway built in the Campus Martius by the proconsul Lucius Cornelius Balbus in 15 BC, who also dedicated a theater there in the same year.

title: Ianus Quadrifons
description: A quadrifrons triumphal arch at Rome that is located at a crossroads in the area of the Velabrum and the Forum Boarium. It dates to the early fourth century AD; its construction employed spolia and it likely honored either Constantine I or Constantius II.

title: Roman theater of Aspendos
description: The Roman theater at Aspendos dates ca. AD 155 and is perhaps the best preserved example of a Roman theater building.

title: Castell Henllys
description: Castell Henllys is an Iron Age hill fort located in north Pembrokeshire, Wales.

title: Hippodrome of Constantinople
description: The Hippodrome was the great racetrack of the city of Constantinople and was connected to the no longer extant imperial palace. At about 450 m in length, the Hippodrome once accommodated about 100,000 spectators.

title: Caerau Hillfort
description: Caerau Hillfort is a multivallate Iron Age in the western suburbs of Cardiff, Wales. The fort covers an area of ca. 51,000 m².

title: Agios Elias Doric temple
description: The Doric temple at Agios Elias, above Asea in Arcadia, dates to ca. 500 B.C.

title: Torre Astura
description: A Medieval coastal fort of the Frangipani.

title: Olevano Romano
description: Remains of polygonal masonry fortification are extant at Olevano Romano in Italy, which is presumed to be the site of a fortified oppidum of the Aequi.

title: Göd-Bócsaújtelep
description: Göd-Bócsaújtelep is an unfinished late Roman fort from the reign of Valentinian along the Limes Sarmatiae.

title: Barcombe Hill Roman Quarry
description: Two quarry faces to the southwest of the summit of Barcombe Hill, near Vindolanda. Findspot of RIB 3373.

title: Coombe Crag Roman Quarry
description: Evidence of Roman quarrying activity was discovered at Coombe Crag, a site some 350 meters south of the line of Hadrian's Wall. The quarry was used as a source of building materials for the Wall and at least eight inscriptions were identified on the sandstone cliff.

title: Queen's Crags Roman Quarry
description: A Roman quarry site and the find spot of RIB 3331.

title: Arco Etrusco
description: The so-called "Arco Etrusco" is one of the gates of ancient Perusia. The gate dates originally from the third century B.C. when it was one of seven gates in the Etruscan wall. In 40 B.C. it was refashioned under Augustus.

title: Porta Eburnea
description: The so-called Porta Eburnea or the Arco della Mandorla is an ancient gate of the Etruscan walls of Perusia.

title: Worthy Down
description: A Middle Iron Age-3rd/4th century A.D. settlement complex at Worthy Down, lying 8 km. NNW of Winchester.

title: Shadwell Roman Bathhouse
description: A second to fourth century A.D. Romano-British bathhouse that was excavated in 2002. Findspot of RIB 3012.

title: Ekagula
description: The dais of the Anunnakū gods, Ekagula (“House, Big Gate”), was located in the TE.E (read as either Tê or Kisīri) district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of two daises in that part of Babylon.

title: Eandasaya
description: The temple of the goddess Ištar of the Star, Eandasaya (“House Which Rivals Heaven”), was located in the New City district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of two temples in that part of Babylon.

title: Ekitušgirzal
description: The temple of the goddess Bēlet-Eanna, Ekitušgirzal (“House, Abode of Joy”), was located in the New City district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of two temples in that part of Babylon.

title: Esag
description: The temple of the god Lugalbanda, Esag (“Foremost House”), was located in the Kullab district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of four temples in that part of Babylon.

title: Eʾešmah
description: The temple of the god Ea, Eʾešmah (“Exalted House”), was located in the Kumar district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of seven temples in that part of Babylon.

title: Enamhe
description: The temple of the god Adad, Enamhe (“House of Plenty”), was located in the Kumar district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of seven temples in that part of Babylon. Enamhe was (re)built by the the Old Babylonian kings Sūmû-lā-El (r. ca. 1881–1845 BC) and Hammu-rāpi (r. ca. 1792–1750 BC) and the Neo-Babylonian ruler Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC).

title: Ness of Brodgar
description: Ness of Brodgar is an archaeological site near Loch of Harray, Orkney. The site covers 2.5 hectares.

title: Standing Stones of Stenness
description: The Standing Stones of Stenness is a Neolithic monument on the mainland of Orkney, Scotland, generally dated to the third millennium BC.

title: Barnhouse Settlement
description: The Barnhouse Settlement is a Neolithic village of approximately 15 houses located adjacent to the Loch of Harray, Orkney Mainland, Scotland.

title: Vapheio Tholos Tomb
description: The Vapheio Tholos Tomb is a Mycenaean tholos built around 1500 BC that is assumed to have held an elite burial or burials. It is best known for the two golden Minoan-style cups it housed.

title: Bollendorf
description: Roman villa rustica in Bollendorf

title: Longuich
description: Roman villa urbana in Longuich

title: Guglia di Marcello
description: The so-called "Guglia di Marcello" or "Aguglia d'Agosta" is a Roman funerary monument located along the ancient via Pompei that once connected Syracuse and Messina. It dates to the period from the first century B.C. to the first century A.D.

title: Roman Theater of Baelo
description: A Roman theater in Baelo that dates to the reign of Claudius.

title: Dūru
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources that is identified with modern Anaz Höyük.

title: Roman amphitheater of Col. Tarraco
description: A Roman amphitheater in Tarragona built in the first century A.D. The structure was renovated under Elagabalus.

title: Maison Carrée
description: A well preserved Roman temple built ca. 16 B.C. and dedicated to Caius and Lucius Caesar.

title: Gingiliniš
description: A town mentioned in an Akkadian inscription of the Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib. This place is generally identified with the modern Tepe Chenchi.

title: Piercebridge Roman Bridge
description: A Roman bridge that carried Dere Street across the River Tees in northern England.

title: Pons Probi
description: The Pons Probi across the Tiber is attested in the Notitia and, according to Platner and Ashby, was likely built under Emperor Probus in the third century AD.

title: Citania de Santa Luzia
description: A fortified protourban site located near the modern city of Viana do Castelo in northern Portugal.

title: Mausoleum of Romulus
description: Tomb of Valerius Romulus (ca. AD 292/295 – 309), son of Maxentius, along the Via Appia.

title: Nuraghe Cuccuru Ibba
description: A pre-nuragic village of the Ozieri culture and later nuraghe located in the Laguna di Santa Gilla.

title: Mortuary Temple of Merenptah
description: Mortuary temple of the Nineteenth Dynasty in the Theban Necropolis.

title: Abbotsbury Abbey
description: Abbotsbury Abbey is a Benedictine abbey located in Dorset, England. It was founded in c.1026 for secular canons, became a monastery of the Benedictine order in 1044, and was dissolved in 1539.

title: Tell Chuera
description: Tell Chuera (also known as Tall Dahr ash Shuwayrah) is a Near Eastern tell in northern Syria occupied from the fourth millennium B.C. onward.

title: Casa Bellezza
description: The so-called "Casa Bellezza" is a Roman domus located on the flank of the Aventine Hill in Rome. Its remains are found at Largo Arrigo VII, no. 2-4.

title: Nuraghe Nuracale
description: A quadrilobate nuragic complex located in the territory of Scano di Montiferro.

title: Bath city walls
description: The circuit walls of Aquae Sulis, enclosing an area of some 23 ha, began in the Roman period and were later reinforced in the Anglo-Saxon and Medieval periods. Various remains are visible at points along the original circuit.

title: Bab adh-Dhra'
description: An early Bronze Age settlement near the Dead Sea inhabited from approximately 3150-2150 BCE.

title: Casa della statuetta indiana
description: The so-called "Casa della statuetta indiana" (I.8.5) lies on the Via dell'Abbondanza. Excavated between 1930 and 1935, it was named for the fine ivory statuette (thought by some to depict Lakshmi) found inside. The house has a slightly irregular floor plan with some rooms added to the structure from adjacent properties.

title: Taberna Pomaria di Felix
description: A fruit shop in Pompeii (I, 8, 1) with an entrance on to the Via dell'Abbondanza.

title: Pistrinum of Betitius Placidus
description: A small shop located in Regio I of Pompeii (I, 8, 7).

title: Aisepos fl.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 56 E2 Aisepos fl.

title: Gorgobina
description: Gorgobina was an ancient Gallic city located near the border of Aquitania, perhaps on the Loire river, although the precise location is no longer certain. Iulius Caesar mentions the site in his commentary on the Gallic War.

title: Saint-Pierre de Vence
description: A Gallo-Roman villa.

title: Castel Vieil, Sainte-Anastasie
description: An important pre-Roman and Gallo-Roman oppidum overlooking the Gardon gorges north of Nimes.

title: Pont de Bornègre
description: A Roman aqueduct bridge connected to the Roman aqueduct of Nîmes.

title: Peyriac-de-Mer
description: A small pre-Roman trading post on the edge of the Bages-Sigean lagoon.

title: Vivios
description: Remains of a Roman villa.

title: Espelt Roman villa
description: A Roman villa that was inhabited from the late first century AD until the fifth century AD.

title: Ezida
description: The temple of the god Marduk as Tutu, later of the god Nabû, at Borsippa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ezida means "True House."

title: Eniggidrukalamasuma
description: The temple of the god Nabû of the ḫarû as at Borsippa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eniggidrukalamasuma means "House which Bestows the Scepter of the Land."

title: Ekišnugal
description: The temple of the moon god Nanna/Suen/Sîn at Ur from the third to first millennium B.C. Over the course of its long history, it was rebuilt (and expanded) numerous times. A few of its more famous builders were Narām-Sîn of Agade, Ur-Nammu of Ur, and Nebuchadnezzar II of Babylon.

title: Eanna
description: The temple of the god Anu and the goddess Ištar at Uruk. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eanna means "House of Heaven."

title: City walls of Sabucina
description: The fortification walls of the Classical city.

title: Roman baths of Coriovallum
description: The site of Coriovallum is known for its well-preserved bath complex. These baths were first built ca. A.D. 40 and then re-built during the reign of Hadrian. They remained in use until the fourth century.

title: Villa del Pastore
description: A large villa at Stabiae covering more than 17,000 square meters.

title: Villa del fondo Ippolito Zurlo
description: A Roman villa located in the contrada Giuliana at Boscoreale on a side street of via Grotta II. The site was excavated by Vincenzo De Prisco in 1897 and subsequently reinterred.

title: Villa of Asellius
description: A Roman villa excavated at Boscoreale in 1903 and 1904 under the supervision of Vincenzo De Prisco and located on the property of one Giuseppe De Martino. Wall paintings and artifacts were recovered from the site and it was subsequently reinterred. Records as to its precise location are less than optimal.

title: Jensberg Celtic oppidum
description: Site of the Celtic wall protecting the oppidum from south-west.

title: Temple complex
description: A Gallo-Roman sanctuary with an enclosed precinct that was linked to the oppidum.

title: Cawdor
description: Site of a Roman fortress near Eastern Galcantray that some consider one of the northernmost Roman forts in Great Britain.

title: Mülheim-Kärlich
description: A Roman villa dating to the second and third centuries A.D.

title: Remstecken
description: Site of a Roman villa rustica, dating from the first to third centuries AD.

title: Haselburg
description: A second century AD Roman villa estate.

title: Dothan
description: An ancient site, connected with the biblical figures Joseph and Jacob.

title: Moab
description: A mountainous strip of land in Jordan that was also the location of the kingdom of Moab, with its capital at Dibon.

title: Spolverino, Alberese
description: An archaeological site of the Roman period connected with the fluvial harbor of Rusellae.

title: Gaulopes
description: A tribe located near the Sinus Capeus, on the west of the Persian gulf.

title: Diyālā
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Denizli
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Bīrǧand
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Tavāna
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: ad-Dauḥa
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Munzur Dağları
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Ḥāʾil
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Dubayy
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Masqaṭ
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Uchkakar
description: Fortified settlement on the banks of the Cheptsa River, inhabited from the 9th-13th centuries CE and associated with the Cheptsa culture

title: Tilmen Höyük
description: A bronze age settlement in the Islahiye valley of modern Turkey where habitation seems to have begun as early as the Late Chalcolithic.

title: Torre del Papito
description: A Medieval tower in Rome's Largo Argentina.

title: Casa dei Crescenzi
description: A structure in Rome built between 1040 and 1065 by one Niccolò, son of Crescenzio and Teodora, in order to control the Ponte Emilio, on whose transit the family charged a toll. The building incorporates ancient spolia.

title: Tumulo di Montecalvario
description: An Etruscan tomb located at Castellina in Chianti in Italy.

title: Chassenon Roman amphitheater
description: Remains of a Roman amphitheater at Chassenon.

title: Caesareum of Alexandria
description: Hellenistic temple constructed by Cleopatra VII and dedicated to Julius Caesar, and later rededicated by Augustus to himself. In 13 BCE Augustus relocated two obelisks from Heliopolis to the site. The temple was converted to a Christian church in the mid-4th century.

title: Alcimoennis
description: An oppidum located on Michelsberg hill in Bavaria, occupied from ca. 500 BC until the first century BC.

title: Portus Cosanus
description: The harbor of the Latin colonial city of Cosa in south Etruria.

title: Villa della Colonne
description: A late Republican and early Imperial villa in the ager Cosanus noted for its turreted enclosure wall.

title: Unnamed group of bridges over R. Zadorra, north of Bele(g)ia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 25 C3 unnamed bridge group (Trespuentes over R. Zadorra, N Bele(g)ia)

title: Ponte Spiano
description: The so-called Ponte Spiano is a Roman bridge located along the Via Flaminia in the modern comune of Sigillo.

title: Ponte Grosso
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

title: Ponte Manlio
description: The Roman bridge known as "Ponte Manlio" carried the Via Flaminia across the Bosso torrent, whose main channel is now some hundreds of meters to the south. This is a well-preserved Roman vaulted arch bridge that dates to the second century B.C.

title: Ponte del Toro
description: A Roman arched bridge on the Via Flaminia near modern Terni.

title: Ponte di Augusto
description: A Roman arched bridge located near Narni built originally in the Augustan period that remained in use until A.D. 1055.

title: Ponte Calamone
description: A Roman bridge near Narnia that was built over the river Nera ca. 27 B.C.

title: Ponte Fonnaia
description: The Roman bridge at Ponte Fonnaia carried a branch of the Via Flaminia over the river Naia. It is located north of modern Acquasparta in Umbria.

title: Ponte di San Giovanni de Butris
description: The remains of a Roman bridge along the Via Flaminia that have been incorporated into the thirteenth-century church of San Giovanni de Butris.
