title: Pollina
description: Modern town in Sicily, near Cefalù, that has been associated with the ancient settlement of Apollonia.

title: Tomb of the Winged Demons
description: The so-called Tomb of the Winged Demons (Sovana, Italy), a third-century BC Etruscan tomb located in the Poggio Felceto necropolis.

title: Roman baths at Gaujac
description: The Roman baths at Gaujac were begun ca. A.D. 20.

title: Roman amphitheater at Albano Laziale
description: The Roman amphitheater at Albano Laziale is generally dated to the mid-third century A.D.

title: Roman cistern
description: A large Roman cistern at Albano Laziale.

title: Lateran Basilica, Palace, and Castra Nova equitum singularium
description: Site of a basilica and palace from early Roman imperial times, as well as an military installation built by Septimius Severus for the Roman imperial cavalry bodyguard. Now the site of the Archbasilica of St. John Lateran (rebuilt in the 16th century): Complesso dei San Giovanni in Laterano (Basilica, Palazzo Apostolico Lateranense, edifici annessi) Holy See; listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1990.

title: Catacomba di San Giovanni
description: Ancient catacombs in the city of Siracusa, built between AD 315 and 360. The main gallery re-purposes parts of an earlier aqueduct.

title: Biblis
description: A spring located in the territory of Miletus.

title: Najafabad
description: Najafabad (Persian: نجف‌آباد‎) is a city in Iran and the capital of Najafabad, Isfahan Province. The discovery of a stele of the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) indicates that the settlement’s ancient name, at least in the eighth century BC, might have been Kišesim.

title: South Palace at Deir el-Ballas
description: Two-story palace near the western bank of the Nile used as an administrative center from the Second Intermediate Period to the early New Kingdom.

title: Dendra
description: Bronze Age cemetery near the Mycenean settlement of Midea.

title: Villa de Los Villares
description: A Roman villa about 200 meters south of the center of the modern village of Santervas del Burgo and about 100 meters south of the left bank of the river Cejos.

title: Forum Traiani
description: Imperial forum constructed at Rome under Trajan between 105-112 CE.

title: Bath-Gymnasium Complex at Sardis
description: Bath/gymnasium complex containing a palaestra and a synagogue that was developed in the 3rd century CE.

title: Tomb of Seuthes III
description: An elaborate tomb located near Kazanlak, Bulgaria. The Tomb of Seuthes III, who was King of the Odrysian Kingdom from ca. 331 to ca. 300 BC, is found in the Valley of the Thracian Rulers.

title: Sanctuary of Artemis Limnatis at Messene
description: A sanctuary on the slopes of Mount Ithome and within the city walls of ancient Messene in the Peloponnese. It was developed beginning in the 4th-3rd centuries BCE.

title: S. Pietro ad centum muros
description: On the hill of Grignano, located on the outskirts of Montebuono, the remains of a Roman villa were first excavated in the nineteenth century in the area of the church of "S. Pietro ad centum muros". Excavation in the 1990s revealed further villa remains beneath the church and in the vicinity of its cemetery. Epigraphic evidence attesting to the consulship of M. Vipsanius Agrippa was discovered immured in the church (CIL 9.4677 and 9.4779).

title: Dilmun Burial Mounds
description: The Dilmun Burial Mounds, a cultural landscape inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage site in July 2019. This landscape includes tombs dispersed in at least 21 archaeological sites in western Bahrain. These tombs date between 2050 and 1750 B.C. In all there are more than 11,774 burial mounds.

title: Madinat Hamad 2 Burial Mound Field (Karzakkan)
description: A necropolis of the early Dilmun culture, dating to the second millennium B.C.

title: San Nicola di Trullas
description: A Medieval church on the island of Sardinia that is dated to 1133.

title: Turkdean
description: Site of a major Roman villa complex in Gloucestershire, active from late second century CE until the end of the fourth century.

title: Avenches Roman amphitheater
description: The Avenches Roman amphitheater.

title: Mogil'nik Maĭtan
description: Bronze Age burial ground in east-central Kazakhstan.

title: Porta Pretoria (Albano Laziale)
description: The principal gateway of Castra Albana.

title: Mochlos (island)
description: Mochlos is an island in the Gulf of Mirabello, although in antiquity it was likely connected to the Cretan mainland. The island is the site of an ancient Minoan settlement.

title: Agora of Halaesa
description: The agora of the ancient city of Halaesa (second century B.C.), now within the archaeological area of Alesa Arconidea, Sicily.

title: Faroe Islands
description: An archipelago made up of 18 islands situated between the Norwegian Sea and the North Atlantic Ocean.

title: Chibanes
description: A fortified site in use from the third millennium BC to the Roman period.

title: Rio Maior
description: A Roman villa.

title: Nuraghe Sa Bosa
description: The remains of a nuraghe near an industrial zone near Sassari.

title: Solenyĭ Dol
description: Burial complex in the southern Ural Mountains region containing a number of Late Antique burials.

title: Theater at Stymphalos
description: The remains of a rock-cut theater at Stymphalos.

title: Villa di Loron, Cervar
description: A site in Istria that served as a major source of olive oil in the 1st-4th centuries CE. The site is associated with the production of Dressel 6B amphorae.

title: Royal Tombs of Vergina
description: The Macedonian royal necropolis at Vergina.

title: Kavuncu
description: Kavuncu is a modern settlement situated near Van in the southeast of Turkey. Here a cylindrical stone (probably a column base) with an inscription of the Urartian king Minua, son of Išpuini (9/8th century BCE) was found (CTU I A 5-53 B).

title: Pagus Augustus Felix Suburbanus
description: The ancient Pagus Augustus Felix Suburbanus corresponds to the territory of today's city of Boscoreale and Boscotrecase. Originating around 80 B.C. with the name of Pagus Felix Suburbanus, it included many farms.

title: Tel Michal
description: A site on the Mediterranean coast of Israel with signs of habitation from the Middle Bronze Age and the Persian through the Roman periods. In the Hellenistic and Roman periods, its purpose was primarily military, and a series of forts occupied the site until around 50 CE. A small watchtower or lighthouse was built on the site in the eighth-ninth centuries CE, after which it was abandoned.

title: Theater of Ephesus
description: The Theater of Ephesus sits at the foot of the Panayir mountains. It could host up to 25,000 spectators.

title: New Nisa
description: The tell site of New Nisa is part of the Parthian fortress of Nisa, designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

title: Old Nisa
description: The tell of Old Nisa is part of the Parthian fortress of Nisa, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

title: Ašnakkum
description: Town in the Khabur River basin in Northern Syria, now known as Chagar Bazar. First settled in the Neolithic Period, the town appears to have been abandoned during the Early Bronze Age. It was resettled in the Early Dynastic period, becoming an administrative center of the Old Assyrian Empire.

title: Theater at Alinda/Alexandria ad Latmum
description: The Roman Theater at Alinda could accommodate about 5,000 spectators.

title: Yazılıkaya
description: A sacred rock-cut sanctuary of the Hittites. The sanctuary was in use from the late sixteenth century B.C. Many of the reliefs date reigns of Tudhaliya IV and Suppiluliuma II in the late thirteenth century B.C.

title: Heroön
description: The so-called Heroön at Sagalassos dominates the Upper Agora in the northwest sector of the city.

title: Palace of the Shirvanshahs
description: A fifteenth-century palace built by the Shirvanshahs in Baku, Azerbaijan.

title: Giant's tomb at Lu Brandali
description: A passage grave associated with the nuragic complex at Lu Brandali near Santa Teresa Gallura.

title: Newport Arch city gate
description: The remains of a third century A.D. city gate.

title: Multangular Tower
description: The Multangular Tower at York once stood at the west corner of the Roman legionary fortress.

title: Roman forum of Col. Clunia (Sulpicia)
description: The Roman forum of Col. Clunia (Sulpicia) dates to the Imperial period. It is equipped with a rectangular basilica and a small tribunal in addition to shops. The paved decumanus enters the square through a gate.

title: Bolʹshoĭ Salbykskiĭ kurgan
description: The Great Salbyk Mound is the largest burial mound in the Khakassia region of Russia. The mastaba-like tomb, associated with the Bronze Age Tagar culture, was constructed in the 7th century BCE, and may have had an astronomical function.

title: San Roque Theatre - Carteia
description: The Roman theater of Carteia.

title: "Western Theater" at Laodicea ad Lycum
description: Digitized by eye in Google Earth on 13 July 2012 at an eye altitude of 683m. Dates are general settlement dates, following Foss and Mitchell in BAtlas.

title: Roman theater of Stobi
description: The Roman theater of Stobi dates to the second century.

title: Arch of the Sergii
description: A Roman triumphal arch at Pula commemorating Lucius Sergius Lepidus and the family of the Sergii for service at the Battle of Actium in 31 BC.

title: Malo rimsko kazalište (Roman theater)
description: The Roman theater in Pula dates to the first century.

title: Temple of Artemis Orthia
description: An Archaic temple dedicated to Artemis Orthia within the sanctuary of this goddess at Sparta. The site contained rich deposits of votives and masks.

title: Underground Shrine (Paestum)
description: A small, underground tomb-like structure located in the agora of Paestum, thought to be either a shrine or a heroon.

title: Porta Marina tower of Poseidonia/Paestum
description: The so-called Porta Marina of Paestum is a gate in the Hellenistic fortifications and is located along a main street axis leading to the port of the city.

title: Waḫšušana
description: A place from the TAVO Index

description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Zabatos
description: A place from the TAVO Index

description: A place from the TAVO Index

description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Sialk
description: Important settlement in central Iran inhabited from about 6000-550 BCE.

title: Tall Abū Ṣalābīḫ
description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Sanctuary of the Public Lares
description: A sanctuary located on the east side of Pompeii's forum (VII, 9, 3), the Sanctuary of the Public Lares was likely built after AD 62. The sanctuary measures ca. 18 x 21 m and centers on an open central courtyard.

title: Mensa Ponderaria
description: The Mensa ponderaria (VII,7,31) was an official public office adjacent to the forum of Pompeii wherein weights and measures were regulated. This location was in use from the late second century BC.

title: Hadda
description: Haḍḍa, a Greco-Buddhist archeological site, is located in the ancient region of Gandhara, near the Khyber Pass, some ten kilometers south of the city of Jalalabad. This major archaeological site from which archaeologists recovered over 23,000 Greco-Buddhist sculptures in the twentieth century is thought to have been destroyed by ongoing military conflict in Afghanistan.

title: Temple of Khonsu at Karnak
description: New Kingdom temple to the god Khonsu, constructed by Ramesses III and expanded by Ptolemy III Euergetes.

title: Absheron (peninsula)
description: A peninsula in the South Caucasus, extending approximately 60 km into the Caspian Sea.

title: Mausoleum of Lucius Munatius Plancus
description: A Roman mausoleum that is associated with Lucius Munatius Plancus.

title: Roman amphitheater at Grumentum
description: Grumentum's amphitheater (first century B.C.) is the only known example in Lucania. The arena measures ca. 62.5 by 60 meters.

title: Roman amphitheater at Frusino
description: The Roman amphitheater at Frusino measures ca. 78 by 57 meters.

title: Roman amphitheater at Al(l)ifae
description: Remains of a Roman amphitheater dating to the later first century A.D.

title: Roman amphitheater at Telesia
description: A Late Republican Roman amphitheater at Telesia.

title: Temple D
description: The temple referred to as "Temple D" in the Largo Argentina is likely the Aedes Lares Permarini, sacred to the lares who protect sailors. The largest of the temples in this sacred area, "Temple D" dates to the second century B.C. and remains largely unexcavated.

title: Temple A
description: So-called "Temple A" is a structure of the third century B.C. and is likely the Temple of Juturna that was vowed by Caius Lutatius Catulus following his victory against the Carthaginians in 241 B.C. It was later converted into a church, the apse of which remains visible.

title: Temple C
description: The so-called "Temple C" of the Largo Argentina sacred area may be dedicated to the Italic goddess Feronia.

title: Roman theater at Verona
description: The Roman theater at Verona dates from the late first century B.C.

title: Roman amphitheater at Simitthu
description: The poorly preserved remains of an amphitheater that had likely been abandoned by the fifth century.

title: Tomb of Tutankhamun (KV62)
description: The rock-cut tomb of the Egyptian pharaoh Tutankhamun (r. ca. 1332-1323 BC), discovered by Howard Carter in 1922.

title: Public baths at Saepinum
description: The public baths at Saepinum are located along the decumanus and date to the first and second centuries.

title: Basilica at Saepinum
description: The Basilica at Saepinum is positioned at the intersection of the cardo and the decumanus.

title: Roman theater at Carsulae
description: The Roman theater at Carsulae dates to the Augustan period, pre-dating the amphitheater.

title: Forum of Carsulae
description: The Forum of Carsulae is supported by terraces and it includes the basilica and a twin sanctuary, in addition to tabernae.

title: So-called twin sanctuary
description: A double sanctuary on the forum of Carsulae. It is no longer clear to which gods these temples belonged.

title: Roman arch
description: A triumphal arch located in the civic forum.

title: Roman arch
description: The Roman arch that stands at Musti (Tunisia).

title: Forum of Suasa
description: The Forum of Suasa measures 50 x 100 meters and was surrounded by a portico.

title: House of the Cryptoporticus at Vulci
description: A well-appointed Roman domus with a large, well-preserved cryptoporticus. The earliest phase belongs to the late second and early first century B.C. with subsequent modifications during the early Imperial period.

title: Castel Sant'Angelo
description: The Mausoleum of Hadrian, also known as the Castel Sant'Angelo, is an Imperial tomb on the banks of the Tiber river.

title: Via Aurelia
description: A Roman road.

title: Ponte Nepesino
description: A bridge along the Via Amerina.

title: Ponte Romano di Parco dei Medici

title: Spring near Murus Anastasii/Makron Teichos

title: Mouseion Hill

title: Mithraeum at Fertőrákos
description: A well-preserved Mithraeum with modern stone vault above ground and site below in Fertőrákos, Hungary at the site of ancient Scarbantia

title: Castellar
description: A Gallic oppidum and sanctuary to the god Dexiva in the Vaucluse départment.

title: Capitolinus Mons
description: The smallest of Rome's hills and one of its most important, the Capitoline served as the citadel (arx) of the city and as the site of its poliadic temple.

title: Arcus Argentariorum
description: A commemorative arch located in the Velabrum dedicated to the Severan emperors in AD 204 by the local association of money-changers (argentarii) and merchants (negotiantes). It was later incorporated into the church of S. Giorgio al Velabro.

title: Polygonal masonry wall

title: Unnamed aqueduct at Ephesus (Aqua Iulia?)

The aqueduct was first commissioned by the emperor Hadrian in 122-126, and it portions of it remained in use into the medieval period. In modern times, it is known as the Değirmendere Aqueduct, after the nearby Kenchrios river (modern Değirmendere).

title: Governor's Palace at Kalhu
description: This beautifully-decorated Assyrian palace is located just north of the Nabû temple Ezida, in the southeast quarter of the citadel of Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud). The building likely served as the office and/or residence of several important individuals in the administration of the Assyrian Empire, probably including the governor of Kalhu. Numerous cuneiform tablets were discovered in three rooms north of the central courtyard. Because many of those Akkadian texts relate to the activities of several governors, British excavators in the 1950s dubbed the building the "Governor's Palace."

title: Kalhu ziggurat
description: The temple-tower of the god Ninurta, which was started by the ninth-century-BC Assyrian ruler Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) and completed by his son and successor Shalmaneser III (r. 858–824 BC), is still the most prominent feature of Kalhu (modern Nimrud). This multi-staged ziggurat, whose remains are now a pyramid of eroding mud-brick, was constructed in the northwest corner of the citadel, next to Kalhu's principal sanctuary, the Ninurta temple.

title: Ninurta temple (Kalhu)
description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. The most important of those was dedicated to the god Ninurta, the patron deity of city, which Ashurnasirpal had constructed between his palace and the ziggurat, a building also consecrated to Ninurta.

title: Ea-Damkina temple (Kalhu)
description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the god Ea and the goddess Damkina. Although its location is not known, the Ea-Damkina temple at Kalhu is thought to have been situated within the Ninurta temple complex, in the northwest corner of the citadel.

title: Kidmuri temple (Kalhu)
description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the divine Kidmuri (probably a collective name for a group of gods).

title: Central Building at Kalhu
description: Near the middle of the citadel of Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud), the ninth-century-BC Assyrian king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) constructed a building with a grand, south-facing entrance. This building, constructed east of the southeast corner of the Northwest Palace, might have been one of the temples built by Ashurnasirpal II when he made Kalhu the administrative capital of the Assyrian Empire. Alternatively, the Central Building might have served as a palace.

title: Al-Khazneh
description: An elaborate, rock-cut monument at Petra built ca. 100 BC to AD 200 known as "Al-Khazneh" or "The Treasury". The Nabatean structure, originally used as a tomb, dates to the reign of Aretas IV Philopatris.

title: Synagogue at Aḥmadiah (Aḥmadiya, Ahmadiyye)
description: Remains of a synagogue in the Golan with Greek and Hebrew Inscriptions

title: Bitti, Complesso di Romanzesu
description: A 7-hectare nuragic complex.

title: Seruci
description: A nuragic complex including a central nuraghe and an associated village.

title: Nuraghe s'Ulimu
description: A two-tower nuraghe located near Ulassai in the province of Nuoro.

title: Qaqqar-aradātu
description: An unlocated city/town in the kingdom of Suhu, probably not far from Alu-eššu, Baqa, and Ribaniš.

title: Dūr-Šamaš-rēša-uṣur
description: This unlocated, fortified settlement was founded and built by Šamaš-rēša-uṣur of Suhu, which he named after himself: Dūr-Šamaš-rēša-uṣur (“Fort Šamaš-rēša-uṣur”). The city is presumably located in the kingdom of Suhu.

title: Enamhe
description: The temple of the gods Adad and Apla-Adad at Anat (Anatho). The Sumerian ceremonial name Enamhe means "House of Plenty."

title: Uqaya
description: This unlocated land/region is presumably near the kingdom of Suhu, in the middle Euphrates region.

title: Ṣumūa
description: An unlocated well presumably in the middle Euphrates region, in or near the kingdom of Suhu.

title: Martu
description: An unlocated well in the middle Euphrates region, near the city Ḫindānu.

title: Habha
description: An unlocated, mountainous region northwest of Assyria, possibly in the Taurus mountains.

title: Suhu
description: The kingdom of Suhu was situated on the middle Euphrates and stretched from the northwestern border of Babylonia in the south to Hindanu in the north. During the 9th and 8th centuries B.C., its rulers held authority over the cities Anat (Anatho), Suru, Rahi-ilu, and even Mari. Approximately thirty Akkadian inscriptions of its rulers Šamaš-rēša-uṣur and Ninurta-kudurrī-uṣur were discovered in the region of Haditha in the early 1980s, prior to the construction of the Haditha dam, which flooded the region; many of Suhu's cities are now underwater.

title: Sarugu
description: The name of a nomadic Aramean tribal group that was in the middle Euphrates region during the early part of the first millennium B.C.

title: Haṭallu
description: The name of a nomadic Aramean tribal group that was active in the middle Euphrates region during the early part of the first millennium B.C. and in Babylonia in the middle of the eighth century B.C.

title: Luhuāyu
description: The name of a nomadic Aramean tribal group that was in the middle Euphrates region during the early part of the first millennium B.C.

title: Hanzanūa
description: The name of a nomadic Aramean tribal group that was in the middle Euphrates region during the early part of the first millennium B.C.

title: Vejano
description: Vejano, located in the Province of Viterbo, is located on the Mignone river approximately 60 km northwest of Rome. While the most visible monument on the site today is the fifteenth century castle known as "La Rocca", the site has a long settlement history reaching back to the Bronze Age.

title: Tropaeum Traiani (monument)
description: A war memorial near the ancient settlement of Tropaeum Traiani (modern Adamclisi)

title: Tell al-Ubaid
description: Tell al-'Ubaid is a small tell located west of Ur.

title: Jemdet Nasr
description: An ancient site in Iraq's Babil Governorate (Iraq) that lends its name to the Jemdet Nasr period (ca. 3100–2900 B.C.).

title: Arumâ
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources that has been identified as modern Ḥirbe Ruma (Khirbet ar-Rumah) and Biblical Rumah.

title: Korucutepe
description: An ancient settlement in the Altınova plain (eastern Anatolia). The site was flooded by the construction of the Keban Dam in 1974.

title: Forum of Vulci
description: The forum of the ancient town, dating to the Roman period.

title: Forum of Roman Corinth
description: The Roman forum of ancient Corinth.

title: Roman theater of Lokroi Epizephyrioi
description: A Roman theater of the first century B.C. built on the site of the fourth century B.C. Greek theater.

title: Etruscan acropolis at Volaterrae
description: The multi-phase acropolis of Etruscan Volaterrae has numerous important phases, beginning in the Archaic period. The monumental site continued to develop and grow during the Hellenistic period. It was identified archaeologically only in the nineteenth century. In the twentieth century it was the subject of major investigations under M. Cristofani and, later, M. Bonamici.

title: Roman theater at Volaterrae
description: The Roman theater of Volaterrae was built during the during the Augustan period under the consulship of Aulus Caecina Severus.

title: Turris Mamilia
description: The Turris Mamilia was a tower in Rome's Subura that was part of the sacred rites of the Equus October.

title: Avitta Bibba amphitheater
description: A Roman amphitheater located in the modern Siliana Governorate of Tunisia.

title: Zababa Gate
description: The Zababa Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the eastern side of the inner city, directly east of the TE.E quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

title: Ehursagtilla
description: The temple of the god Ninurta, Ehursagtilla (“House Which Exterminates the Mountains”), was located in the Šuanna district (modern Ishin Aswad) of Babylon. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, this was one of two temples in that part of the city, which was located in the southern part of the eastern half of Babylon. The building was rebuilt by the Neo-Babylonian king Nabopolassar (r. 625–605 BC).

title: Kullab
description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Kullab was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained four temples.

title: TE.E
description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, TE.E (read as either Tê or Kisīri) was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained one temple and two daises.

title: Anghelu Ruju necropolis
description: A pre-nuragic necropolis discovered in 1903.

title: Gardens of Maecenas
description: The Gardens of Maecenas or "Horti Maecenatis" were extensive, planned gardens laid out on Rome's Esquiline Hill by Caius Cilinius Maecenas in the mid-30s B.C. These formal gardens occupied what had previously been the agger of the Servian walls and the adjacent necropolis that had an unsavory reputation. Following the death of Maecenas, the gardens became imperial property.

title: North Palace at Babylon
description: The Neo-Babylonian king Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC) constructed a new royal residence for himself at Babylon. This grand palace was constructed north of the so-called “South Palace,” the traditional royal residence of the kings of Babylon. The building, which is referred to as the “new palace” (ēkallu eššu) in Achaemenid-period texts, is generally called the “North Palace,” “Nordburg,” and “New Palace.”

title: Marduk Gate
description: The Marduk Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the eastern side of the inner city, directly east of the Kullab quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

title: Emah
description: The temple of the goddess Ninmah/Bēlet-ilī, Emah (“Exalated House”), was located in the Ka-dingirra district (modern Kasr) of Babylon. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, this was one of four temples in that part of the city, which was located in the northern part of the eastern half of Babylon. Emah was rebuilt by the Assyrian king Ashurbanipal (r. 668–ca. 631 BC) and the Babylonian king Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC).

title: Eridu
description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Eridu was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained thirteen temples (including Esagila) and the ziggurat Etemenanki. Eridu is also a name of Babylon itself.

title: Ka-dingirra
description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Ka-dingirra was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained four temples. Ka-dingirra is also a name of Babylon itself.

title: New City/Newtown
description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, New City (ālu eššu) was one of the six city districts of the eastern half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained two temples and one dais. This city quarter dates back to the late Old Babylonian Period (as demonstrated by a commercial archive excavated in the Merkes).

title: Tuba
description: According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon, Tuba was one of the four city districts of the western half of the inner city of Babylon and it contained three temples.

title: 'Ain Ghazal
description: A Neolithic settlement inhabited from ca. 7250 BC to 5000 BC; located in the northwest of Jordan.

title: Mount Fumaiolo
description: A mountain of the northern Apennines (elevation 1,408 m; 4,619 ft) from which the Tiber River originates.

title: Poggio Colla
description: An Etruscan settlement located in the Mugello valley.

title: Stony Stratford
description: Findspot of the Stony Stratford Hoard, an urn discovered in 1789 containing three fibulae, two headdresses, and approximately 30 decorated silver and gilt bronze plaques, among which were three dedications to Jupiter, Vulcan, and Mars (RIB 215, 216, and 217).

title: Maşat Höyük
description: A Bronze Age Hittite center ca. 100 km east of Boğazkale/Hattusa.

title: Arsham
description: An ancient fortress located somewhere between Mosul and modern Zakho; its precise location is unknown today.

title: Tomen y mur
description: The Roman fort at modern day Tomen y Mur, presumably Flavian in date, was likely abandoned by the middle of the second century A.D.

title: Bagni di Nerone
description: The so-called "Baths of Nero" are located near the Porta a Lucca in Pisa.

title: Podere S. Mario
description: A rural site located in the territory of Volterra.

title: Temple of Al-Lat at Palmyra
description: A temple sacred to the goddess Al-Lat in Palmyra. The earliest shrine on the site was constructed in the mid-first century BCE, and was greatly expanded during the second century CE. The temple was closed and its altar destroyed during the 380s CE.

title: So-called House of the Doric Peristyle
description: A large private house in Cyrene.

title: Via Julia Augusta
description: A road begun in 13 BC by Augustus that was, in effect, a merging of the Via Postumia and the Via Aemilia Scauri.

title: Mura Messapiche
description: Well-preserved remains of the ashlar fortification walls at Manduria.

title: *Atuna (kingdom)
description: A kingdom in Tabal mentioned in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian kings Tiglath-pileser III (r. 744-727 BC) and Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC).

title: *Atuna
description: *Atuna is the capital of the kingdom *Atuna in Tabal.

title: Jauṣa[...]
description: The partially preserved kingdom Jauṣa[...] is mentioned together with the city Hubušnu and Mount Mulî in a royal inscription of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC).

title: Jā' (region)
description: A region on Cyprus (Akkadian Jadnana). The eighth-century-BC Assyrian king Sargon II states that seven kings of Jāʾ, a region of Jadnana, sent him tribute.

title: Harrua
description: Harrua is a Quean fortress located on the Cilician plain. In the eighth century BC, perhaps only for a short time, Phrygia controlled the territory in which Harrua is was located. The Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705), after his armies defeated the Phrygian king Midas (= Mitâ of Musku), restored Harrua to Que, which was then a province of the Assyrian Empire.

title: Lamena (mountain)
description: A mountain in Que, probably in the region of Kozan or north of Adana, mentioned in royal inscriptions of the Assyrian king Shalmaneser III (r. 858-824 BC).

title: Falerna
description: A rural tribe of Rome, which was established in 318 B.C.

title: Villa della Cecchignola
description: A Roman villa that was, in antiquity, located along the via Ardeatina, perhaps at the ninth mile. Excavations by Carlo Fea (1828) and twentieth century excavations (1939) recorded the villa on the land of the Cecchignola (formerly a property of the Torlonia family). The precise location of the archaeological site is today unknown.

title: Tor di Mezzavia di Frascati
description: The Tor di Mezzavia is a Medieval tower located along the modern Via Tuscolana, marking the midway point between Rome and Frascati.

title: Kara-Tepe
description: A Buddhist monastery constructed near the city of Tarmita/Termez in the early second century CE.

title: Roman amphitheater of Venusia
description: A Roman amphitheater dating to the first and second centuries.

title: Gravelly Guy
description: A settlement near modern Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England, occupied from the late Neolithic through the Roman periods.

title: Azeia
description: A settlement in Troas whose precise location cannot be determined today.

title: Silwan necropolis
description: Iron Age cemetery located on the eastern slope of the Kidron Valley, containing burials dated from the 9th-7th centuries BCE.

title: Aetolian League
description: Based in Aetolia in central Greece, the Aetolian League was founded in the Hellenistic period to counter the power of Macedon and the Achaean League. It was allied with Rome in the First Macedonian War (215-205 BCE), but later was opposed to the republic in Rome's war against Antiochos (192–188 BCE). After Rome's victory in 188, the Aetolian League was fully subordinate to Rome.

title: Achaean League (Second)
description: Established in 280 BCE, the second Achaean League was centered in the northern and central Peloponnese. Allied to Rome in the Second Macedonian War (200-196 BCE), the league extended its control over all of the Peloponnese. In the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BCE) the League's relationship with Rome deteriorated; in ca. 146 BCE this led to open warfare, which resulted in the defeat and dissolution of the league.

title: Shio-Mgvime monastery
description: Monastery near the town of Mtskheta in Georgia. According to tradition, the monastery was founded in the 6th century CE by St. Shio the Anchorite. It was one of Georgia's largest monastic communities in the early Middle Ages, and it remained in active use throughout the Medieval and Early Modern periods.

title: Little Oakley Roman villa
description: The site of a Roman villa that was partially excavated in 1939 and then again from 1951 to 1978. The site was occupied from ca. A.D. 60 until the fourth century.

title: Naga ed-Deir
description: The necropolis associated with the unlocated city This (Thinis), capital city of the unified Egyptian kingdom in the Early Dynastic period. The necropolis stretches for 1.5 kilometers and contains thousands of burials from the Predynastic period through the early Coptic period, with particularly large numbers of burials from the Predynastic period (ca. 3800–3200 BCE) and the late Old Kingdom-First Intermediate Period (ca. 2300–2061 BCE).

title: Ananauri Big Kurgan No. 3
description: Bronze Age burial site of the Alazani-Bedeni culture near the Alazani River in eastern Georgia. The site is dated to the first half of the 24th century BCE.

title: Rabaçal Roman villa

title: Arbor Low stone circle
description: An important stone circle of the East Midlands, dating to the Neolithic period.

title: Temple F at Selinus
description: Temple F at Selinus is a Doric temple located on the site's so-called "East Hill". Dedicated either to Athena or Dionysus, the temple dates to the middle of the sixth century B.C. The non-canonical ground plan of 6 x 14 columns gives the temple an elongated aspect.

title: Kuntillat 'Ajrud
description: A late ninth to early eighth century BC site located in the northeastern part of the Sinai peninsula, the fortress-like Kuntillat ‘Ajrud may have been a sanctuary. Hebrew and Phoenician inscriptions have been identified at the site.

title: Roman bath at Volaterrae
description: A bath complex located adjacent to the theater of Volaterrae.

title: House of the cithara player
description: The so-called "House of the cithara player" (I,4,5 and 25) opens both on to the Via Stabiana and the Via dell'Abbondanza. One of the largest aristocratic homes in Pompeii, it was formed from two adjoining properties.

title: House of Octavius Quartio
description: The House of Octavius Quartio or the House of Loreius Tiburtinus (II,2,2).

title: Porta Nocera
description: A city gate of Pompeii located at the southern terminus of Strada di Porta Nocera.

title: tribus Arnensis
description: The tribus Arnensis was one of the later rural tribes of Rome, which was established in 387 B.C.

title: Porta Nola
description: A city gate located at the eastern terminus of the Strada di Nola. In antiquity, the gate was known as Porta Urbulana.

title: tribus Camilia
description: The tribus Camilia is one of the sixteen oldest rural tribes of Rome.

title: tribus Claudia
description: The tribus Claudia was the twenty-first rural tribe.

title: Monte Li Santi
description: A Faliscan sanctuary located on the slopes of Monte Li Santi.

title: Watling Street
description: A Roman road in Britain.

title: Dere Street
description: Dere Street is a Roman road in northern Britain and Scotland, also known as the Via Regia. Dere Street connected Eburacum with Veluniate.

title: So-called Palace of the Dux
description: A large building complex located on the western hill of Apollonia, probably built between the fifth and sixth centuries A.D. Its position and size, the presence of a chapel with a reliquary, and some public rooms led Goodchild to identify it as the residence of the Dux.

title: Saint Hripsime Church
description: A fourth century AD church rebuilt in the seventh century AD in order to house remains of the eponymous saint. The church is located in the city of Vagharshapat (Etchmiadzin), in the Armavir Province of Armenia. Listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000.

title: Eflatun Pınar
description: A Hittite sacred spring located 80 km west of Konya, Turkey.

title: Karatepe
description: A late Hittite fortress (Azatiwataya) located in Cilicia that became a significant Neo-Hittite center after the collapse of the Hittite Empire.

title: Ta' Ħaġrat Temple Complex
description: Ta' Ħaġrat is a megalithic temple complex on the island of Malta (ca. 3600-3000 B.C.), included in the UNESCO World Heritage List.

title: Los Vilars
description: A fortified Iberian site in use from ca. 750 B.C. to 325 B.C.

title: Gallo-Roman bath complex at Mackwiller
description: A Gallo-Roman bath complex located at the modern town of Mackwiller in the French commune of Waldhambach.

title: Via Latina
description: A Roman road running southeast from Rome toward Campania.

title: Vicus Iugarius
description: An ancient street that led from the Forum Romanum to the porta Carmentalis, passing between the basilica Iulia and the temple of the Castors.

title: Stadium at Anazarbos
description: A stadium south of the city proper at Anazarbos (modern Dilekkaya in Turkey)

title: Ringwall Rentmauer (Weilrod)
description: A Celtic hill-fort from the La Tène period.

title: Roman Forts and Camps at Cawthorn
description: A series of contiguous Roman forts.

title: Reycross
description: A castra aestivalia perhaps dating from the campaigns of Agricola.

title: Temple of Zeus at Cyrene
description: The Doric Temple of Zeus at Cyrene

title: Agade
description: Agade was the capital of the Akkadian state, which was the dominant military and political force in southern Mesopotamia ca. 2334-2113 B.C. Agade (also known as Akkad and Akkade) is mentioned in cuneiform texts from the late third millennium B.C. to the Neo-Babylonian period. The exact location is still unknown and debated among scholars, many of whom place it along or east of the Tigris River, between Samarra and Baghdad.

title: Cuarto Roble
description: A fortified Roman villa within the territory of Norba Caesarina. Re-occupation occurred during the Islamic period in Spain.

title: Temple of Vesta at Rome
description: The Temple of Vesta, located at the east end of the Forum Romanum.

title: Pyramid of Kenchreai
description: A pyramidal structure located near the modern village of Hellenikon in Greece, whose ancient name is unknown. It is variously interpreted as one of several mass graves mentioned by Pausanias or as a fort or guard tower for a farm or other installation. Possibly of classical date.

title: Temple C at Selinus
description: The so-called Temple C at Selinus is a Doric temple that dates to the second half of the sixth century B.C.

title: Tall-e Bakun
description: Prehistoric archaeological site located 3 km south of Persepolis. The site consists of two mounds (Tall-e Bakun A and B).

title: Villa romana di via Carciano
description: A Roman villa dating to the second century A.D.

title: Villa di Formello
description: A Roman villa dating ca. 50 B.C. located near Monte Gennaro.

title: Ḫafāǧa
description: A Sumerian city located on the Diyala River known for its Early Dynastic temples.

title: Kythnos (island)
description: Kythnos is an island in the Aegean Sea and one of the Cyclades.

title: Lacedaemon/Laconia
description: Lacedaemon/Laconia is a region comprising the south-eastern part of the Peloponnese.

title: Laconicus Sinus

title: Ladon/Selleis (river)

description: A prehistoric Iberian settlement of the Iron Age.

title: Antinoeion at Hadrian's Villa
description: A sacred precinct at the western end of Villa Hadriani, comprising two temples at opposite (north and south) ends of a plaza or garden, and (on the western edge of this complex) a small colonnaded hemicycle. Here, Hadrian may have planned to build a large, semi-circular temple-tomb for Antinous, in place of which his successors built the colonnaded hemicycle.

title: Sanctuary of Aphrodite Paphia
description: A major sanctuary to Aphrodite on Cyprus; activity is found as early as the 3rd millennium BCE.

title: Public Bath of Pella
description: The Public Bath at Pella is a bathing complex constructed and continuously renovated between the 4th and the 1st centuries BCE.

title: Persian and Hellenistic Administrative Building (PHAB), Tel Kedesh
description: The Persian and Hellenistic Administrative Building was constructed at Tel Kedesh by the Persians in the mid-4th century BCE and was in use through the middle Hellenistic Period (around 143 BCE).

title: Grove of Asklepios at Kos
description: Mentioned in ancient sources, this sacred grove in the ancient sanctuary of Asklepios located on the Aegean island of Kos cannot be precisely located today.

title: Funerary Chamber of Manlia Felicitas
description: A subterranean funerary chamber with three frescoes walls depicting animal and vegetal life, located around the third mile of the Via Appia.

title: Polygonal wall of Signia
description: The circuit wall of ancient Signia realized in polygonal masonry.

title: Monte Tamburino necropolis
description: A necropolis with inhumations dating to the fifth and fourth centuries B.C.

title: Santi Quattro Coronati
description: Santi Quattro Coronati is an early Christian basilica on Rome's Caelian Hill begun by Pope Miltiades in the fourth century A.D.

title: Sobek temple, Qaşr Qārūn
description: A Ptolemaic temple to the god Sobek.

title: Northwest Palace at Kalhu
description: An impressive and ornately-decorated palace constructed at Kalḫu (modern Nimrud, biblical Calah) by the ninth-century-BC Assyrian ruler Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC), likely completed between 865 and 869 BC. This multi-winged palatial complex served as the primary residence and chief administrative center of the Assyrian Empire until Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC) moved the imperial capital to Dūr-Šarrukīn in 706 BC. The Northwest Palace, the name given to it by its excavators (since it was built in the northwestern part of Kalḫu’s citadel), remained in use until the very end of the Assyrian Empire (612 BC). The southern half of the building also functioned as the burial place of prominent royal women, including Mullissu-mukannišat-Ninua, the wife of Ashurnasirpal and the mother of Shalmaneser III.

title: Stonehenge
description: An ancient formation of stones set in a field near Salisbury (Wiltshire County, England).

title: Roman amphitheater at Segobriga
description: The Roman amphitheater at Segobriga dates to the Flavian period. It measures approximately 75 by 65 meters and could seat 5,500 spectators.

title: Arch of Augustus at Aosta
description: The Arch of Augustus at Aosta is a commemorative arch dedicated to Augustus ca. 25 BC following victories over the Salassi.

title: Roman amphitheatre, Charterhouse
description: An amphitheater stood to the west of the lead mining settlement at Charterhouse Roman Town.

title: Roman civil amphitheater at Carnuntum
description: Located outside the city wall, the Roman amphitheater at Carnuntum dates to the later second century. It could accommodate some 13,000 spectators. The amphitheater likely went out of use by the fourth century.

title: Roman theater at Lupia(e)
description: The precise date of the Roman theater at Lecce is uncertain, but it is generally assigned to the Augustan period.

title: Roman Amphitheater at Mérida
description: The Amphitheatre of Mérida was inaugurated in 8 B.C.

title: Roman Circus at Mérida
description: The Roman Circus at Mérida dates ca. 20 B.C.

title: Aquincum Military Amphitheater
description: The Aquincum Military Amphitheater dates to the reign of Antoninus Pius.

title: Diavolino II tomb
description: An Etruscan tomb of the seventh century B.C.

title: Roman theater at Fiesole
description: The Roman theater at Fiesole dates to the first century.

title: Roman theater at Falerii
description: The Roman theater at Falerii was excavated in 1829.

title: Falerii Novi amphitheater
description: The Falerii Novi amphitheater is located north of the city walls.

title: Roman theater at Vendeuil-Caply
description: The larger of the two Roman theaters at Vendeuil-Caply was located at the northwest angle of the cardo and the decumanus.

title: Theater at Philippi
description: The initial phase of the Theater at Philippi dates to just after 356 B.C. when Philip II conquered the city.

title: Temple of Apollo at Metropolis
description: A peripteral Doric temple built in the mid-6th c. BCE and destroyed by fire in the 2nd c. BCE. The temple faces east, and was built of mudbrick on foundations of local sandstone, with sandstone column drums and a terracotta roof. A 4th c. BCE dedicatory inscription found in the cella attests the worship of Apollo. The structure was discovered in 1994 following the activity of looters.

title: Temple of Jupiter, Damascus
description: The Temple of Jupiter in Damascus was begun during the rule of Augustus and completed during the rule of Constantius II.

title: The Great Altar at Pergamon
description: A monumental altar built during the reign of king Eumenes II.

title: Temple of Trajan at Pergamon
description: The Temple of Trajan at Pergamon, also referred to as the Traianeum, was dedicated to Trajan and Zeus Philios and completed during the reign of Hadrian.

title: Palace of Diocletian
description: A third century A.D. fortified palace built by the emperor Diocletian.

title: Church of Panagia Chalkeon
description: An eleventh century A.D. Byzantine church in Thessaloniki.

title: Capitolium of Brixia
description: The Capitolium of Brixia was built in A.D. 73.

title: Sultan Kala
description: A fortified area at Merv covering some 400 hectares.

title: Erk Kala
description: Erk Kala, founded in the sixth century B.C., was at the center of Merv.

title: Qatna
description: A city in western Syria first settled in the Early Bronze Age III (ca. 2700-2600 BCE). In the Middle Bronze Age (2000-1600 BCE), it became a major trading center and the capital of a regional kingdom. In the Late Bronze Age Qatna the city became a vassal of first the Mitanni Kingdom, then the Neo-Hittite Empire and Egypt. The city's acropolis was abandoned in the Late Bronze Age I, though the surrounding area remained inhabited. It was resettled in the 10th century BCE as part of the Aramaean kingdom of Hamath, but was sacked by the army of Sargon II in 720 and ultimately abandoned in the 6th century BCE.

title: Eremo di San Michele Arcangelo
description: A rock-cut Christian sanctuary located on Monte Altino in the Monti Aurunci that was begun ca. A.D. 830.

title: Alaca Höyük
description: A Neolithic and Hittite settlement located to the northeast of Boğazkale.

title: Hattusa
description: The Late Bronze Age capital of the Hittite empire (near modern Boğazkale in Turkey). The site was enrolled as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1986.

title: Arzâ
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources; the modern site is T. Ǧāmā.

title: Bliznet͡sy
description: Iron age burial mound near Dnipro (Dnipropetrovsk).

title: Roman theater at Salamis/Konstantia
description: Salamis remained an important city of Cyprus during the Roman period and the theater is one part of a complex of monumental architecture there.

title: Roman amphitheater at Trier
description: The Roman amphitheater at Trier dates to the reign of Antoninus Pius and was renovated under Constantius Chlorus. The arena measures ca. 71 x 47.5 meters.

title: Neuri
description: A tribe whose territory was located on the Hypanis to the west of the Borysthenes.

title: Porta Nigra
description: The so-called "Porta Nigra" is a surviving Roman city gate that dates to ca. A.D. 186-200. It was enlisted as part of the "Roman Monuments, Cathedral of St. Peter and Church of Our Lady in Trier" UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1986.

title: Motroninskoe Gorodishche
description: At Motroninskoe Gorodishche in Mielniki (central Ukraine, obl. Cherkassy) an early Iron Age fortified settlement has been identified. The ancient site was a large settlement of the ancient Scythians.

title: Temple of Trajan at Italica
description: A sanctuary dedicated to Trajan in the 'urbs nova' of Italica that flourished under the patronage of Hadrian.

title: Haltwhistle Burn Roman Fortlet and Camp
description: Site of Roman fortlet and temporary camp. The fortlet guarded the crossing of the Burn by the Stanegate. It pre-dates the construction of Hadrian's Wall, which passes 0.5 km to the north.

title: Paturro Roman villa
description: A luxury terraced villa in Spain's Murcia region that was first built in the Republican period and then abandoned by the third century A.D.

title: Nossa Senhora da Tourega
description: An imperial villa located in the territory of Ebora.

title: Caer y Twr
description: Caer y Twr is the site of a Roman period hill fort in Anglesey, Wales.

title: Royal Palace of Qatna
description: A large palace constructed in about 1600 BCE in Qatna, an important Bronze Age city in Syria.

title: Royal Hypogeum at Qatna
description: Tomb VI at Qatna, known as the Royal Hypogeum, is a tomb complex located approximately 12 meters below the Royal Palace of Qatna. The tomb consists of a long corridor and 4 burial chambers, and contained approximately 20 burials.

title: Penydarren Roman fort
description: Roman fort built ca. 74-78 CE and occupied no later than the first third of the second century, now built over by a sports stadium.

title: Roman tilery at St Oswald's Priory
description: Site of a second century CE Roman tile manufactory on the grounds of the later medieval priory of St. Oswald at Gloucester.

title: Priddy
description: A Roman building located approximately 270 meters north and east of Priddy Church. The site, excavated in 1964, has been interpreted as being part of a small villa site.

title: Quirinal Hill
description: One of the hills of Rome, comprised of several smaller peaks. According to tradition its first inhabitants were Titus Tatius and the Sabines; during the Republic the hill was a mostly residential area.

title: Doric temple of Segesta
description: The Doric temple of Segesta is an incomplete (6 x 14) temple of the Doric order begun in the 420s B.C.

title: Kothon
description: The Kothon harbor is an artificial port basin of the Punic phase of the island, dating to the sixth century B.C.

title: Queen's pyramid
description: There are three satellite pyramids, typically referred to as "Queen's pyramids", associated with the pyramid of Menkaure on the Giza plateau.

title: Maadi
description: A Predynastic settlement located on the eastern bank of the Nile on the outskirts of modern Cairo.

title: Porta Gemina at Asculum
description: A city gate of the first century B.C.

title: Roman theater at Asculum
description: The Roman theater at Asculum was discovered during excavations in 1932. The structure dates to the first century A.D.

title: Forum of Segobriga
description: The Forum of Segobriga is traditionally dated to the early Iulio-Claudian period when Segobriga became a municipium.

title: Theater at Segobriga
description: Construction of the Roman Theater at Segobriga began under Tiberius and was completed during the Flavian period.

title: Roman amphitheater at Rusellae
description: The Roman amphitheater at Rusellae dates to the first century.

title: Roman amphitheater of Martigny
description: The Roman amphitheater of Martigny likely dates to the reign of Trajan.

title: Porta Praetoria at Aosta
description: A gate of the city wall of the Augustan colony, ca. 25 B.C.

title: Roman amphitheater at Aosta
description: The Roman amphitheater at Aosta likely dates to the first century A.D. Its remains are englobed within Medieval structures.

title: Roman theater at Aosta
description: The Roman theater at Aosta dates ca. 25 B.C.

title: Heidentor
description: A triumphal monument built at Carnuntum between A.D. 354 and 361, perhaps by Constantius II.

title: Roman amphitheater at Carthago Nova/Col. Urbs Iulia
description: The Roman amphitheater at Cartagena dates to the first century.

title: Lucera Castle
description: A castle originally built by Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor in AD 1233.

title: Monumental entrance arch at Mérida
description: The so-called "Arch of Trajan".

title: Aquincum Civil Amphitheater
description: The Aquincum Civil Amphitheater is the smaller of two Roman amphitheaters located in Budapest, Hungary. It was built between ca. A.D. 250 and 300.

title: Arch of Septimius Severus at Lepcis Magna
description: The Arch of Septimius Severus at Lepcis Magna dates ca. A.D. 203.

title: Basilica of Septimius Severus
description: The Basilica of Septimius Severus belongs to the Severan Forum at Lepcis Magna.

title: Roman amphitheater at *Moridunum
description: The Roman amphitheater at Moridunum is located in Carmarthenshire. It is one of only seven surviving Roman amphitheaters in Britain.

title: Pietrera tomb
description: An Etruscan tholos tomb of the seventh century B.C. at Vetulonia.

title: Mura dell Arce
description: The so-called "Mura dell Arce" of Vetulonia served as the sixth- and fifth-century B.C. fortifications of Etruscan Vetulonia. These are massive walls built in megalithic technique using limestone.

title: Belvedere tomb
description: An Etruscan tomb of the seventh century B.C.

title: Pian di Civita, Tarquinii
description: The Pian di Civita was the ancient urban area of Tarquinia.

title: Tomb of the Shields and Chairs, Caere
description: The so-called Tomb of the Shields and Chairs at Caere dates ca. 520 - 500 B.C. The organization of this tomb is similar to that of the Tomb of the Capitals and the Tomb of the Cornice. It has a short dromos and a large vestibule. In the vestibule are two seats carved from the tuff bedrock as well as a series of hanging shields carved in relief.

title: Tomb of the Five Chairs, Caere
description: An Etruscan tomb at Caere dated ca. 625-600 B.C.

title: Porta di Giove, Falerii
description: A Roman gate in the city's defensive wall.

title: Theater of Tegea
description: The remains of the Hellenistic theater of Tegea are to be found beneath the tenth century A.D. Middle Byzantine church of Palaia Episkopi.

title: Kontopigado, Alimos
description: An Early Helladic workshop site.

title: Acropolis of Circeii
description: The polygonal masonry walls of the Acropolis of Circeii enclose an area of approximately two hectares. The walls likely date to the middle republican period.

title: Tuvixeddu Punic necropolis
description: A Punic necropolis near Caralis in Sardinia.

title: Pozzuolo necropolis
description: A necropolis of Etruscan Veii.

title: Santa Maria in Cosmedin
description: A minor basilica church in Rome, Italy. Tradition holds that the church was founded in the sixth century to serve the Greek community at Rome. The beginnings of the present edifice lie in the eighth century.

title: San Giorgio in Velabro
description: A church dedicated to St. George located in Rome's Velabrum. Legend connects the church's location with the spot where the Roman she wolf found the abandoned twins, Romulus and Remus.

title: Hercules Cubans
description: A shrine that is located on the Tiber's right bank, according to the Regionary Catalogues.

title: Temple of Poseidon at Isthmia
description: The Poseidon sanctuary at Isthmia lies 16 km to the east of Corinth. The initial phase belongs to the seventh century BC, although the sanctuary was destroyed ca. 470 BC and rebuilt in 440 B.C.

title: Graeco-Roman theater at Isthmia
description: A theater founded ca. 390 B.C. with subsequent Hellenistic and Roman renovations.

title: Basilica Manastirine
description: An important extra-mural Christian site at Solina. The site includes the basilica and the cemetery of Manastirine, associated with a Christian martyr.

title: Shunet ez Zebib
description: A large mudbrick structure located at Abydos in Upper Egypt that dates to the Second Dynasty (ca. 2700 B.C.) of ancient Egypt.

title: Osireion
description: The Osireion at Abydos is located to the rear of the temple of Seti I. It is an integral part of Seti I's funeral complex and was built to resemble an 18th Dynasty Valley of the Kings tomb.

title: Cybele sanctuary
description: A temple sacred to Cybele located at Neuss am Rhein.

title: Temple of Demeter
description: A Doric temple ascribed to Demeter with origins in the fourth century B.C.

title: Malthi chamber tomb
description: A Mycenaean chamber tomb at Malthi, located near the Greek village of Vasiliko.

title: Cava d’Ispica
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F5 Cava d’Ispica

title: Cava Portella Misilbesi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Cava Portella Misilbesi

title: Cave di Barone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B3 Cave di Barone

title: Cave di Belice
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B3 Cave di Belice

title: Cave di Cusa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B3 Cave di Cusa

title: Cena
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C4 Cena

title: Centuripae
description: A city of the indigenous Sikels, Centuripae allied itself with Athens during the expedition against Syracuse.

title: Cephaloedium
description: An city founded on an imposing promontory on the northern coast of Sicily.

title: Cerami
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F3 Cerami

title: *Chalae?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 *Chalae?

title: Charybdis
description: Charybdis was a sea monster that was rationalized in the form of a whirlpool located in the Strait of Messina.

title: Chrysas (river)
description: A river of central Sicily.

title: Chrysas, T.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Chrysas, T.

title: Chydas? (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F2 Chydas? fl.

title: Cignana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Cignana

title: Cittadella
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G5 Cittadella

title: Colle Madore
description: Colle Madore is an archaeological site connected with the Sicanians.

title: Colle Rotondo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C4 Colle Rotondo

title: Comiciana?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Comiciana?

title: Cosconiana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Cosconiana

title: Cossyra (settlement)
description: A harbor settlement on the island of the same name.

title: Pantelleria (island)
description: An island in the Strait of Sicily with human occupation dating back at least 35,000 years, Pantelleria has evidence for Bronze Age, Punic, Roman, Medieval, and modern phases. The Romans first acquired the island in 255 B.C. They called it Cossyra.

title: Cozzo Cicirello
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Cozzo Cicirello

title: Cozzo Matrice
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Cozzo Matrice

title: Cozzo Mususino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Cozzo Mususino

title: Cozzo S. Nicola
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Cozzo S. Nicola

title: Cozzo Sannita
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D3 Cozzo Sannita

title: Cozzo Spolentino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Cozzo Spolentino

title: Crimisus (river)
description: A river of western Sicily.

title: Cusumano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Cusumano

title: Cyanes Fons
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G4 Cyanes Fons

title: Cyane (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G4 Cyane fl.

title: Cyclopum Scopuli Tres
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G3 Cyclopum Scopuli Tres

title: Damyrias (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G4 Damyrias fl.

title: Daskon Akron
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G4 Daskon Akron

title: D(a)edalium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 D(a)edalium

title: Dianae Fons?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F5 Dianae Fons?

title: Didyme (island)
description: One of the Aeolian Islands with Greek occupation from the fourth century B.C.

title: Drepanum
description: Drepanum, the modern Trapani, Sicily, is an ancient port city. The archaeological remains of the ancient city are meager. During the First Punic War, Hamilcar fortified the site. The Roman Republic lost a naval engagement near Drepanum in 249 B.C. but then prevailed in the battle of the Egadi islands in 241 B.C. The city was likely of censorial status thereafter.

title: Durrueli di Realmonte
description: A Roman villa rustica dating to the first century A.D. located in the Punta Grande beach, in the territory of Realmonte, province of Agrigento, Sicily.

title: Eknomos?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Eknomos?

title: Eleutheros (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Eleutheros fl.

title: Elymi
description: The Elymians were an indigenous people inhabiting western Sicily during the Bronze Age and the first millennium BC.

title: Emporion Segestanon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 B2 Emporion Segestanon

title: Engyon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F3 Engyon

title: Entella
description: Entella was an ancient city in the interior of Sicily, situated on the left bank of the river Hypsas.

title: Epipolai
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G4 Epipolai

title: Erikodes/Ericusa (island)
description: One of the Aeolian Islands; the island is the site of the extinct Montagnola volcano.

title: Erineos (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G5 Erineos fl.

title: Eryx
description: An ancient, indigenous settlement of western Sicily, likely inhabited by the Elymians.

title: Eryx (mountain)
description: Mount Eryx is a mountain of western Sicily. The mountain is mentioned by numerous ancient authors; notably in the Aeneid Virgil discusses it in relation to Venus Erycina.

title: Euboia?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F4 Euboia?

title: Euryelos
description: A fortress built by Dionysius the Elder 9 km west of Syracuse, in the modern hamlet of Belvedere (Sicily).

title: Feudo Nobile
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Feudo Nobile

title: Fiume di Mallo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Fiume di Mallo

title: Fiumedinisi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G2 Fiumedinisi

title: Fontana Calda di Butera
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Fontana Calda di Butera

title: Francavilla di Sicilia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 G3 Francavilla di Sicilia

title: Gaulos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 inset Gaulos

title: Gaulos (island)
description: The island called Gozo in modern times, part of the country of Malta.

title: Gela
description: A Greek colony of Sicily founded by Rhodians and Cretans ca. 688 B.C. The oikists were the Rhodian Antiphemos and the Cretan Entimos.

title: Gela(s) (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E4 Gela(s) fl.

title: Gemelli Colles
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D3 Gemelli Colles

title: Geraci
description: A fourth century A.D. Roman villa with mosaic pavements. The villa may have extended to some 10,000 square meters in area.

title: Roman Villa at Għajn Tuffieħa, Malta
description: Ruins at this ancient site include a Roman-era bath complex and extensive mosaics. Its ancient name is unknown.

title: Giarranauti
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F4 Giarranauti

title: Gioiosa Vecchia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 F2 Gioiosa Vecchia

title: Grancifone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 D4 Grancifone

title: Grattauli
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C3 Grattauli

title: Grotta Regina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 C2 Grotta Regina

title: Halaesa
description: Halaesa is located on the north coast of Sicily between between Kalakta and Kephaloidion. The city was founded in 403 B.C. by Archonides of Herbita. The city sided with Rome during the First Punic War and was made "libera et immunis". By the Augustan period it had become a municipium.

title: Halaisos (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 47 E3 Halaisos fl.

title: Halicyae
description: A town of the Elymians located between Lilybaeum and Entella.

title: Haluntium
description: An ancient settlement located between Tyndaris and Calacte. Some authors ascribe the foundation of the site to the Acarnanians.

title: Halykos (river)
description: The Halykos (modern Platani) is the fifth longest river in Sicily.

title: Heirkte (mountain)
description: A mountain, probably Monte Pellegrino (contra Manni 1981, 86-87).

title: Santa Cristina
description: A nuragic sanctuary centered on a sacred well that was in use from ca. 1200 to 700 BC.

title: Broglio di Trebisacce
description: Broglio di Trebisacce is the site of a protohistoric settlement located on the plain of Sibari not far from the Calabrian coast. Discovered in 1978, the site was excavsed by Renato Peroni from 1979 to 1985.

title: Tell al-Fūl
description: An archaeological site in East Jerusalem, identified as a possible location for the ancient sites of Gibeah or Perath/Parah.

title: Golata Niva
description: An archaeological site near the village of Sinemorets. The site of a Thracian aristocratic woman's home, dated to the third to second centuries BCE.

title: Temple of the Oxus
description: The Temple of the Oxus is a Seleucid-era temple situated within the citadel of Takhti-Sangin, a Graeco-Bactrian town between the Vakhsh and Panj rivers.

title: Nuraghe Murtas
description: A single-tower nuraghe dating between 1500 and 1200 B.C.

title: Nuraghe Perda su Luaxiu
description: A nuraghe located near Quartu Sant'Elena.

title: Tel Kabri
description: Archaeological site near the modern settlement of Kabri in northern Israel. The site shows signs of occupation from the late Neolithic period and the Early (Ia-II) and Middle (IIA-B) Bronze Ages. The site was an important city in the Middle Bronze Age, rapidly expanding during the 18th century BCE with the construction of a rampart and one of the largest known Canaanite palaces. It was abandoned by about 1500 BCE, and later habitations (in the Iron Age, Hellenistic, and Ottoman periods) were of smaller scale.

title: Cadmea
description: The acropolis / fortress of Thebes. The fortress was destroyed by Alexander the Great in 335 B.C. and later rebuilt by Cassander in 316 B.C.

title: Temple of Artemis at Sardis
description: A large temple dedicated to Artemis at the city of Sardis in western Asia Minor. A sanctuary to Artemis was constructed on the site during the Persian Era (ca. 547-334 BCE), and construction on a new temple on the site began during the third century BCE. The temple was never fully completed. A small church was built on part of the site in the 5th century CE, but the structure declined from the 7th century onwards, and many of its stones were reused or burned.

title: Mithraeum at Poetovio
description: The third of five shrines sacred to Mithras found near the site of Poetovio.

title: Roman amphitheater at Sopron
description: The Roman amphitheater at Sopron dates to the later first century A.D.

title: Halberg Mithraeum
description: A natural cave in the side of the Halberg hill was enlarged for the use of the Mithras cult.

title: Temple of Athena at Sounion
description: The Temple of Athena at Sounion (ca. 470 B.C.) with its L-shaped colonnade was built on the site of an earlier temple (sixth century B.C.) at the same location.

title: Sanctuary of Phrontis(?)
description: The site of a shrine assumed to honor to the hero Phrontis.

title: Moron
description: A Spanish village located in the southeast of the province of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Morón de la Frontera.

title: Alcala de Guadayra
description: A Spanish village located to the east of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Alcalá de Guadaíra.

title: Pilias/Torre del Rey
description: A Spanish village located in the west of the province of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Pilas.

title: Niebla
description: A Spanish village located in the northeastern part of the province of Huelva that once belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Moger
description: A Spanish village located in the east of Huelva that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. While there is on-site evidence for long-term human activity since antiquity, the present settlement, known in modern terms as Moguer, is traditionally said to have been founded in 1333 by the Señorío de Moguer ("Seigneury of Moguer").

title: Milecastle 37 (Housesteads)
description: One of the milecastles along Hadrian's Wall, approximately 400 meters to the west of Housesteads Roman fort (Vercovicium)

title: Theban necropolis
description: Collective name for the complex of tombs and temples on the western bank of the Nile, opposite the city of Thebes/Luxor. The necropolis was used for royal and elite burials throughout the Pharaonic period.

description: A place from the TAVO Index

description: A place from the TAVO Index

title: Gaziantep
description: Gaziantep, also referred to as Antep, is located in southeastern Turkey. The site has a long history of settlement that begins in the Neolithic period. The site has a significant Hittite presence. Some scholars suggest it is the site of the Hellenistic city of Antiochia ad Taurum.

title: Tall Malʿabīya
description: A place from the TAVO Index

description: A place from the TAVO Index
