title: Bavian/Khinnis
description: Just a few kilometers upstream of the city, the 7th-century B.C. Assyrian king Sennacherib had an architectural complex built and several stele-like panels (with accompanying inscriptions) carved into a nearby cliff face. The site may have served as a summer residence for the Assyrian king and may have been used as a headquarters to supervise the construction of a vast network of canals and aqueducts that was created specifically for providing water to Nineveh and the Assyrian heartland. The "Khinnis Reliefs" were included on the 2014 World Monuments Watch to increase awareness of cultural heritage in the Khinnis/Bavian area.

title: Dur-Sharrukin
description: Dūr-Šarrukīn (“Fort Sargon”), modern Khorsabad, became the capital of the Assyrian Empire during the reign of the eighth-century-BC ruler Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC). According to the Assyrian Eponym Chronicle, the foundations of the city were laid in 717 BC and the city itself was completed in early 706 BC, one year before Sargon was killed on the battlefield. Sargon’s newly-constructed, rectangular-shaped capital, which he modelled on the general plan on Babylon, was abandoned upon his death in 705 BC; his son and successor Sennacherib (r. 704–681 BC) made Nineveh Assyria’s principal administrative center.

description: An important region surrounding the Tigris–Euphrates river system, in the northern part of the Fertile Crescent, roughly corresponding to most of modern Iraq and Kuwait, eastern Syria, and Southeastern Turkey. Mesopotamia was a critical part of many empires and kingdoms, including the Sumerians, Akkadians, Assyrians, Babylonians, the Achaemenids, Alexander the Great, and the Seleucids. It was also a site of intense conflict between the Roman, Parthian, and Sassanid Empires until the 7th century Muslim conquest.

description: Excavations at Tell Museifneh (Eski Mosul) in the 1980s revealed remains of a well-built stone building that was identified as a Christian basilica dating to the seventh century A.D. The apisdal basilica measured ca. 50 x 50 meters.

title: *Mouzoura
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 B1 *Mouzoura

title: Mygdonia
description: A plain in Mesopotamia surrounding Nisibis. Alexander the Great settled Macedonian veterans here.

title: Nabaris/Navarra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 C3 Nabaris/Navarra

title: Naqadeh tepe
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 H4 Naqadeh tepe

title: ‘Naxouana’
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 H1 ‘Naxouana’

title: Nicephorion (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D2 Nicephorion fl.

title: Nineveh/Ninos
description: This important Mesopotamian city flanks the eastern edge of the Tigris flood plain, opposite modern Mosul, of which it is now a suburb. From the third millennium B.C. onwards, Nineveh was the most important religious center of the goddess Ištar in the area that would become the Assyrian heartland. Starting in the Middle Assyrian period, the city came under the authority of the kings of Assyria, who often sponsored large-scale building activities there. However, it was not until 704 B.C. that Nineveh became the administrative capital of Assyria, when the Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib moved the royal family and court there and transformed the city into a thriving imperial metropolis. Nineveh remained Assyria’s capital until 612 B.C., when it was captured and destroyed by a Babylonian-Median collation led by Nabopolassar and Cyaxares. The visible remains of the (7th-century) Assyrian city include the citadel mound Kuyunjik, the smaller mound of Nebi Yunus, and the twelve-kilometer-long city wall.

title: Niphates (mountain)
description: A mountain range in Armenia, belonging to the eastern Taurus massif.

title: Nisibis/Antiochia
description: Nisibis/Antiochia was an ancient city of Mesopotamia that began as part of an Aramaean kingdom that the Assyrian king Adad-Nirari II captured in 896 BC. Following its capture by Alexander the Great, the city became Antiochia Mygdonia under the Seleucids.

title: Nodh-Ardashirakan
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 F4 Nodh-Ardashirakan

title: Nuarsak?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 G2 Nuarsak?

title: Nymphaeum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 E2 Nymphaeum

title: Oghlu Qal'eh
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 H1 Oghlu Qal'eh

title: Ormi/[Urmia]
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 H3 Ormi/[Urmia]

title: Paline
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 B1 Paline

title: Palios
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 B1 Palios

title: Parthenias/Nymphios (river)
description: A river that originates in the Anti-Taurus Mountains and is a major tributary of the Tigris.

title: Phasiane/Bassiane
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D1 Phasiane/Bassiane

title: Phasioi
description: An ancient people, tribe, or cultural group. Located: on Basean plain, and probably in upper R. Aras basin.

title: Phasis (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D1 Phasis fl.

title: Pheison

title: Qotur Qal'eh
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 G2 Qotur Qal'eh

title: Rehimena
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 E3 Rehimena

title: Resaina/Theodosiopolis
description: A Roman garrison town located near the Chaboras that was later renamed Theodosiopolis.

title: Rhabdion
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D3 Rhabdion

title: (Ris)Kepha(s)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D3 (Ris)Kepha(s)

title: Sanasounitai
description: An ancient people, tribe, or cultural group. Located: inhabitants of Sasun.

title: Sangar Qal'eh

description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 E3 Sareisa

title: Sargathon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D3 Sargathon

title: Satala
description: Satala was the station of the Legio XV Apollinaris.

title: Satalka/Thamanon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 E3 Satalka/Thamanon

title: Sauras
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 C3 Sauras

title: Seh Gubba

description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 C4 Shadikanni/Ar(a)ban/(H)Oraba?/*Castellum Arabum

title: Shukaraba
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D2 Shukaraba

title: Siah Qal'eh
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 G1 Siah Qal'eh

title: Sinara
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 C1 Sinara

title: Singara
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 89 D4 Singara

title: Singaras
description: A mountain range, now called Sinjar Mountain (Shengar/Shengal), located in northwestern Iraq.

title: Siphrios
description: A large Roman or late Roman fortress that was at least partly maintained into the medieval period. Known today as Rabat Kalesi, it is located to the northeast of the village of Hisaraltı in modern Turkey.

title: Amphitheater of Dura-Europos
description: Intramural amphitheater located within the military sector on the north side of Dura-Europos. Built on the site of the former Bath F3, which was destroyed by fire. The amphitheater's dedication in 216 CE is attested by an inscription found fallen from above entrance C on the south side of the amphitheater.

title: Coemeterium Maius
description: A major Roman necropolis and catacomb along the Via Nomentana.

title: So-called Area A in Berenike
description: Ruins of a Hellenistic courtyard house (possibly connected to the adjacent building, known as Area X) in the archaeological site of Sidi Khiribech in Berenike (modern Benghazi).

title: Roman amphitheater at Santa Maria Capua Vetere
description: Sometimes referred to as the "Anfiteatro Campano", the Roman amphitheater at Santa Maria Capua Vetere is the second largest in the Roman world. Begun under Augustus, it was further renovated under Hadrian and Antoninus Pius.

title: Fingrinhoe Roman Site
description: A multi-acre site, now located within the bounds of the Fingringhoe Wick Nature Discovery Park in Colchester. The site may have been or included a Roman military supply base that was in use until ca. A.D. 120. The site included several structures, a ditched enclosure, and a possible villa.

title: Tomb of Menidi
description: A Mycenaean tholos tomb first discovered in 1872. It is one of four such tholoi known in Attica.

title: Roman theater at Aizanoi
description: The Roman theater at Aizanoi is part of a theater-stadium complex. The complex is built after A.D. 160 with the patronage of one M. Apuleius Eurycles.

title: Temple of Zeus
description: The Temple of Zeus is Aizanoi's main sanctuary. The temple complex was built under Domitian.

title: City wall, Nicopolis
description: The Roman period city wall of Nicopolis.

title: Villa of Manius Antoninus
description: The Villa of Manius Antoninus at Nicopolis.

title: Gallic oppidum of Montlaurès
description: The archaeological remains of a Gallic oppidum lying approximately 4 km NNW of Col. Narbo Martius. Occupied from mid-sixth century BCE until the mid-first century BCE.

title: Palace of Tupkish
description: Palace at the Hurrian city Urkesh, constructed by Tupkish in the late third millennium BCE.

title: A'ali Mound Cemetery
description: A large complex of burial mounds located near the town of A'ali in central Bahrain. The burials date to the early Dilmun era, ca. 2050-1700 BCE.

title: Wheathampstead
description: A Belgic oppidum in England, founded sometime after 50 BC.

title: Macellum of Puteoli
description: A macellum of Roman Puteoli. The discovery of a statue of Serapis at the site led to a misidentification of the building as a Serapeum.

title: Rione Terra
description: The original urban nucleus of Puteoli, dating from the second century B.C. onwards.

title: Tarxien (Malta)
description: A megalithic temple complex (ca. 3150 BC) named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980.

title: Blatades Monastery
description: A fourteenth century monastery.

title: Theater of Melos
description: The Theater of Melos likely has Hellenistic origins but the visible phase belongs to the Roman period.

title: Anazarbos city wall
description: The Anazarbos city wall visible today was built in the 10th century of the current era.

title: Ecclesiastical complex, Port of Sanitja
description: Archaeological excavations in 2008 and 2010 revealed an ecclesiastical complex at the west side of the port of Sanitja on the Spanish island of Menorca. This comples may date to the sixth century A.D.

title: Areopagus
description: Named after a mythical trial of the god Ares, the Areopagus is a rocky outcropping in Athens located to the northwest of the acropolis. The hill was used as a meeting place for the Council of the Areopagus which functioned as a council of elders for the city of Athens. The Areopagus is also traditionally identified as the setting for Paul's sermon to Athens.

title: Cathedral of St. James, Jerusalem
description: A 12th-century Armenian church in Jerusalem, the principal church of the Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem.

title: Khirbet Qeiyafa
description: Khirbet Qeiyafa, also known as Elah Fortress, is an Iron Age fortress site located about 40 kilometers southwest of Jerusalem, overlooking the Elah Valley. The site was likely constructed in the late eleventh century BCE and destroyed or abandoned in the mid- to late tenth century BCE.

title: Jabal al-Bayḍā
description: Hill southwest of Mount 'Abd al-'Aziz in Syria. The peak at the southwestern end of the hill is known as Rās et-Tell. Excavations were carried out there by Max von Oppenheim in the early 20th century, uncovering sculptures and graves from the Bronze Age.

title: Dhāt Kāhl
description: Large town in the Arabian Peninsula inhabited from the 4th century BCE-5th century CE. The town was the capital of the Kindah Kingdom.

title: Santa Prisca
description: A titular church on Rome's Aventine Hill dedicated to Saint Prisca. A Mithraeum dating to the late first century A.D. was discovered on the site in 1934.

title: Fontaines Salées
description: Salt springs continuously exploited from the Neolithic period through the early modern era. Also the site of a Roman bath complex.

title: Saint-Pierre-d'Aurillac
description: Remains of Gallo-Roman substructures that support the choir of the present church.

title: Dunning camp
description: Temporary Roman camp of Flavian date

title: Via Ostiensis
description: An ancient road running from Rome to Ostia, exiting the city walls of Rome at the Porta Trigemina.

title: Via Nomentana
description: The ancient road connecting Rome and Nomentum.

title: Alepotrypa
description: A cave in Diros Bay in Greece used as a settlement in the middle and late Neolithic Period. The site was sealed by an earthquake and abandoned around 3200 BCE.

title: Civita di Artena
description: The remains of an ancient fortified center close to the town of Artena, Italy. The original settlement, of uncertain name, may have been established by the Volsci; both Ecetra and Fortinum have been suggested. The modern village was known as Monte Fortino until 1873.

title: Roman amphitheater at Trebula Mutuesca
description: The archaeological remains of the Roman amphitheater at Trebula Mutuesca are located at Monteleone Sabino in the Province of Rieti, Italy.

title: White Pyramid
description: A pyramid built by Pharaoh Amenemhat II.

title: Bouros-Kastri peninsula
description: A peninsula in southeastern Euboea, part of the Karystia region.

title: Sanctuary of Apollo at Halieis
description: The Sanctuary of Apollo at Halieis is a temple complex dedicated primarily to Apollo, constructed outside of the city of Halieis and dating between the seventh and fourth centuries BCE.

title: Agora at Malia
description: The so-called "agora" is a large open courtyard to the northwest of the Middle Minoan palace at Malia.

title: Unit IV-1 at Nichoria
description: Unit IV-1 is a large, megaron-style building constructed during the 11th century BCE at the site of Nichoria in Messenia, Greece.

title: Athenian Treasury at Delphi
description: The Athenian Treasury at Delphi, built between 510 and 480 BC, is a building intended to house offerings made to Apollo by the citizens of Athens.

title: Polygonal wall of Roman castrum
description: The polygonal masonry wall of the Roman castrum at Pyrgi encloses an area of ca. 5.7 ha.

title: Qalat-i Dinka
description: Archaeological site in the Peshdar Plain with remains dated to the Neo-Assyrian period. The mound is part of a larger frontier settlement known as the Dinka Settlement Complex.

title: Armenia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 90 B1 Armenia

title: Castalian spring
description: A spring in the ravine between the Phaedriades cliffs (on the lower southern slope of Mt. Parnassos) at Delphi.

title: Hypogeum of via Dino Compagni
description: A Christian catacomb on the ancient Via Latina used during the fourth century.

title: Tomb of Puimre at Thebes
description: Tomb TT39 in the Theban Necropolis, the burial site of Puimre (or Puyemre), an Egyptian official of the 18th Dynasty.

title: Purṭir
description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Urarṭu.

title: Temple of Olympian Zeus, Syracuse
description: The Temple of Olympian Zeus is located approximately 3 km southwest of Syracuse on the Cyane river.

title: Tel Dalit
description: Walled town in the northern Shephelah dated to the Early Bronze Age.

title: Temple of Olympian Zeus, Athens
description: The Temple of Olympian Zeus is also known as the Olympieion. A colossal temple dedicated to Zeus, it was built in three stages, beginning in 515 BCE and ending in 131 CE.

title: Roman amphitheater of Carthage
description: A Roman amphitheater built at Carthage.

title: Villa di Teodorico
description: A palatial Roman villa and bath complex that has been connected with Theodoric the Great, with twentieth century interpretations labeling it as Theodoric's "hunting lodge". More recent excavations have uncovered evidence for earlier building phases, dating from the first century B.C. through the third century A.D.

title: Arc de Diane
description: The ruins of a Roman bath complex at Divona Cadurcorum.

title: Tall Mūzān
description: Urkesh or Urkish (the modern Tell Mozan) is a tell located in the foothills of the Taurus Mountains of northeastern Syria. Hurrians founded the site during the fourth millennium B.C.

title: Arènes de Fréjus
description: A 12,000 seat Roman amphitheater located in Fréjus, France.

title: Pathyris (nome)
description: An administrative division of Egypt at certain periods, centered on the settlement of the same name.

title: Gallo-Roman Theater of Lillebonne
description: The Gallo-Roman Theater of Lillebonne was in use from the first to the third century.

title: Tall Marjab
description: Tall Marjab is a small, heavily denuded mound in the Dhi Qar province of southern Iraq, some 15 kilometers south of Nasiriya and ca. 10 kilometres southeast of Ur. Traces of a small settlement dating to fourth and third millennium BCE were found here in the course of brief excavations by British archaeologists Leonard Woolley and Max Mallowan in 1929-30.

title: Nērebtum
description: Nērebtum is a medium-sized Bronze Age settlement located east of Baghdad on the left bank of the Diyala river. Nērebtum was inhabited from the third to the early second millennium BCE. Excavations at the site by the University of Chicago from 1934 to 1936 exposed two extensive temple structures, one dedicated to the moon god Sîn, another to the goddess Ištar-Kititum, along with extensive fortification walls and private houses.

title: Roman siege camp
description: A siege camp dating to the Roman siege of the fortress of Masada in A.D. 72.

title: Necropolis of Selva Miccia
description: The Necropolis of Selva Miccia, located along the road leading to Vulci, contains tombs of the seventh and sixth centuries B.C., corresponding in phase to the elite structure excavated at località Le Sparne.

title: Doric temple at Kaulonia
description: The Doric Temple at Caulonia has been dated ca. 420 B.C.

title: Puzriš-Dagan
description: An ancient city of Lower Mesopotamia, Puzriš-Dagan was founded in the twenty-first century B.C. by King Shulgi of Ur.

title: Mount Nebo
description: A mountain in Jordan rising to ca. 817 meters (2680 feet) above sea level, Mount Nebo is connected with the Hebrew prophet Moses and a Christian site (4th century AD) stands on its summit.

title: Fortunatae Insulae (Canary Islands)
description: The "Blessed Islands", equivalent in most ancient literature to the modern Canary Islands (Islas Canarias).

title: Canaria? (island)
description: Canaria? (Gran Canaria) is an island of the Canary Islands archipelago.

title: Logie Durno camp
description: Temporary Roman marching camp

title: Raedykes camp
description: A temporary Roman marching camp.

title: Via Valeria
description: An ancient road from Rome to Corfinium.

title: House of the outdoor triclinium
description: A Roman domus in Pompeii facing on to the Via Nocera.

title: tribus Horatia
description: The tribus Horatia was a rural tribe of ancient Rome.

title: tribus Oufentina
description: The tribus Oufentina was a later rural tribe of Rome, established in 318 B.C.

title: House of the Tragic Poet
description: The so-called "House of the Tragic Poet" (VI, 8, 3, 5) was built in the first century BC and has the plan of a classic "Samnite" house. The house was excavated in 1824. It lies at the corner of the Via delle Terme and the Via della Fullonica, across from the Forum Baths.

title: tribus Poblilia
description: Tribus Poblilia was a later rural tribe of Rome, which was established in 358 B.C.

title: Forum of Pompeii
description: Main forum of the Roman city of Pompeii (VII, 8).

title: Aurelian Walls
description: The Aurelian Walls of Rome began as a fortification system built by Aurelian and Probus between 271 and 275. They enclose an area of approximately 1,400 hectares.

title: Audleystown Court Cairn
description: A dual court grave near the south shore of Strangford Lough in County Down, Northern Ireland.

title: Knockeen dolmen
description: A megalithic dolmen located in Knockeen, County Waterford, Ireland.

title: Portonaccio sanctuary at Veii
description: The extraurban sanctuary of Minerva at Portonaccio is an important Etruscan cult center. The temple dates ca. 510 B.C. and was adorned with acroterial sculptures, notably the famous "Apollo of Veii".

title: Ezida (Kalhu)
description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the god Nabû. Unlike most of the religious buildings constructed at Kalhu, the Ezida ("True House") was built in the southeast corner of the Citadel.

title: Burnt Palace at Kalhu
description: The Burnt Palace, which was destroyed by fire when Kalhu fell to anti-Assyrian Babylonian and Median forces in 612 BC, has the longest building sequence yet identified at Nimrud (biblical Calah). This royal residence, which was constructed in the southeast quarter of the citadel, had at least nine phases of occupation between the Middle Assyrian and Hellenistic Periods. The so-called Burnt Palace was rebuilt/renovated three times during the ninth to seventh centuries BC and it might have temporarily served as a royal residence during the reign of Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC), while that Assyrian king was building his new capital Dūr-Šarrukīn. An immense collection of burnt ivories (the ‘Loftus ivories’) was discovered in and near the throne room in 1954–55; these are now in the British Museum (London).

title: Sebetti temple (Kalhu)
description: When Kalhu (biblical Calah, modern Nimrud) became the principal administrative center of the Assyrian Empire in the ninth century BC, king Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) built (or rebuilt) numerous temples. One of those was dedicated to the divine Sebetti. The location of this building is not known.

title: Qal’at Salah El-Din/Fortress of Saladin
description: An ancient castle, located in modern Syria. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2006 as part of the "Crac des Chevaliers and Qal’at Salah El-Din" listing.

title: Acropolis of Malthi
description: The acropolis of ancient Dorion.

title: Santa Costanza
description: A fourth century AD structure along the Via Nomentana that was built by Constantine I as a mausoleum, originally housing the remains of his daughters Constantina and Helena. It was dedicated as a Christian church in the Middle Ages.

title: The Great Sphinx
description: A monumental limestone sphinx situated on the Giza plateau, likely connected with the reign of Pharaoh Khafre.

title: Valley Temple of Khafre
description: The Valley Temple associated with the pyramid of Khafre. The Valley Temple is linked to the pyramid and its mortuary temple via a causeway.

title: Greek theater of Segesta
description: Remains of a Greek theater at Segesta that was first built in the first half of the third century B.C.

title: Tell Hassuna
description: Tell Hassuna is a settlement of northern Iraq, located in the Nineveh Province approximately 35km south-west of Nineveh. This is the type site for the Hassuna culture of the early sixth millennium B.C.

title: Enirgalana
description: The cella/shrine of the goddess Ištar in the Eanna temple at Uruk. The Sumerian ceremonial name Enirgalana means "House of the Prince of Heaven."

title: Ekišibgalekura
description: The shrine/seat of the goddess Ninimma in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekišibgalekura may mean "House, Keeper of the Seal of the Ekur."

title: Eušumgalana
description: The shrine/seat of the goddess Ninkasi in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eušumgalana means "House of the Dragon of Heaven."

title: Eešbanda
description: The shrine/seat of the goddess Šuzianna in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eešbanda means "House, Little Chamber."

title: Eankikuga
description: The shrine/seat of the god Kusu in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eankikuga means "House of the Pure Heaven and Underworld."

title: Dur-Sharrukku/Sippar-Aruru
description: Dur-Sharrukku is an unlocated city in northern Babylonia that also goes by the name Sippar-Aruru (starting in the 7th century B.C.). In the 8th century B.C., Dur-Sharrukku served as an Assyrian provincial center.

title: Eedinna
description: The temple of the goddess Ištar (as Bēlet-Sippar) at Sippar. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eedinna means "House of the Steppe."

title: Ša-Iṣṣur-Adad
description: An unlocated fortified settlement in the territory of the Chaldean tribe of Bīt-Amukāni.

title: Emeteursaga
description: The shrine/cella of the god Zababa in the Edubba temple at Kish. The Sumerian ceremonial name Emeteursaga means "House, Worthy of the Hero."

title: Egalmah
description: The temple of the goddess Gula (as Ninisinna) at Larsa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Egalmah means "Exalted Palace."

title: Dūru-ša-Ladīni
description: An unlocated fortified settlement in the area of Bīt-Dakkūri. The Akkadian name means "Fortress of Ladīnu."

title: Bīt-Karziabku
description: Bīt-Karziabku was originally the name of a Kassite clan, which was named after its eponymous tribal ancestor Karziabku; the Akkadian name means "House of Karziabku." By the reign of the Middle Babylonian king Nebuchadnezzar I (1125-1104 B.C.), Bīt-Karziabku had become district/region with several towns. It is presently unlocated, but may have been situated in or near the province of Namar, which some scholars suggest may have been in the Hamrin basin.

title: Gurasimmu
description: The name of a West Semitic tribe living in southern Babylonia, perhaps near Ur.

title: Parthenon
description: The poliadic temple of Athena located on the Athenian Acropolis and constructed at the height of Athenian power between 447 and 432 BCE. The Parthenon is the largest Doric temple in mainland Greece.

title: Achladia
description: A Minoan site in eastern Crete that was the site of a so-called "large rural villa" covering some 270 square meters and dating to the Middle Minoan and Late Minoan periods.

title: Ay-ibūr-šabû
description: The processional road of the god Marduk in Babylon, whose Akkadian ceremonial name means "May the Arrogant Not Flourish." The street runs north-south through the city, from the Ištar Gate to the Esagil temple. The northern stretch of Ay-ibūr-šabû is sometimes referred to as Ištar-lamassi-ummānīšu ("The goddess Ištar is the Guardian Angel of Her Troops").

title: Enun
description: The shrine/seat of the goddess Ningal in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Enun means "Princely House."

title: É.AŠ.AN.AMAR
description: The shrine/seat of the god Enlil in the Egipar temple at Ur. The exact meaning and reading of the Sumerian ceremonial name are uncertain.

title: Ešahula
description: The temple of the god Nergal at Me-Turnat. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ešahula means "House of the Happy Heart."

title: Edurgina
description: The temple of the god Bēl-Ṣarbi at Bāṣ. The Sumerian ceremonial name Edurgina means "House, Established Abode."

title: Larak
description: A city located near the Tigris River, possibly east or northeast of Nippur.

title: Dutēti
description: An unlocated town in Babylonia that is reported to have been located on one of the banks of the Euphrates River.

title: Baduldua
description: The city wall of Sippar. Its Sumerian ceremonial name means "Wall Built in Ancient Times." In the 7th century B.C., the wall was also called Badullisâ ("What Named in Ancient Times").

title: Rocca San Silvestro, Campiglia Marittima
description: The Rocca San Silvestro is a tenth century fortified village on Monte Rombolo near Campiglia Marittima in the Alta Maremma. The village was built in order to exploit rich mineral resources in the area.

title: Necropoli di San Placido
description: A large Roman necropolis in Messina, uncovered in 1914 during the works to build the modern Palazzo della Prefettura.

title: Circus Maximus
description: An ancient chariot-racing venue at Rome and a major location for public entertainments (ludi), the Circus Maximus is located between the Aventine and Palatine hills.

title: Glanum dam
description: A Roman dam that created the Lac du Peirou and supplied Glanum with water. While the ancient dam was destroyed in the late nineteenth century, the reservoir remains.

title: Zahhak Castle
description: A fortified citadel located in Hashtrud, East Azerbaijan Province, Iran. It takes its name from the mythological figure Zahhak. The site is in use from the second millennium BC until the Timurid era.

title: Porta Saracena
description: A gateway in the polygonal masonry circuit wall of Segni.

title: Castro de Ulaca
description: Fortified vettonian settlement.

title: Pen-y-Gaer Roman fort
description: A Roman auxiliary fort in Powys, situated midway along the Roman road linking the forts at Brecon Gaer (Cicutio) and Abergavenny (Gobannio).

title: tribus Palatina
description: An urban tribe of Rome created under the reign of Servius Tullius.

title: Red Basilica
description: A Roman temple built above the Selinus river which was originally constructed for the worship of Egyptian gods, most likely Isis and/or Serapis. In the Byzantine era it was converted into a church of St. John. It was subsequently ruined, although the rotunda on the north side is still an active mosque.

title: Nuraghe Trochesia
description: A monopteral nuraghe.

title: Honorific arch
description: An honorific arch built in Pompeii near the intersection of the streets known by the modern names of the Via della Fortuna and the Via di Mercurio.

title: House of Iphigeneia
description: The House of Pinarius Cerialis and Cassia or Casa dell’orefice or Casa di Ifigenia (III, 4, b).

title: House of Obellius Firmus
description: The House of M. Obellius Firmus lies south of the Via di Nola and is also known as the House of the Count of Turin. Excavated in 1910, the house's name is derived from electoral graffiti found on the site. (IX, 14, 2, 4, a, b)

title: tribus Cornelia
description: A rural tribe of ancient Rome.

title: tribus Fabia
description: The tribus Fabia was a rural tribe of Rome.

title: Gladiators' barracks
description: A training ground for gladiators in Pompeii noted for the more than 100 inscriptions connected to gladiating. (V, 5, 3)

title: House of the Prince of Naples
description: An atrium house with an austere facade located on the west side of the Vicolo dei Vettii (VI 15, 7-8).

title: House of Publius Casca Longus
description: The House of Publius Casca Longus (I, 6, 11) is located on the Via dell'Abbondanza and is also known as the Casa dei Quadretti Teatrali.

title: Piscina Mirabilis
description: A freshwater cistern at Bacoli on the Gulf of Naples, the Piscina Mirabilis likely provided sailors of the Roman fleet with drinking water. Its capacity is estimated at 12,600 cubic meters.

title: Kumtepe (Troad)
description: The oldest permanent settlement in the Troad.

title: Brú na Bóinne - Archaeological Ensemble of the Bend of the Boyne
description: Three primary prehistoric sites comprise the Archaeological Ensemble of the Bend of the Boyne located on the north bank of the River Boyne, some 50 km knorth north of Dublin, Ireland. These sites are Newgrange, Knowth, and Dowth.

title: Italia Annonaria
description: A Late Roman vicariate established by Constantine I with its administrative capital located at Mediolanum (Milan).

title: Rouweyha
description: An ancient place, located in modern Syria, with remains of an ancient basilica, residential buildings, and several tombs. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011 as part of the "Ancient Villages of Northern Syria."

title: Nuraghe Palmavera
description: A site near Alghero, Sardinia, belonging to the first nuragic phase (fifteenth and fourteenth centuries BC).

title: Il Tondo

title: Tell Agrab
description: Tell Agrab, or Ajrab, is a medium-sized archaeological mound in the Diyala Province of central Iraq, some forty kilometers east of Baghdad. The site was excavated by archaeologists from the Oriental Institute of the University of Chicago in 1936 and 1937. Tell Agrab seems to have been inhabited from the early 3rd millennium BCE until the beginning of the Old Babylonian Period (ca. 1800 BCE). In its early history, the site held a temple possibly dedicated to the god Šara.

title: Ajanta Caves
description: The Ajanta Caves are among the earliest Buddhist cave monuments and date from the second and first centuries B.C. During the Gupta period (fifth and sixth centuries A.D.), additional decorated caves were added to the group.

title: Temple of Jupiter
description: A temple dedicated to the Capitoline triad is located on the forum of Saepinum.

title: Cajarc
description: A Gallo-Roman pottery workshop producing terra sigillata in the Flavian period.

title: Roman villa at Tourmont
description: Remains of a large Roman villa and site of a significant coin hoard of the third century A.D.

title: Quarries at Aquae Albulae
description: Travertine quarries in the vicinity of Tibur and Aquae Albulae.

title: Gallic oppidum of Castel-Coz
description: The archaeological remains of a pre-Roman oppidum.

title: Sacriportus
description: Sacriportus is an ancient site of Latium located between Signia and Praeneste, although its precise location is no longer known. It was the site of a decisive battle between Caius Marius and Lucius Cornelius Sulla.

title: Clivus Capitolinus
description: The principal road leading to the Capitolium and the Arx in the city of Rome.

title: Waddon Hill
description: A Roman fort in Dorset, England, that began as a temporary camp under Vespasian.

title: Roman theater of Suasa
description: The Roman theater of Suasa was discovered in 2003 during excavations near the amphitheater. The semicircular structure measures ca. 55 meters in diameter and dates to the first century A.D.

title: Thermopolium
description: A dining establishment that served drinks and hot food in antiquity. There are several well-preserved wall paintings in the interior.

title: Horti Lucull(i)ani
description: An elite villa and garden on the Pincian Hill in Rome laid out originally by Lucius Licinius Lucullus ca. 60 BC. The present day Villa Borghese gardens still cover a portion of the Gardens of Lucullus.

title: South Agora
description: The so-called South Agora was the city's secondary public square. The complex dedicated by a local aristocrat Diogenes to the emperor Tiberius.

title: Theater
description: The Theater of Aphrodisias dates to the second half of the first century B.C. and stands on the eastern slope of the acropolis.

title: Tetrapylon
description: The monumental columnar entrance to the sanctuary of Aphrodite

title: Gutium
description: Gutium is a designation appearing in cuneiform texts of the third, second, and first millennia B.C. for the land of the Gutians (Akkadian Gutî or Qutî), a people responsible for bringing an end to the Akkadian empire. In first millennium B.C. sources, the name is used as an archaic designation for the region northeast of Babylonia, near and in the Zagros Mountains.

title: Arco Felice Vecchio
description: The so-called "Arco Felice Vecchio" is a city gate of the first century A.D. built under the administration of Domitian.

title: Via Celle necropolis

This site appears in first millennium B.C. texts together with Ur, Uruk, Larsa, Eridu, and Kullab (Uruk sanctuary), as well as in Assyrian and Neo-Babylonian texts and inscriptions.

title: Ur(i)
description: A major Sumerian city-state founded during the Ubaid period, ca. 3800 B.C. In archaeological terms, Ur is particularly well known for the lavish tombs of its Royal Cemetery, its massive Ziggurat. The site served as the capital of the Ur III dynasty.

title: Uruk/Orchoe/Erech/Orikut
description: Uruk was an ancient Sumerian (and later Babylonian) city located on the Euphrates river. At its height (ca. 2900 BC), Uruk's population may have topped 50,000 people and its walls enclosed an area of more than six square kilometers, making it the largest city in the world at that point in time.

title: Antonine Wall
description: A series of fortifications approximately 63 km in length, spanning the breadth of modern day Scotland between the Firth of Forth and the Firth of Clyde. The Antonine Wall was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2008.

title: Hadrian's Wall
description: Hadrian's Wall or Vallum Aelium was the first of two Roman fortifications built across northern Britannia. The project was begun in A.D. 122 and the works eventually stretched from the River Tyne near the North Sea to the Solway Firth on the Irish Sea. The wall represented the northern limit of the Roman Empire.

title: Graupius (mountain)
description: Site of Roman military victory over the native Caledonians in AD 83 or 84, chronicled in Tacitus' Agricola. Its location has never been conclusively identified, notwithstanding centuries of scholarly debate. Dozens of candidate sites have been proposed (and dismissed) over the years, however, the general consensus seems to agree upon a location somewhere in northeast Scotland extending north from Perthshire well into Aberdeenshire.

title: Eulmaš
description: The temple of the goddess Anunnītu at Sippar-Anunnītu (=Sippar-Amnanum).

title: Etemenanki
description: The ziggurat of the god Marduk at Babylon. The Sumerian ceremonial name Etemenanki means "House, Foundation Platform of Heaven and Underworld."

title: Emeslam
description: The temple of the god Nergal at Cutha. The Sumerian ceremonial name Emeslam means "House, Warrior of the Netherworld."

title: Emašdari
description: The temple of the goddess Ištar of Agade at Babylon. The Sumerian ceremonial name Emašdari means "House of Animal Offerings." The Neo-Babylonian king Nabonidus rebuilt/renovated it.

title: Ekurra
description: The temple of the god Bunene at Sippar. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekurra means "House of the Mountains."

title: Ekunankuga
description: The ziggurat of the god Šamaš at Sippar. The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekunankuga means "House, Pure Stairway of Heaven."

title: Eduranna
description: The ziggurat of the god Šamaš at Larsa. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eduranna means "House, Bond of Heaven."

title: Badnigerimhuluha
description: Nineveh’s outer stone wall was called Badnigerimhuluha ("Wall, Terrorizer of Enemies"). It was constructed by the Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib after he moved the Assyrian capital to Nineveh. The visible remains of the twelve-kilometer-long wall and some of its gates are still visible today.

title: Sîn-Šamaš Temple
description: One of the temples in the citadel of Nineveh that was dedicated to the moon-god Sîn and the sun-god Šamaš. Its Sumerian ceremonial name is not preserved in extant cuneiform sources and its exact location remains unknown. The temple is generally believed to have been east of the temples of Ištar (Emašmaš) and Nabû (Ezida) and south of the North Palace (palace of Ashurbanipal).

title: Emašmaš
description: The most important temple in the citadel of Nineveh was dedicated to the city's tutelary deity, the goddess Ištar. The temple was located in the center of the citadel and went by the Sumerian ceremonial name Emašmaš (meaning uncertain).

title: Ekituškuga
description: A ziggurat dedicated to the goddess Ištar was built near the center of the citadel of Nineveh, not far from the city’s main temple Emašmaš. This structure was given the Sumerian ceremonial names Ekituškuga ("House, Pure Abode") and Ekibikuga ("House whose Site is Pure").

title: Šibaniba Gate
description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Šibaniba Gate was the seventh of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Dumuq-ašnan-u-lahar-qerebša-kayyān, which means "The Choicest of Grain and Flocks Are Constantly Inside It."

title: Halahhu Gate
description: Most 7th-century B.C. Assyrian inscriptions record that Nineveh had eight south- and east-facing gates: the Halahhu Gate was the eighth and last of these. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Bābilat-ḫiṣib-huršānī, which means "The Bearer of the Produce of the Mountains."

title: Adad Gate
description: The northern city wall of Nineveh had three gates: the Adad Gate was the easternmost of the three. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Adad-šārik-hegalli-ana-māti, which means "The God Adad Is the Provider of Prosperity to the Land."

title: Sîn Gate
description: The northern city wall of Nineveh had three gates: the Sîn Gate was the westernmost of the three. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it and called it the Gate of the Garden, which was given the Akkadian ceremonial name Igisigsig-mušammeh-ṣippāti ("The God Igisigsig Is the One Who Makes Orchards Flourish"). Late in 695 B.C. or early in 694 B.C., the gate was dedicated to the moon-god Sîn and renamed Nannāru-nāṣir-agê-bēlūtīya ("The Divine Nannāru Is the One Who Protects My Lordly Crown").

title: Step Gate of the Gardens
description: Nineveh's western wall had seven (or eight) gates: the Step Gate of the Gardens was the third gate from the northern city wall. The Neo-Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed it sometime between 694 and 691 B.C. and he gave it the Akkadian ceremonial name Igisigsig-mušammeh-ṣippāti, which means "The God Igisigsig Is the One Who Makes Orchards Flourish." The gate is still unlocated, but, based on its everyday name Akkadian name mušlālum ša kirî ("Step Gate of the Gardens"), it must have led up to Sennacherib's Palace on the citadel, perhaps at the foot of the sloping passage Room LI of the South-West Palace.

title: Tell Ras Budran
description: An unusual circular "fort" dating to the Old Kingdom period of ancient Egypt.

title: tribus Pomptina
description: The tribus Pomptina (or Pontina) was a later rural tribe of Rome, which was established in 358 B.C.

title: Hospitium of Hermes
description: A Roman hospitium located near the Porta Stabia in Pompeii (I, 1, 8).

title: tribus Romilia
description: An older rural tribe of ancient Rome that was located at the edge of Etruscan territory, across the river Tiber.

title: Stabian Gate
description: A Roman city gate at the southern terminus of Strada Stabiana in Pompeii.

title: tribus Sabatina
description: The tribus Sabatina (or Sabatia) was a later rural tribe of ancient Rome, which was established in 387 B.C.

title: Chûn Castle
description: Chûn Castle is an Iron Age hill fort near Penzance in Cornwall, United Kingdom.

title: Marchena
description: A Spanish village located in the east of the province of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Santa Eufemia
description: A Spanish castle and village located in the north of the province of Córdoba that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Soria
description: Soria is located on the Duero river in north-central Spain. Inhabited in pre-Roman times by the Arevaci, the site became prominent in the eleventh century as it was positioned near the border between Muslim-controlled lands and those controlled by Christians. It was absorbed into the Kingdom of León in 1134 and later (thirteenth century) belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Guadalferza
description: A Spanish castle and village located in the south of the province of Toledo, 18 km from Los Yébenes, that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. It is now known as Guadalerzas.

title: Umbret
description: An ancient and medieval Spanish village located to the west of Sevilla that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Its modern name is Umbrete.

title: Saint-Michel tumulus
description: The Saint-Michel tumulus is a megalithic funerary mound in Brittany and one of the largest such mounds in Europe.

title: Brownshill Dolmen
description: The Brownshill Dolmen is a megalithic portal tomb built between 4000 and 3000 BC near Carlow, Ireland.

title: Silbury Hill
description: Silbury Hill is a prehistoric artificial chalk mound near Avebury and is part of the Stonehenge, Avebury and Associated Sites UNESCO World Heritage Site. The mound stands to 40 meters (131 ft) in height.

title: Regio II, Pompeii
description: The so-called Regio II, an archaeological subdivision located in the eastern section of Pompeii, includes the Amphitheater and the Large Palaestra, as well as a number of residences and commercial structures.

title: Aquitania (Roman province)
description: A Roman province formed in 27 B.C. by Augustus. According to Strabo, it incorporated the territories of the Aquitani and 14 other peoples whose territories were located between the Garumna and Liger rivers.

title: Arabia (province)
description: A Roman province founded under Trajan shortly after 22 March 106 CE. It included the territory to the east of the Jordan river and the Sinai peninsula to the Red Sea.

title: Armenia (Roman province)
description: A Roman province formed under Trajan in 114 CE, but given up by Hadrian in 118 CE.

title: Armenia Minor (Roman eparcheia)
description: Territory west of the Euphrates and Armenia (Roman province) included in the province of Cappadocia by Vespasian.

title: Asia
description: The Roman province of Asia, located on the eastern coast of the Aegean Sea. The region was bequeathed to the Roman Republic by Attalus III of Pergamum in 133 BCE. It was divided into seven smaller provinces by Diocletian in the 4th century CE.

title: Baetica
description: Baetica was one of three Roman Imperial provinces in the Iberian peninsula.

title: Belgica (province)
description: The Roman province also called Gallia Belgica.

title: Bithynia et Pontus
description: A province of the Roman Empire on the Black Sea coast that was formed when the former kingdoms of Bithynia (annexed by Rome in 74 B.C.) and Pontus (annexed in 63 B.C.) were joined together.

Following the Bar Kokhba War (132-135), Hadrian changed the province's name to Palaestina, and in the mid- to late 4th century CE the area was divided into three provinces (Palaestina Prima, Secunda, and Tertia or Salutaris).

title: So-called 'Tomb of Cicero' at Formiae
description: A 24-meter tall tower tomb on the Via Appia at Formiae is traditionally considered as a possible location of the Tomb of Cicero.

title: Roman theater at Spoletium
description: The Roman theater at Spoletium dates to the first century B.C.

title: Ponte delle Torri
description: A thirteenth century aqueduct at Spoletium.

title: Pizzone necropolis
description: A Roman necropolis located at Nocera Superiore which was buried by the volcanic ejecta of the Vesuvian eruption of A.D. 79.

title: Arco di Riccardo
description: A surviving gate of the ancient city walls of Tergeste that dates to the first century B.C.

title: Arènes de Lutèce
description: The Roman amphitheater of Lutetia (modern Paris).

title: Via Cornelia
description: The Via Cornelia was an ancient road that ran along the north side of the circus Gai et Neronis. The road diverged from the Via Triumphalis west of the pons Neronianus, near a large tomb known as the Meta Romuli.

title: Gallo-Roman temple at Nasium
description: Archaeological remains of the Gallo-Roman temple at ancient Nasium, located at Mazeroie, commune Naix-aux-Forges

title: Marsicovetere Roman villa
description: A Roman villa rustica belonging to the senatorial family of the Bruttii Praesentes that has been connected with Bruttia Crispina, the wife of Commodus. The villa was inhabited from the second century B.C. to the seventh century A.D. The villa's archaeological remains are found in the locality of Barricelle in the territory of the community of Marsicovetere in the province of Potenza.

title: Theater-temple complex, Monte San Nicola
description: A theater-temple complex that stands within pre-Roman walls belonging to a period of Samnite occupation on Monte San Nicola in the municipality of Pietravairano.

title: Street of Facades, Petra
description: The so-called "Street of Facades" is a necropolis that is lined with tall, rock-cut tombs that have elaborate facades.

title: Ramat Raḥel
description: An archaeological site identified by Yohanan Aharoni as a possible location of Beit HaKerem.

title: Bougon
description: Bougon is the site of five Neolithic barrows located in Poitou-Charentes, France. The earliest dates ca. 4800 BC.

title: Haghartsin
description: Armenian monastery complex constructed between the 9th-13th centuries CE.

title: Tell Abu en-Ni'aj
description: Archaeological site in the Jordan Valley containing the remains of a village dated to the Early Bronze Age IV (ca. 2500-1900 BCE).

title: Leuctra tropaion
description: A trophy monument erected by the Thebans following their defeat of the Spartans in 371 BC.

title: Iri-sagrig
description: A city of southern Mesopotamia attested from the Fara period (Early Dynastic IIIa) through the Old Babylonian period, located on the Tigris river near Nippur, about 60-80km north of Umma. The exact location of the site is unknown to archaeologists, but known to looters, who have stolen and sold thousands of tablets from the site.

title: Sasso Pisano
description: A sacred Etruscan thermal site.

title: Necropolis of Campo della Fonte
description: The Campo della Fonte at Rusellae.

title: Roman theater of Scythopolis
description: The Roman theater of Scythopolis.

title: Jawa (Dair El-Kahf)
description: A proto-urban center in Jordan's Black Desert (Dair El-Kahf subdistrict) dating from the late fourth millennium B.C. This place should not be confused with Tall Jawa in central Jordan.

title: Tall Jawa (Al-Qwasmeh)
description: Tall Jawa is an archaeological and historical site in central Jordan (Al-Qwasmeh subdistrict).

title: Località De Santis I at Pontecagnano
description: Necropolis in Pontecagnano containing fifty burials from the Orientalizing Period (725-550 BCE) and an additional six burials from the Lucanian period (4th-3rd centuries BCE).

title: Serra Orrios
description: An important nuragic complex that includes remains of a megalithic megaron-type structure.

title: Pomeroy Wood
description: Site of a late first-century Roman military base and later roadside civilian settlement. The fort is also known as Gittisham Roman fort.

title: Drobeta amphitheater
description: The Drobeta Roman amphitheater.

title: Mausoleum Augusti
description: A monumental tomb built in the Campus Martius at Rome by Augustus and dedicated in 28 B.C. The mausoleum served as a family tomb for the Iulio-Claudians.

title: Poikile Petra
description: Poikile Petra is the name of a road connecting Seleucia ad Calycadnum and Corycus.

title: Elginhaugh Roman fort
description: Site of the most completely excavated timber-built auxiliary fort (with annexe) in the Roman Empire, situated in present-day Midlothian, Scotland. Roman occupation was short-lived, having been established in the early 70s CE and abandoned in or shortly after 86. Now completely built over by the Royal Bank of Scotland Data Centre.

title: Mura Serviane, Anagni
description: An ancient opus quadratum wall at Anagni referred to as "Mura Serviane" based on its construction technique.

title: Woodcock Hall
description: Site of late Iron-Age and Romano-British settlement near present-day Saham Toney in Norfolk. An Neronian-era fort is directly adjacent.

title: Nemyriv Hillfort
description: Scythian hillfort site located on the Southern Bug River near the modern town of Nemyriv. The site was primarily inhabited in the early Iron Age (8th-6th centuries BCE), with additional deposits from the Chalcolithic Age, the Bronze Age, the La Tene period, the Chernyakov Culture, and the Middle Ages.

title: Santuario di Pyrgi
description: A sanctuary with twin temples located at the Etruscan port. The Pyrgi sanctuary was initially excavated by Massimo Pallottino in 1957. The so-called Pyrgi Plaques were discovered here in 1964.

title: Asharne
description: Tell ‘Acharneh is located 35 km northwest of Hama, on the north bank of the Orontes River, at the crossroads of two main trade routes. This center for the production of oil, wax, and wheat was occupied during the Bronze and Iron Ages, as well as during the First Crusades. Its ancient name, Tunip, is known from second-millennium-BC sources. A stele fragment bearing an inscription of the Neo-Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721–705 BCE) found there attests to the city’s occupation during the Iron Age.

title: Kaleköy
description: Kaleköy is a modern village situated ca. 15 km northeast of Mazgirt and ca. 90 km to the north-northeast of Elaziğ in the southeast of Turkey. In the cliff face above the village, lies an Urartian rock-cut tomb. At the left of its entrance is a rock-cut inscription of the Urartian king Rusa, son of Argišti II (seventh century BCE) (CTU I A 12-6). Nowadays the inscription is heavily damaged.

title: Camars
description: An Etruscan settlement near the modern village of Gonfienti (Prato).

title: Stadium of Antoninus Pius (Puteoli)
description: A stadium of ancient Puteoli constructed under Antoninus Pius in the second century A.D. that was revealed by excavation in 2008.

title: Oroanda
description: A settlement in the mountains of Pisidia, near the south-western shore of lake Trogitis.

title: Megaron A at Thermon
description: Megaron A is an apsidal megaron built sometime between 1400 BC and 1100 BC in the area of the later Sanctuary of Apollo at Thermon.

title: Stoa of Attalos
description: The Stoa of Attalos, located on the eastern side of the ancient Athenian agora, is a long, rectangular, two-story building of limestone and marble, with an external and internal colonnade. It was originally constructed around 150 BCE and then reconstructed in the 1950s.

title: Valladolid
description: The site of Celtiberian and Roman settlement eventually gave way to Moorish and, later, Christian foundations. Valladolid grew rapidly during the twelfth and thirteenth centuries under the kings Alfonso VIII and Alfonso X.

title: Roman temple of Córdoba
description: A pseudodipteral, hexastyle, Corinthian order temple begun under Claudius and completed under Domitian. The temple is likely sacred to the imperial cult.

title: Porta Rosa
description: An arched gateway built using the Lesbian polygonal masonry technique at Velia.

title: Belvoir Fortress
description: A Crusader fortress located in northern Israel. Gilbert of Assailly, Grand Master of the Knights Hospitaller, began construction in 1168.

title: Aspronisi
description: A volcanic island that formed on the southwestern edge of the Santorini archipelago following a major volcanic eruption that occurred ca. 1625 BC.

title: Durisdeer
description: The best preserved of the series of Roman fortlets established in upper Annandale and Nithsdale, dating ca. A.D. 140.

title: Akripos
description: An ancient settlement whose precise location can not be determined today

title: Via Postumia
description: A Roman road (via publica) of northern Italy begun in 148 B.C. by Spurius Postumius Albinus Magnus.

title: Montesei di Serso
description: A hilltop settlement with a long-term habitation, stretching from ca. 2000 BC to the first century BC. The archaeological site preserves the remains of 4+ mid-first millennium BC dwellings.

title: Uraš Gate
description: The Uraš Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the southeastern side of the inner city, directly south of the Šuanna quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

title: Pyramid of Khentkawes
description: Khentkawes I was a queen of the 4th dynasty of ancient Egypt. She may have been a daughter of the pharaoh Menkaure, and the wife of both kings Shepseskaf and Userkaf. Her tomb at Giza – LG100 – is located close to Menkaure's pyramid complex.

title: Šamaš Gate
description: The Šamaš Gate is one of Babylon's eight city gates and it is situated on the southwestern side of the inner city, directly south of the Tuba quarter. King Nebuchadnezzar II built the gate ca. 575 B.C.

title: Eanšar
description: The shrine in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eanšar means "House of All Heaven."

title: Eadgigi
description: The shrine/seat of the god Nusku in the Egipar temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eadgigi means "House of the Counsellor."

title: Eganunmah
description: The treasury of the god Nanna/Suen/Sîn in the Ekišnugal temple at Ur. The Sumerian ceremonial name Eganunmah means "House, Exalted Storehouse."

title: Etenten
description: The temple of the goddess Ba-KUR at Ša-Iṣṣur-Adad.

title: Ekurnizu
description: The sanctuary of the goddess Ninlil at Ḫursagkalama (Tell Ingharra). The Sumerian ceremonial name Ekurnizu means "House, Fearsome Mountain."

title: E-ibbi-Anum
description: The temple of the god Uraš at Dilbat. The Akkadian ceremonial name E-ibbi-Anum means "House, Anu Called It into Being."

title: Edimgalkalama
description: The temple of the god Ištarān/Anu-rabû at Der. The Sumerian ceremonial name Edimgalkalama means "House, Great Bond of the Land."

title: Sūrānu
description: A town probably not far from Uruk.

title: Šapīya
description: An unlocated settlement in the territory of the Chaldean tribe of Bīt-Amukāni.

title: Amnanum
description: Name of an Amorite tribe who settled near Sippar-Amnanu (Tell ed-Der) and also near Tuttul (Tell Bi'a) during the Old Babylonian Period.

title: Suteans
description: A West Semitic semi-nomadic group attested principally in Babylonia during the first millennium B. C. The Sutû are also attested in cuneiform sources of the second millennium B.C., including several of the Amarna Letters, and these earlier texts provide evidence for the Suteans living in the Levant and Syria, west of the Euphrates River.

title: Nēmed-Enlil
description: The outer wall of Babylon was called by the ceremonial Akkadian name Nēmed-Enlil/ Nēmetti-Enlil, which means "Bulwark of the God Enlil." According to the text Tintir = Babylon, Nēmed-Enlil (and the inner wall Imgur-Enlil) had eight city gates, four on the eastern side of the Euphrates and four on the western side of the river. The Assyrian kings Esarhaddon and Ashurbanipal and the Babylonian kings Nabopolassar, Nebuchadnezzar II, and Nebonidus all undertook construction on Babylon’s outer wall.

title: Imgur-Marduk
description: The city wall of Nippur according to the so-called "Kuyunjik Ziqqurrat List" (7th century B.C.). Its Akkadian ceremonial name means "The God Marduk Showed Favor."

title: Castro da Cola
description: A Bronze and Iron Age oppidum.

title: Parreitas Roman villa
description: A Roman village and villa.

title: Adro Vello
description: The remains of a Roman villa and necropolis.

title: Nuraghe Lugherras
description: A nuragic site of the Middle Bronze Age near Oristano, Sardinia.

title: Nuraghe Ruju
description: A hilltop nuragic complex with a central tholos tower dating to the Middle and Final Bronze Age (1600-1000 BC).

title: Bulls of Guisando
description: A series of Celtiberian sculptures located near El Tiemblo, Ávila, Spain. These statues were perhaps originally created during the second century BC.

title: Midhowe
description: A large Neolithic chambered cairn located on the island of Rousay, Orkney, Scotland.

title: Cat Stane
description: An irregular standing stone bearing a fragmentary Latin inscription, the Cat Stane is likely a Neolithic monument re-used for a burial of the fifth or sixth century AD.

title: Lion Gate at Mycenae
description: The Lion Gate is the main gate in the Cyclopean walls of the citadel of Mycenae. It takes its name from the sculptural decoration placed in the relieving triangle over the monolithic lintel, which depicts two animals (lions or griffins) in heraldic position on either side of a Minoan-style pillar.

title: Caimeni
description: Caimeni is a name ascribed to the geological predecessors of Palea and Nea Kameni. The two later islands were formed by volcanic activity between AD 1620 and 1850.

title: Tell Wilaya
description: Tell Wilaya is a small site that was occupied from the Jemdet Nasr Period to the Old Babylonian Period. Its ancient name is not known, but it may have been Keš.

title: Ugal-amaru
description: According to an inscription of the Neo-Babylonian king Nabonidus, the name of the wall of Cutha was Ugal-amaru, whose ceremonial name means "Great Storm, (which is) a Deluge."

title: Imgur-Enlil
description: The great, inner wall of Babylon was called by the ceremonial Akkadian name Imgur-Enlil, which means "The God Enlil Showed Favor." According to the text Tintir = Babylon, Imgur-Enlil had eight city gates, four on the eastern side of the Euphrates and four on the western side of the river. The Assyrian kings Esarhaddon and Ashurbanipal and the Babylonian kings Nabopolassar, Nebuchadnezzar II, and Nebonidus all undertook construction on Babylon’s great wall. Imgur-Enlil is one of the seven wonders of the ancient according to some classical sources.

title: Sumer
description: Sumer (Akkadian Šumeru; Sumerian Kiengir) is the name of a historical region of southern Mesopotamia, now modern-day southern Iraq. It is home to one of the world’s earliest civilizations and one of the places where writing was first developed. Eridu, Girsu, Lagash, Shuruppak, Umma, Ur, and Uruk are among its most well-known urban centers.

title: Nuraghe di Sant'Itroxia
description: A Middle Bronze age nuragic site with evidence of a giant's tomb and a nuragic tower.

description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F4 La Bobadilla

description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 F3 El Borracho

description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 26 D3 Brovales
