description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 unlocated Zeiritai

title: Zingabene
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 4 unlocated Zingabene

title: Zingis Pr.
description: Zingis Pr. was a promontory of east Africa.

title: Caldaccoli aqueduct
description: A first century A.D. Roman aqueduct that carried water from the locality known as "Caldaccoli" to baths in Pisa.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C3 unnamed bridge (at Calignaia, NW Vada Volaterrana)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C3 unnamed bridge (near Antignano)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 E4 unnamed bridge (Telamon)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C2 unnamed centuriation (SE Taberna Frigida)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C2 unnamed centuriation (Pisae)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 D2 unnamed centuriation (Luca)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 E2 unnamed centuriation (Ad Solaria)

title: An unnamed quarry on Ilva
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 C4 unnamed quarry (Ilva)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 B3 unnamed monastery (Caprasia)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 B3 unnamed monastery (Urgo)

title: Monastero di San Mamiliano
description: The monastery of San Mamiliano located on the island of Montecristo.

title: Untitled Villa on the island of Igilium.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 D5 unnamed villa (Igilium Ins.)

title: Ad Herculem
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Ad Herculem

title: Ad Martis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Ad Martis

title: Aquae Populoniae
description: Remains of an Etrusco-Roman thermal complex, dating from the third century B.C. to late antiquity, were documented between 2000 and 2003.

title: Barpana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Barpana Ins.

title: Birakellon
description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

title: Bondelia
description: An ancient settlement, attested by literary or documentary sources, whose precise location cannot be determined today

title: Boron
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Boron

title: Bullia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Bullia

title: Columbaria
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Columbaria Ins.

title: Hasta
description: An unlocated road station in coastal Etruria.

title: Herakleous Hieron
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Herakleous Hieron

title: In Portu
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated In Portu

title: Kelsilon
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Kelsilon

title: Manliana
description: Now unlocated, Manliana was situated along the Via Aemilia Scauri near Populonia.

title: Menaria
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Menaria Ins.

title: Piscinae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Piscinae

title: Scabris
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Scabris

title: Traianos Limen
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Traianos Limen

title: Triturrita
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Triturrita

title: Turrita
description: Now unlocated, Turrita was a station (statio) near Pisae.

title: Velinae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Velinae

title: Venaria/Oinarea (island)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Venaria/Oinarea Ins.

title: Vesidia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 unlocated Vesidia fl.

title: Eryx
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 false name Eryx

title: Lingeus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 41 false name Lingeus fl.

title: Acquarossa
description: Acquarossa was an Etruscan settlement that was abandoned in the sixth century BC. The settlement occupied a steep-sided plateau and had an area of approximately 32 ha. Its ancient name is unknown.

title: Ad Aesim
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Ad Aesim

title: Ad Aesim
description: A statio located at the mouth of Aesis fl. on the Adriatic coast; the Antonine Itinerary places it between Ancona and Sena Gallica.

title: Ad Aquas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E3 Ad Aquas

title: Ad Centesimum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E3 Ad Centesimum

title: Ad Fines/Ad Casas Caesarianas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Ad Fines/Ad Casas Caesarianas

title: Ad Octavum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Ad Octavum

title: Ad Statuas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Ad Statuas

title: Ad Vicesimum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Ad Vicesimum

title: Aequiculi
description: Aequiculi was a municipium in the territory of the Aequi.

title: Aesis
description: An Umbrian town that became a colonia civium Romanorum under the name of Aesis in 247 B.C.

title: Aesis (river)
description: Aesis fl. (modern Esino river) is a river of the Marche region of Italy and flows into the Adriatic Sea.

title: Ager Gallicus (region)
description: A region of Italy in which Gallic settlement had taken place after 400 BC. This territory was captured by Rome following the battle of Sentinum in 295 BC.

title: Alba Fucens
description: A town of the Aequi along the Marsic frontier where the Romans established a Latin colony in 304/3 B.C. Alba Fucens was a significant center of the middle republican period and became a place where Rome kept state prisoners, including Syphax of Numidia, Perseus of Macedonia, and Bituitus, king of the Arverni.

title: Albinia (river)
description: The Albegna is a river of southern Tuscany and flows from Monte Amiata to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

title: Albula (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Albula fl.

title: Algae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Algae

title: Allumiere
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Allumiere

title: Alsietinus lacus
description: The Alsietinus lacus, modern Lago di Martignano, is a small volcanic crater-lake in southern Etruria. The lake was the source of the Augustan aqueduct aqua Augusta Alsietina that served non-potable water to the Transtiberim and Ianiculum.

title: Alviano Scalo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C3 Alviano Scalo

title: Ameria
description: Ameria, claimed by Cato the Elder as the oldest town in Umbria, was an important center that may have gained Roman municipal status as early as 338 B.C., following the Latin War.

title: Amiternum
description: Amiternum was an ancient settlement of the Sabines that Rome captured in 293 BC. The settlement was situated at the intersection of four Roman roads: the Via Caecilia, the Via Claudia Nova, and the two branches of the Via Salaria. The historian Sallust was born at Amiternum in 86 B.C.

title: Ancon(a)
description: A port city founded by colonists from Syracuse in 387 BC.

title: Anguillara
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Anguillara

title: Anneianum
description: Anneianum was located in the Etruscan Apennines, along the road from Faventia to Florentia.

title: Anxanum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Anxanum

title: *Aprutium
description: An ancient region of eastern Italy (modern Abruzzo).

title: Aqua Viva
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Aqua Viva

title: Aquae Apollinares
description: The Aquae Apollinares were thermal springs located between Careiae and Tarquinii, perhaps to be associated with the Bagni di Stigliano or Bagni di Vicarello.

title: Aquae Apollinares Novae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Aquae Apollinares Novae

title: Aquae Cutiliae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Aquae Cutiliae

title: Aquae Passeris
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Aquae Passeris

title: Aquae Tauri
description: A thermal site in Etruria northeast of Centumcellae.

title: Armenta (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Armenta fl.

title: Arna
description: Arna was an ancient city of Umbria.

title: Arretium
description: Arretium (the Etruscan Aritim) was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae and described by Livy as one of the "Capitae Etruriae". The Romans captured the city in 311 B.C. and it became a station on the via Cassia.

title: Asciano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Asciano

title: Asculum
description: Asculum (modern Ascoli Piceno) was the principal city of the Piceni.

title: Asisium
description: A Roman settlement built over an Umbrian one on a western foothill of the Apennines, Asisium received municipal status and was assigned to the Tribus Sergia. Totila destroyed most of the city in A.D. 545.

title: Aspia (river)
description: The Aspio river.

title: Aternum
description: Aternum (modern Pescara) was a settlement at the mouth of the Aternus river.

title: Aternus (river)
description: The Aterno-Pescara river.

title: Attidium
description: An ancient settlement of Umbria mentioned only by Pliny the Elder. Numerous inscriptions discovered at the site indicate that Attidium achieved the status of a municipium.

title: *Aufenginum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 *Aufenginum

title: Aufinum
description: Aufinum (modern Ofena) was an ancient center of the Abruzzo. Pliny lists the Aufinates Cismontani among the communities of the Vestini.

title: *Aurinia/Saturnia
description: An Etruscan town that Dionysius of Halicarnassus claimed had been founded by the Pelasgians, Saturnia received a Roman colony in 183 BC.

title: Auximum
description: Auximum (modern Osimo) is an ancient settlement of Picenum. The original foundation was likely carried out by Greeks from Ancona. The Romans made it a base for military operations from 174 B.C.

title: Aveia
description: Aveia was a settlement of the Vestini in the valley of the Aterno river.

title: Avens (river)
description: A river of the Sabine territory.

title: Axia
description: Axia was an Etruscan center located to the west of Viterbo.

title: Baccanae
description: Baccanae was a road station along the Via Cassia.

title: Badies
description: Badies is a site (vicus) along the Via Salaria mentioned in the Antonine Itinerary. Its location is no longer certain.

title: Balneum Regis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C3 Balneum Regis

title: Batinus? (river)
description: The Batinus? is mentioned by Pliny and may correspond to the Tordino river.

title: Blera
description: An Etruscan town located on the Via Clodia.

title: Caelanum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Caelanum

title: Cales
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Cales

title: Caletranus Ager
description: The Caletranus Ager was the territory surrounding the Etruscan city of Caletra.

title: Camerinum
description: Camerinum was a town in Umbria on the frontiers of Picenum that was allied to Rome from 309 B.C.

title: Campovalano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Campovalano

title: Capena
description: An ancient urban center in Faliscan territory adjacent to Etruria, Capena was sacked by the Romans in 390 BC.

title: Capestrano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Capestrano

title: Carsulae
description: An ancient settlement originating the late fourth or third centuries BC and lying along the route of the Roman Via Flaminia.

title: Casone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A2 Casone

title: Castellina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A2 Castellina

title: Castelluccio di Pienza
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Castelluccio di Pienza

title: Castellum Firmanorum
description: Castellum Firmanorum was the ancient port of Firmum Picenum.

title: Castelsecco
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Castelsecco

title: Castiglione del Lago
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C2 Castiglione del Lago

title: Castro
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Castro

title: Castrum Novum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Castrum Novum

title: Castrum Truentinum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Castrum Truentinum

title: Casuentillani
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Casuentillani

title: Centum Cellae
description: Centum Cellae (modern Civitavecchia) was an ancient coastal settlement in Tyrrhenian Etruria. The emperor Trajan re-builds the harbor at the site in 106/7 and Pliny the Younger mentions its name, Centum Cellae. Saracens destroyed the city in A.D. 812.

title: Cetamura
description: Cetamura is an ancient hilltop settlement with occupation phases stretching from the Etruscans to the Romans to the Medieval period. The site is located near Gaiole, Radda and Castellina in Chianti, Italy.

title: Chianciano Terme
description: Chianciano Terme begins as an Etruscan site, with a temple located near the natural springs. By the first century B.C. the site was popular with Romans as a healing spa.

title: Le Ciliegeta
description: The site of Le Ciliegeta, near the source of the river Arno, served as a rich stips votiva. The site was discovered in 1836. The finds included over 600 bronzes, more than 1,000 pieces of aes rude, 2,000 weapons and other artifacts.

title: Ciminius (lake)
description: A caldera lake of northern Latium.

title: Ciminius (mountain)
description: A volcanic massif rising 1053 meters above sea level; the modern Monte Cimino.

title: Cingulum
description: Cingulum was a town in Picenum.

title: *Cingulus (mountain)
description: Monte S. Vicino.

title: Civita
description: Civita di Bagnoregio

title: Cività di Bagno
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Cività di Bagno

title: La Cività di Spedino
description: La Cività di Spedino was a fortified upland center (951 m ASL) in the territory of the Aequi.

title: Civitalba
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Civitalba

title: Clanis (river)
description: Clanis fl. (Chiana river) is a river of central Italy that flows into the Tiber river.

title: Clasius? (river)
description: Clasius? fl., a river of Umbria and part of the Tiber river's basin.

title: Cliternia
description: A city of the Aequiculi located in the valley of the Salto river.

title: Clitumnus (river)
description: A small river of Umbria.

title: Clocoris (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Clocoris fl.

title: Cluana
description: Cluana was an ancient settlement in Picenum.

title: *Cluentus (river)
description: The Chienti river is found in Italy's Marche region. It flows from near Serravalle di Chienti to the Lago di Pievefavera and from there it joins the Fiastra river and eventually flows into the Adriatic Sea.

title: Clusinus L.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Clusinus L.

title: Clusium
description: Clusium, the Etruscan Clevsin (modern Chiusi), was a major city of Etruria. Lars Porsena was a sixth century B.C. king of Clusium.

title: Cluviae
description: A city of the Carricini Samnites.

title: Colle delle Fate
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Colle delle Fate

title: Colle Plinio
description: A hilltop villa near Tifernum Tiberinum commonly associated with one of the villas of Pliny the Younger.

title: Collepezzuto
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Collepezzuto

title: Contrada Altavilla
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Contrada Altavilla

title: Contrada S. Rustico
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Contrada S. Rustico

title: Corchiano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Corchiano

title: Corciano
description: The environs of Corciano were inhabited by Etruscans and, later, there is evidence for Roman villas. In 1812, a series of bronze panels from an Etruscan parade chariot was discovered at Castel San Mariano di Corciano.

title: Corfinium
description: Corfinium was the principal city of the Paeligni in the valley of the Aternus river. The site becomes the capital of the breakaway Italic groups that oppose Rome during the Social War.

title: Cortona
description: An Umbrian city that, under Etruscan influence, expanded and came to be called 'Curtun'. Later it became the Roman colony of Cortino.

title: Cosa
description: A Latin colony in south Etruria founded ca. 273 B.C.

title: Crustumius (river)
description: Crustumius fl. (Conca river)

title: La Cuma, Monte Rinaldo
description: The principal archaeological remains found in the "La Cuma, Monte Rinaldo" site are those of a late Republican sanctuary dating to the third through first centuries B.C.

title: Cumara? (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Cumara? fl.

title: Cunerum Pr.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F1 Cunerum Pr.

title: Cupra Maritima
description: Cupra Maritima was a coastal city of Picenum (regio V) assigned to the tribus Velina.

title: Cupra Montana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Cupra Montana

title: Cures
description: Cures (also Cures Sabini) was a Sabine city located in the Tiber river valley along the Via Salaria. The Romans conquered Cures in 290 B.C. under M'. Curius Dentatus and granted it status as a municipium in the tribus Sergia.

title: Cutiliensis L.
description: A lake located near ancient Reate.

title: Doganella
description: Doganella was an important Etruscan settlement of the Albegna valley, occupied between ca. 600 and 400 B.C. The city may have comprised as many as 240 ha.

title: Eretum
description: Eretum was a settlement of the Sabines and is involved in legendary accounts of early Rome.

title: Etruria/Tuscia (region)
description: Etruria/Tuscia was an ancient region of Central Italy inhabited by the Etruscans.

title: Faesulae
description: Faesulae (modern Fiesole) was an Etruscan foundation called Viesul, Viśl, or Vipsul. The city was conquered by Romans in 283 B.C. Sulla would settle Roman veterans there. Citizens of the town supported the conspiracy of Catiline.

title: Falerii
description: A fortified town located some 6 km from Falerii Veteres and established by the ancient Romans ca. 241 B.C.

title: Falerii Veteres
description: Falerii Veteres was the principal city of the Faliscans. It is located on a tuff outcropping at the point where several tributaries of the Treia join to flow into the Tiber. After rebelling against Rome in 241 B.C., Falerii suffered serious reversals of fortune.

title: Falerio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Falerio

title: Falisci
description: The name for a group of Italic people who occupied the Ager Faliscus within Etruria.

title: Fanum Fortunae
description: Fanum Fortunae, the site of a shrine to Fortuna, is first mentioned in the ancient sources in 49 B.C. when Iulius Caesar held the town. An Augustan colony was established at the site and the Romans prevailed in the Battle of Fano in A.D. 271. The town was eventually destroyed by the Ostrogoths.

title: Fanum Fugitivi
description: A road station on the Via Flaminia, located between Interamna and Spoletium.

title: Farfarus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Farfarus fl.

title: Ferentium
description: Ferentium (modern Ferento) was a city of Etruria first mentioned in the Liber Coloniarum ca. 123 BC that became a Roman municipium after the Social War. Substantial remains of the city remain; the site was the birthplace of Otho and noted for its fine stone monuments and statues.

title: Fescennium
description: Fescennium (modern Narce) was a Faliscan settlement located ca. 5 km south of Falerii Veteres.

title: *Firmidianum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 *Firmidianum

title: Firmum Picenum
description: Firmum Picenum was founded as a Latin colony in 264 B.C. with 6,000 colonists. It received municipal status after 48 B.C.

title: Fisternae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Fisternae

title: Flaminia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Flaminia

title: Florentia
description: Florentia (modern Florence / Firenze) was founded as a colony for military veterans ca. 80 B.C. by Lucius Cornelius Sulla.

title: Flusor (river)
description: The Potenza river.

title: Fons Clitumni
description: Originally the site of a shrine dedicated to the river god Clitumnus and later a paleochristian shrine. The temple was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011.

title: Fontecchio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Fontecchio

title: Foruli
description: Foruli was a Sabine town located between Amiternum and Interocrea.

title: Forum Aurelii
description: A settlement in Etruria situated on the Via Aurelia between Centumcellae and Cosa according to the Antonine Itinerary.

title: Forum Cassii
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Forum Cassii

title: Forum Clodii
description: An ancient road station on the Via Clodia.

title: Forum Decii
description: A town of the Sabines mentioned by Pliny the Elder.

title: Forum Flaminii
description: A town founded in 220 B.C. by Caius Flaminius during the construction of the Via Flaminia.

title: Forum Novum (Vescovio)
description: Forum Novum was a Roman town and an early medieval bishopric. It is located in the Sabine hills and was likely founded as a market center during the Republican period. It had achieved the status of municipium by the first century A.D. The market center seems to have remained active until at least the fourth century and by the fifth century, a bishopric is established there.

title: Forum Sempronii
description: An ancient Roman colony, founded in the time of Gaius Sempronius Gracchus.

title: Fulginiae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Fulginiae

title: Furfo
description: A vicus of the Vestini.

title: Galeata
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Galeata

title: Ghiaccio Forte
description: Ghiaccio Forte was an Etruscan settlement, most likely founded in the fourth century B.C., that was sacked by the Romans ca. 280 B.C.

title: Graviscae
description: The port of the Etruscan city of Tarquinia.

title: Grotte di Castro
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Grotte di Castro

title: Grotte di S. Nicola
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Grotte di S. Nicola

title: Grotte di Torri
description: Grotte di Torri is located on the left bank of the Tiber river in the modern comune of Montopoli di Sabina. It has been inhabited since pre-Roman times.

title: Hatria
description: An ancient city of Picenum that may have originated as colony established by Etruscans from Adria in the Veneto region. An alternate narrative suggests that the city's origins may be as a late sixth century B.C. colony founded by Aegina.

title: Heba
description: A Roman colony that was established in the third or second century B.C., Heba lay near modern Magliano. Funerary evidence indicate previous Etruscan occupation at the site.

title: *Hercules Curinus
description: A sanctuary dedicated to Hercules Curinus located near Sulmo.

title: Helvia Ricina
description: An ancient settlement in Picenum at modern Villa Potenza in Marche, Comune di Macerata, Italy.

title: Helvillum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Helvillum

title: Helvinus? (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F2 Helvinus? fl.

title: Himella (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Himella fl.

title: Hispellum
description: Hispellum (modern Spello) is an ancient settlement of Umbria that became a Roman colony in the first century BC.

title: Histonium
description: Histonium, on the Adriatic coast, was a chief town of the Frentani.

title: Horta
description: The Etruscan settlement of *Hurta (the modern Orte) was close to the Vadimonis Lacus where the Romans fought, and won, two engagements against Etruscan armies.

title: Iguvium
description: An Umbrian hilltown, Iguvium is best known as the find-spot of the Iguvine Tables.

title: *Incerulae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 *Incerulae

title: Interamna Nahars
description: An Umbrian center founded in the seventh century B.C. that became an important Roman municipality along the Via Flaminia.

title: Interamnia Praetuttiorum
description: Originally a settlement of the Praetuttii located at the confluence of the rivers Tordino and Vezzola (modern Teramo).

title: Intercisa/Petra Pertusa
description: Intercisa/Petra Pertusa was a road station on the Via Flaminia. The toponym derives from the rock-cut tunnel or galleria that dates to the reign of Vespasian.

title: Interocrium
description: A Sabine town that was later known as a mansio on the course of the Via Salaria.

title: Interpromium
description: A village of the Marrucini, forming a station on the Via Claudia Valeria between Corfinium and Teate.

title: Lucus Feroniae
description: A sanctuary and grove of Feronia and an associated settlement located along the Via Tiberina in the territory of Capena.

title: Lugnano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C3 Lugnano

title: Luni sul Mignone
description: Luni sul Mignone is a site with archaeological evidence for habitation in the later second millennium BC, continuing into the Italian Iron Age. Excavations conducted by the Swedish Institute in Rome (1960-1963) exposed three phases of settlement activity.

title: Magliano Sabina
description: Magliano Sabina is located in Lazio, some 50 km north of Rome and some 30 km west of Rieti.

title: Manliana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Manliana

title: Marrucini
description: The Marrucini were an Italic tribe centered around Teate in the Abruzzo. In conflict with Rome through the end of the Second Samnite War, the Marrucini became allied with Rome thereafter. Their language was likely in the Sabellic family.

title: Marsi
description: The Marsi were an ancient Italic tribe. Their chief center was located at Marruvium.

title: Marsiliana d’Albegna
description: An ancient settlement located near the confluence of the rivers Albegna and Elsa.

title: Marta (river)
description: The Marta river flows from Lake Bolsena to the Tyrrhenian Sea. Its course flows past both Tuscania and Tarquinia and enters the Tyrrhenian Sea near Lido di Tarquinia.

title: Martanum
description: An ancient harbor of the city of Tarquinia.

title: Maternum
description: Maternum was a settlement of ancient Etruria that is known from the Peutinger Table. It is located along the Via Clodia between Saturnia and Tuscana.

title: Matilica
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Matilica

title: Matrinum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G3 Matrinum

title: Matrinus? (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Matrinus? fl.

title: Metaurus (river)
description: Metaurus fl. (Metauro river) flows from near Monte dei Frati in the Apennine Mountains to the Adriatic Sea. The Metaurus was the site of two key battles in antiquity. The first, in 207 B.C., saw the defeat of Hasdrubal Barca by the consuls Marcus Livius Salinator and Gaius Claudius Nero. The second, the Battle of Fano, saw Aurelian defeat the Alamanni in A.D. 271.

title: Mevania
description: Mevania (modern Bevagna) was a Roman municipium in Umbria located on the Via Flaminia. The town was enrolled in the tribus Aemilia.

title: Mevaniola
description: Mevaniola was a Roman city located in the Bidente valley. Its inhabitants were of Umbrian extraction, connected with the settlement of Mevania (Bevagna).

title: Minio (river)
description: A river that flows some 62 km from the Monti Sabatini to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

title: Misco? (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Misco? fl.

title: Misus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E1 Misus fl.

title: Mola di Monte Gelato
description: An ancient settlement 30 km north of Rome that was excavated from 1986-90. An imperial villa existed on the site up until the third century AD.

title: Montariolo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Montariolo

title: Monte Calvo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Monte Calvo

title: Montedoro di Scapezzano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E1 Montedoro di Scapezzano

title: Monte S. Angelo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Monte S. Angelo

title: Monteferetra
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C1 Monteferetra

title: Montefortino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Montefortino

title: Montelibretti
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Montelibretti

title: Monterano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Monterano

title: Monti della Tolfa
description: Monti della Tolfa, a volcanic group of mountains in the Anti-Apennines in the northern part of Lazio in central Italy.

title: Poggio Civitate (Murlo)
description: An Etruscan elite complex of the seventh and sixth centuries B.C. located at Poggio Civitate, a hill adjacent to the medieval town of Murlo and about 25 km south of Siena.

title: Musarna
description: Musarna is an ancient Etruscan settlement discovered in 1849 just west of Viterbo, Italy. The École française de Rome has been conducting excavations at the site since 1983.

title: Naharcer
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Naharcer

title: Nar (river)
description: The Nera river, a tributary of the Tiber.

title: Nelurus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Nelurus fl.

title: Nemora Vacunae
description: Shrine dedicated to a rural divinity of the Sabina.

title: Nepet
description: Nepet had become a Roman town before 396 B.C. when Livy dubs it, along with Sutrium, as one of the "keys" to Etruria. It became a Roman colony in 383 B.C. and a municipium after the Social War.

title: Nequinum/Narnia
description: Nequinum/Narnia (modern Narni) was an ancient settlement in Umbria. It became a Latin colony in 299 BC.

title: Novilara
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Novilara

title: Nuceria
description: Nuceria (modern Nocera Umbra) is an ancient town in Umbria, perhaps founded in the seventh century B.C. by Camerinum.

title: Numana
description: Numana was a settlement of ancient Picenum located south of Ancona.

title: Nursia
description: Nursia was the northernmost city of the Sabines.

title: Ocriculum
description: An ancient Umbrian city that became allied with Rome in 308 B.C.

title: [Orcla]
description: [Orcla] or Norchia is an ancient Etruscan settlement located near Tarquinia and along the line of the Roman Via Clodia.

title: Ortona
description: An ancient site in Italy that most likely originates with the Frentani.

title: Osa (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A3 Osa fl.

title: Ossaia
description: Site of a Late Republican and Imperial Roman villa (first to fifth centuries A.D.)

title: Ostia Aterni
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Ostia Aterni

title: Ostra
description: Ostra was an ancient town of Umbria.

title: Paeligni
description: An ancient Oscan tribe of eastern Italy, the Paeligni are mentioned in the historical sources first in the fourth century BC when they oppose Rome during the Second Samnite War. The Paeligni came into alliance with Rome at the end of the fourth century BC but again took sides against Rome in the Social War.

title: Paganica
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Paganica

title: Pallanum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Pallanum

title: Pallia (river)
description: The Pallia is a tributary of the Tiber river.

title: Palmensis Ager
description: Pliny the Elder discusses the Palmensis Ager in connection with his description of the Praetutii.

title: Passo Corese
description: Passo Corese is located near Cures (Fara in Sabina). The site is often connected with Titus Tatius' march on Rome in 747 B.C.

title: Pausulae
description: Pausulae was a town of Picenum mentioned by Pliny the Elder. It was a Municipium of Regio V.

title: Peltuinum
description: Peltuinum was a settlement of the Vestini located along the Via Claudia Nova. The town is notable as the birthplace of the Roman general Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo.

title: Perusia
description: A city of ancient Umbrian and Etruscan origin, Perusia aided Rome during the Second Punic War but was sieged and reduced by Octavian in the first century B.C. during campaigns against Lucius Antonius. It was rebuilt by Augustus and became Colonia Vibia Augusta Perusia quite late, in A.D. 251-3, under Trebonianus Gallus.

title: Pescara
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Pescara

title: Phalacrinae
description: A Roman town in which the emperor Vespasian was born in A.D. 9.

title: Piano Tondo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Piano Tondo

title: Picenum (region)
description: Picenum was a region of Central Italy, extending along the coast of the Adriatic Sea from the mouth of the Aesis to that of the Matrinus, and inland as far as the central Apennines.

title: Pieve Socana
description: Pieve di Sant'Antonino a Socana, a Medieval parish church, is built atop the remains of an Etruscan sanctuary.

title: Pinna
description: Pinna (modern Penne) was a center of the Vestini. The site came under Roman control after the Social War (89 BC).

title: Pisaurum
description: Pisaurum (modern Pésaro) was founded as a Roman colony in the territory of the Picentes in 184 BC.

title: Pisaurus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Pisaurus fl.

title: Pitigliano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Pitigliano

title: Pitino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Pitino

title: Pitinum
description: An ancient center of the Vestini.

title: Pitinum Mergens
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Pitinum Mergens

title: Pitinum Pisaurense
description: An ancient settlement in Umbria, known mostly via its inclusion in the texts of Pliny the Elder and Ptolemy, as well as by means of various epigraphic evidence.

title: Planina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Planina

title: Plestia
description: Plestia was a municipium of the tribus Ufentina.

title: Plestinus L.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Plestinus L.

title: Poggio Buco
description: Poggio Buco was a pre-Roman site located in the valley of the Fiora river. Its archaeological remains include those of a circuit wall and a necropolis. The archaeological site is located ca. 9 km west of Pitigliano.

title: Poggio Sommavilla
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Poggio Sommavilla

title: Polimartium
description: An ancient Roman settlement (modern Bomarzo in Italy)

title: Ponte a Buriano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Ponte a Buriano

title: Ponte Capo d’Acqua
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Ponte Capo d’Acqua

title: Potentia
description: A city settled in an area subjugated by Rome during the fourth century B.C. The local populace rebelled against Rome after the defeat at Cannae (216 B.C.), however the defeat of the Carthaginians eventually led to Potentia's reincorporation into the Roman sphere.

title: Praetuttii
description: The Praetuttii were an ancient tribe of central Italy.

title: Prolaqueum
description: A statio on the road from Nuceria to Ancona.

title: Punta La Penna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 H4 Punta La Penna

title: Quintianum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Quintianum

title: Quinto Fiorentino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A1 Quinto Fiorentino

title: Raiano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Raiano

title: Rapinium
description: Rapinium is located on the coast of Etruria between Centumcellae and Graviscae, at modern Bagni Sant'Agostino.

title: Reate
description: Reate (modern Rieti) was a major Sabine center that came to be captured by Manius Curius Dentatus in late third century B.C.

title: Regis Villa/Regae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Regis Villa/Regae

title: Respampani
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Respampani

title: Rosia Campus
description: A plain in the territory of the Sabines near Reate, reputed to have the most fertile soils in Italy.

title: Rostrata Villa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Rostrata Villa

title: Rusellae
description: An Etruscan city captured by Rome in 294 B.C., Rusellae's >2 mile circuit of megalithic walls represent an important early instance of stone fortification walling in the Italian peninsula.

title: Sabatinus lacus
description: A volcanic lake in Latium north of Rome (modern Lago di Bracciano).

title: Sabini
description: The Sabini (Sabines) were an Italic tribe of central Italy and belonged to the Osco-Umbrian language group. Their territory straddled parts of the modern regions of Lazio, Umbria, and the Abruzzo. Ancient writers connect them with Rome at the time of its foundation, as represented by the episode of the 'rape of the Sabine women' reported by various ancient authors.

title: Sacraria
description: A station on the Via Flaminia near Le Vene.

title: Saena
description: Saena was an Etruscan city that received a Roman colony (Saena Iulia) in the time of Augustus.

title: Sagrus (river)
description: A river of eastern Italy (modern Sangro).

title: S. Anatolia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 S. Anatolia

title: S. Casciano dei Bagni
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 S. Casciano dei Bagni

title: S. Erasmo di Cesi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 S. Erasmo di Cesi

title: San Giovenale
description: The archaeological remains of an Etruscan settlement were discovered at San Giovenale, close to Blera, Italy, by the Swedish Institute at Rome in the 1950s and 1960s. The ancient name of the site is unknown.

title: San Giuliano
description: An Etruscan settlement evidenced by its extensive, surviving necropolis, which now lies within the Parco Naturale Regionale Marturanum in the administrative territory of Barbarano Romano, Italy. Its modern name is transferred from a nearby medieval church.

title: S. Pier Maggiore
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A1 S. Pier Maggiore

title: S. Valentino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 S. Valentino

title: S. Vittore
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 S. Vittore

title: Sappinates?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Sappinates?

title: Sarsina
description: Sarsina was a town of the Umbri that was captured by Cornelius Scipio in 271 B.C. and was the birthplace of the Latin author Plautus. The necropolis at Sarsina has been extensively studied.

title: Sarteano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Sarteano

title: Sena (river)
description: The Nevola river.

title: Sena Gallica
description: Located at the mouth of the river Misa, Sena Gallica was founded by the Senonian Gauls in the fourth century B.C. and became the site of Rome's earliest Adriatic colony before 280 B.C. Pompeius Magnus destroyed the city in 82 B.C.

title: Senones
description: An ancient Gallic tribe that entered Italy after 400 BC and settled on the Adriatic coast from Forlì to Ancona, marking the so-called Ager Gallicus.

title: Sentinum
description: An ancient town in the region of Italy now known as Le Marche, Sentinum is perhaps best known for the pivotal Battle of Sentinum of the Third Samnite War that took place nearby in 295 BC.

title: Sepernates?
description: An ancient people of Etruria inhabiting the area around Nazzano Romano.

title: Septempeda
description: Septempeda was an ancient settlement of Picenum. Its Roman phase began as a conciliabulum in the third century B.C.

title: Sestinum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C1 Sestinum

title: Settefinestre
description: A Late Republican Roman slave-run villa owned by the senatorial family of the Volusii.

title: Soracte (mountain)
description: Soracte M. (Monte Soratte) is a mountain near Rome, Italy, the highest peak of which rises to 691 masl (2,267 ft). A site of ritual activity in antiquity, the mountain was sacred to Dis Pater.

title: Sorano
description: Sorano was a Villanovan and, later, Etruscan settlement.

title: Sorrina
description: Sorrina was a small Etruscan settlement on Viterbo's Colle di San Lorenzo, of which some traces remain. Epigraphic evidence also attests to a Roman municipium - Surrina Nova - that was likely located between Viterbo and Lake Bullicame.

title: Spoletium
description: An ancient city along the route of the Via Flaminia; an initial colony was established there in 241 BC.

title: Statonia
description: An ancient city of south Etruria.

title: Statulae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Statulae

title: Suana
description: Suana (Sovana) has Etruscan origins but later became a Roman municipium. In the fifth century A.D. it became an episcopal see.

title: Suasa
description: Suasa was the site of a Roman municipium in Umbria. It lies in the Piano Volpello along a road from Cales to Sena Gallica. Alaric razed the settlement in 409.

title: Succosa
description: Succosa was located between the Portus Cosanus and the Via Aurelia Antica to the north. It is mentioned in the Itineraries and located on the Tabula Peutingeriana. F.E. Brown suggests that Succosa, derived from "sub-Cosa", emerges in the first century B.C. following the decline of the hill-top colony. It may also be the "Respublica Cosanorum" that is mentioned in Severan inscriptions known from the hill-top town.

title: Superaequum
description: One of three towns of the Paeligni which possessed municipal rights.

title: Sutrium
description: An ancient settlement along the line of what would become the Roman Via Cassia and described by Livy, together with Nepet, as one of the keys to Etruria. A Latin colony was founded at the site after the fall of Veii.

title: Tadinae
description: Tadinae (Sant'Antonio della Rasina to the west of Gualdo Tadino) is an ancient municipium of Umbria and was a road station on the Via Flaminia.

title: Talamone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A3 Talamone

title: Tarchna/Tarquinii
description: An ancient city of Etruria and the leading city of the doudecim populi Etruriae, Tarquinia (called Tarch(u)na or Tarchna in Etruscan) was a major urban center of ancient Italy.

title: Teate
description: Originally named Teate Marrucinorum, Teate (modern Chieti) was the principal settlement of the Marrucini. Strabo attributes its origins to Arcadian Greeks.

title: Tessuinus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Tessuinus fl.

title: Tetricus M.
description: Tetricus M., a mountain group in Italy, part of the central Apennines.

title: Tifernum Mataurense
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C1 Tifernum Mataurense

title: Tifernum Tiberinum
description: An Umbrian hilltown in the floodplain of the Tiber river north of Perusia.

title: Tinea (river)
description: The Topino river in Umbria.

title: Tinna (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F2 Tinna fl.

title: Tiora Matiene
description: Tiora Matiene was the site of an ancient oracle of the god Mars.

title: Tirinus (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Tirinus fl.

title: Tolentinum
description: Tolentinum was a town of Picenum that is listed as having municipal status in the Liber Coloniarum.

title: Tolenus (river)
description: A river of Lazio and Abruzzo that is a tributary of the Velino.

title: Traianus?
description: A Roman villa that is typically associated with the emperor Trajan.

title: Trasumennus L.
description: Trasumennus L. (Lake Trasimeno) is the largest lake of the Italian peninsula and the site of a major engagement of the Second Punic War on June 21, 217 B.C.

title: Trea
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Trea

title: Trebiae
description: Trebiae was an ancient city of Umbria (regio IV) located near the line of the Via Flaminia.

title: Trebula Mutuesca
description: Trebula Mutuesca or Trebula Mutusca was one of two Sabine cities bearing the name Trebula.

title: Tres Tabernae
description: An ancient people, tribe, or cultural group. Located: near Trevi.

title: Trevignano
description: Trevignano Romano, located on the shores of Lake Bracciano, lies some 47 km from Rome. Archaeological evidence for Etruscan occupation, in the form of tombs dating to the eighth - sixth centuries B.C., has been discovered to the north of the modern town. A medieval castle was built there under Innocent III ca. 1200.

title: Truentus (river)
description: A river of Picenum that flows from its source on the Gran Sasso d'Italia to the Adriatic Sea at Porto d'Ascoli.

title: Tuder
description: Tuder, modern Todi, is an ancient city of Umbria. Its foundation likely occurred during the eighth/seventh centuries BC, although legendary traditions associate the site with the activities of Herakles.

title: Tuficum
description: Tuficum was an ancient city of Umbria located on the Aesis river. It became a municipium of the tribus Oufentina.

title: Tuscana
description: An ancient city that traced its legendary origins to Ascanius, son of Aeneas. The site became an important Etruscan mercantile center and eventually achieved Roman municipal status in 88 B.C.

title: Umbria (region)
description: The eponymous region of the Umbri, an ancient Italic people who spoke the Umbrian language. The physical geography of the landlocked region is hilly and dominated by the Appennine Mountains.

title: *Umbro (river)
description: The Ambra flows from the foot of Monte Luco to the Arno river.

title: Urbs Salvia
description: An ancient city of Regio V (Picenum) where a Roman colony was founded in the second century B.C.

title: Urvinum Hortense
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Urvinum Hortense

title: Urvinum Mataurense
description: Urvinum Mataurense (modern Urbino).

title: Vacchereccia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Vacchereccia

title: Vadimonis (lake)
description: A partially dry lake of ancient Etruria near Orte. The Romans were victorious in two battles fought against the Etruscans there (310 and 283 BC).

title: Velini L.
description: In the Roman period the Lacus Velinus was a larger body of water than the surviving remnant that is now known as Lake Piediluco. Modern intervention drained water away from the lake into the lower Nera River.

title: Velini L.
description: A lake formed by three rivers (Avens, Himella and Tolenus) in the territory of the Sabines.

title: Velzna/*Volsinii Veteres/Urbiventus
description: Volsinii Veteres was one of the most powerful and important cities of Etruria, as it was the location of the important federal sanctuary located at the Fanum Voltumnae.

title: Verucchio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C1 Verucchio

title: Vespasiae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Vespasiae

title: Vestini
description: The Vestini were an ancient tribe of Italy and lived in the southern part of the modern Abruzzo, between the Gran Sasso and the northern bank of the Aterno river. A major center was located at Pitinum.

title: Vettona
description: Vettona (modern Bettona) is an ancient settlement of Umbria located between Perusia and Mevania. Pliny the Elder lists it among the municipalities of Umbria, and it also numbered as one of the “xv Populi Umbriae".

title: Vicarello
description: A large, Roman imperial estate covering ca. 2,000 ha on the shores of Lake Bracciano. The name may derive from Vicus Aurelius, suggesting a connection with Marcus Aurelius.

title: Vicus Martis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Vicus Martis

title: Vicus Matrini
description: Vicus Matrini was a mansio along the Via Cassia, located between Sutri and Forum Cassi. The site's name is attested on the Peutinger Table.

title: Vicus Novus/Ad Novas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Vicus Novus/Ad Novas

title: Vignanello
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Vignanello

title: Villa S. Silvestro
description: The remains of a Republican temple podium now support a Christian church at Villa S. Silvestro in Umbria. The temple's podium likely dates, in its first phase, to the third century B.C.

title: Villalfonsina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 H4 Villalfonsina

title: Visentium
description: Visentium (Bisenzio) was an Etruscan settlement located on the shores of Lago di Bolsena. The site has yielded especially important evidence for Iron Age and Etruscan period burials.

title: Vittorito
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Vittorito

title: Volsiniensis L.
description: A volcanic lake of northern Latium formed by the collapse of the Vulsini volcano. Roman sources record volcanic activity at the site as late as the second century B.C.

title: Volsinii
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Volsinii

title: Volusii
description: A villa associated with the Volusii Saturnini built ca. 50 B.C.

title: Vomanus (river)
description: The Vomano river in Abruzzo flows into the Adriatic Sea.

title: Vulci
description: Vulci (originally Velch or Velx in Etruscan) was an Etruscan city 80 km northwest of Rome. Vulci was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae.

title: Zerninus? (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Zerninus? fl.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A1 unnamed aqueduct (Florentia)

title: Roman aqueduct at Arretium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 unnamed aqueduct (Arretium)

title: Untitled
description: An aqueduct located near the sulphurous springs at Aquae Tauri, northeast of Centumcellae.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 unnamed aqueduct (Spoletium)

title: Unnamed aqueduct near Amiternum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 unnamed aqueduct (near Amiternum)

title: Unnamed bridge
description: An unnamed ancient bridge located on the Via Aurelia over the Osa river at Telamon.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 unnamed bridge (at Ponte a Buriano)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 unnamed bridge (W Ponte a Buriano, over R. Arno)

title: Ponte di Pogi
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 unnamed bridge (over *Umbro fl., W Arretium at Pogi)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 unnamed bridge (near Aquae Apollinares? on road to Tarquinii at La Mola)

title: Ponte dell'Abbadia
description: An ancient bridge over the Fiora river (the ancient Armenta) near Vulci. Ancient name unknown.

title: Bridge on Via Cassia near *Volsinii Veteres
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C3

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 unnamed bridge group (on Via Cassia, near Sorrina)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Clodia, at Blera)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 unnamed bridge group (on Via Amerina, near Nepet)

title: Unnamed bridge over the Nar river near Terni
description: An ancient bridge near the *Via Curia.

title: Unnamed bridge
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1-C4 unnamed bridge (on Via Flaminia (20))

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 unnamed bridge (S Camerinum)

title: Ponte di Quintodecimo
description: The Ponte di Quintodecimo is located near Acquasanta Terme.

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A1 unnamed centuriation (Florentia)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A3 unnamed centuriation (Heba)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A4 unnamed centuriation (Cosa)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 unnamed centuriation (Hispellum)

title: Untitled
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E1 unnamed centuriation (Fanum Fortunae)

title: Unnamed centuriation near Potentia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F2 unnamed centuriation (Potentia)

title: Acerrae Vafriae
description: An ancient settlement of Umbria that is attested in Pliny the Elder but is recorded as a place that had vanished by his own day.

title: Ad Aquilam
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Aquilam

title: Ad Grecos
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Grecos

title: Ad Ioglandem
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Ioglandem

title: Ad Martis
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Martis

title: Ad Pirum Filumeni/Ad Pirum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Pirum (Filumeni)

title: Ad Mensulas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Mensulas

title: Ad Nonas
description: Ad Nonas is the name of a now unlocated road station near Cosa; the name is attested in the Peutinger Table.

title: Ad Novas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Novas

title: Ad Sextum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ad Sextum

title: Ad Tine Recine
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated ‘Ad Tine Recine’

title: Aequum Faliscum
description: A settlement along the Via Flaminia, now unlocated. Strabo places it between Otricoli and Rome; the possibility must be allowed that it is taken to the identical with Falerii.

title: Alfaterni
description: An ancient people whose territory is unlocated

title: Ametinum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Ametinum

title: Angelum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Angelum

title: Anguillarius
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated *Anguillarius

title: Batia/Vatia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated ‘Batia’/‘Vatia’

title: Biturgia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 unlocated Biturgia

title: Boustagalloron

description: A now-unlocated pagus in the territory of the Sabines. Septem Aquae was known for springs and lakes that were popular with tourists. Cicero visited the area in 54 B.C.

title: Severus (mountain)
description: A mountain probably near Mt. Tetricus.

title: Solinates

title: Subertani

title: Suillates
description: The Suillates were an ancient people of Umbria. Their territory is now unlocated.

title: Tarinates

title: Testruna
