title: Acqua Acetosa
description: A settlement along the Via Laurentina that has yielded significant evidence for protohistoric occupation, including funereal evidence of the eighth and seventh centuries B.C.

title: Acquafredda
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Acquafredda

title: Ad Aquas Salvias
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Ad Aquas Salvias

title: Ad Bivium
description: A statio in Latium located at the intersection of the Via Latina and the Via Labicana, near the modern Valmontone.

title: Ad Decimum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Ad Decimum

title: Ad Decimum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ad Decimum

title: Ad Duas Lauros
description: The toponym 'Ad Duas Lauros' refers to a large imperial property at the third mile of the Via Labicana and today comprised of the archaeological park of Centocelle. The site is mentioned in the Liber Pontificalis as that of a large imperial villa in which Helena, mother of Constantine I, lived. Archaeological work conducted in the late 1990s identified the remains of substantial Republican period villas in the same area, with evidence of both elite dwellings and viticulture. The villas identified are the Villa della Piscina and the Villa Ad Duas Lauros.

title: Ad Gallinas Albas
description: Ad Gallinas Albas refers to a location along the Via Flaminia.

title: Ad Nonum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ad Nonum

title: Ad Nonum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ad Nonum (1)

title: Ad Pictas
description: Ad Pictas is a road station east of Rome, known mostly for its role in Sulla's march on Rome in 88 B.C. The precise location of the statio continues to be debated.

title: Ad Quintanas
description: Ad Quintanas is the name of a road station on the Via Labicana.

title: Ad Sextum
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Ad Sextum

title: Ad Sponsas
description: Ad Sponsas was a road station on the Via Appia.

title: Ad Statuas
description: Ad Statuas was a road station on the Via Labicana located east of Rome.

title: Ad Turres
description: Ad Turres was located on the Via Aurelia some 10 miles from Lorium and 12 miles from Pyrgi.

title: Adriano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Adriano

title: Aeflanus (mountain)
description: Colle Ripoli-Monte S. Angelo.

title: Aefula
description: Aefula was an ancient settlement of Latium that had disappeared by the time of Pliny the Elder, although the cult of Bona Dea there continued to flourish.

title: Aequi
description: The Aequi were an ancient Italic tribe of northeast Latium in the first millennium BC.

title: Afilae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 E2 Afilae

title: Alba Longa?
description: Alba Longa, located in the Alban Hills southeast of Rome, was the chief city and founder of the Latin League. Conflict with Rome caused Alba's destruction in the seventh century B.C. The legendary history of Romulus and Remus connects them to the royal lineage of the city.

title: Albanus L.
description: A volcanic lake in ancient Latium at the foot of Albanus Mons, Albanus Lacus (Alban Lake) is connected with the site of the city of Alba Longa and, later, with imperial properties of the Flavian house.

title: Albanus M.
description: The second highest summit of the Alban Hills, Mons Albanus is an extinct volcano with an elevation of 950 m (3,117 ft). In the middle of the first millennium B.C. there may have been volcanic activity as noted by the historian Livy. The mountain was sacred for Latin peoples who held important festivals there and a major shrine to Iuppiter Latiaris stands on the mountain top.

title: Albuccione
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Albuccione

title: Albunea (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 Albunea fl.

title: Algidus
description: An ancient settlement of Latium located in the territory of the Aequi.

title: Algidus (mountain)
description: Algidus (mons) refers to the eastern rim of the dormant Alban volcano in the Alban Hills of central Italy, known today as  Monte Artemisio.

title: Alsium
description: Alsium served as a port for Caere, together with Fregenae.

title: L’Altare
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 L’Altare

title: Anagnia
description: Anagnia was a Hernican town that sided with Rome against the Volscians and later became civitas sine suffragio.

title: Anio (river)
description: The Anio river (modern Aniene) is a river of northern Latium.

title: Annunziatella
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Annunziatella

title: Antemnae
description: Antemnae is an ancient Latin settlement located north of Rome near the point where the Anio and Tiber rivers intersect. Connected with Rome's early history, Antemnae was involved in episodes such as the 'Rape of the Sabine Women' and Romulus is said to have celebrated a triumph over the Antemnates in 752 BC.

title: Antium
description: Antium ranked as one of the most important and most powerful centers of Latium and was captured by Rome at the close of the Latin War in the fourth century B.C. Imperial Antium was well known for a number of coastal villas.

title: Villa degli Antonini
description: The so-called 'Villa of the Antonines', located near Genzano di Roma in the Alban Hills, lies just south of the Via Appia between the road's 18th and 19th milestones.

title: Aquae Albulae
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Aquae Albulae

title: Aquae Albulae
description: A group of springs located west of Tibur (modern Tivoli). The main spring, known as Lago della Regina, preserves traces of an ancient Roman bath.

title: Arcinazzo
description: An imperial villa of the Trajanic and Hadrianic periods located on the Altipiani di Arcinazzo.

title: Ardea
description: Ardea was an ancient settlement of the Rutuli in Latium.

title: Aricia
description: Aricia is an ancient Latin settlement and a member of the Latin League.

title: Artena
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Artena

title: Astura (river)
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D4 Astura fl.

title: Baebiana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 Baebiana

title: Il Barco
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Il Barco

title: Il Barco
description: The so-called "Barco Borghese" is an archaeological site located in Monte Porzio Catone (Roma) in Italy. This multiperiod site began as a Roman terracing or substructure, perhaps originally meant to support a villa (basis villae). Subsequent modification and reuse converted the Roman structure into a "barco", an enclosure for animal hunts.

title: Bel Poggio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Bel Poggio

title: Bovillae
description: A town of ancient Latium along the line of the Via Appia, Bovillae is traditionally considered to be a colony of Alba Longa and was one of the thirty cities of the Latin League.

title: Bruto e Pisoni
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Bruto e Pisoni

title: Buglioncino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 Buglioncino

title: Buon Riposo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 Buon Riposo

title: Cabum?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Cabum?

title: Caere
description: Caere (also known as Cisra or Cerveteri) was a major Etruscan polis located ca. 50 km north-northwest of Rome in southern Etruria.

title: Calepodius
description: A Christian catacomb originally containing the tombs of Pope Callixtus I and Pope Julius I, along with that of the eponymous Saint Calepodius.

title: Campo del Fico
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 Campo del Fico

title: Campoverde
description: Campoverde (Lazio) lies some 60 km south of Rome. In 1977-1978 a quantity of votive material was recovered from a body of water known as the "Laghetto del Monsignore". This spring-fed body of water was interpreted as an open-air votive depository.

title: Campus Martius
description: The Campus Martius or "field of Mars" is the name given to the level ground between the slopes of the Capitoline, the Quirinal, and Pincian hills, and the Tiber river.

title: Capannacce
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Capannacce

title: Capitolium
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Capitolium

title: Cappellette
description: The site of a villa located between Frascati and Monte Porzio Catone. It is associated with Matidia Augusta on account of an inscribed fistula discovered there in 1888.

title: I Cappuccini
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 I Cappuccini

title: Careiae
description: An ancient town on the Via Clodia.

title: Casal Rotondo
description: A Roman tomb that supports a Medieval farmhouse (casale) at the sixth mile of the Via Appia. The tomb originally dates ca. 30 BC; it was a large, circular tomb with a diameter of approximately 35 m.

title: Casale del Cavaliere
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Casale del Cavaliere

title: Casale di Gregna
description: A villa at the seventh mile of the Via Latina.

title: Casale Martellona
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Casale Martellona

title: Casale Morena
description: A villa located at the eighth mile of the ancient Via Latina. The villa was first built in the first century B.C. and continued in use until the fourth century. During its life span there were several phases of architectural modification and expansion.

title: Casali
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Casali

title: Casali Vitriano
description: T. Ashby notes the presence of a villa platform to the west of the "upper Casale Vitriano". This platform seems to be a terrace at least 34 m in length.

title: Case Nuove 1
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Case Nuove 1

title: Case Nuove 2
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Case Nuove 2

title: Case Rosse
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Case Rosse

title: Cassio
description: A villa in Tibur that has been incorrectly linked to Gaius Cassius Longinus. In the eighteenth century, the site produced a cache of Egyptianizing sculpture that likely dates to the reign of Hadrian and is now held in the Vatican Museums.

title: Castel Campanile
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 Castel Campanile

title: Le Castella
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Le Castella

title: Castel Madama
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Castel Madama

title: Castelporziano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 Castelporziano

title: Castel Savello
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 Castel Savello

title: Castra Albana
description: Castra Albana was a permanent, fortified camp of the Legio II Parthica constructed during the Severan period.

title: Castrimoenium
description: A Latin settlement that became a Roman municipium.

title: La Cecchina
description: The so-called "Torraccio della Cecchina" is a Roman funereal monument dating to the second century A.D. It is located at the ninth kilometer of the modern Via Nomentana.

title: Centroni
description: The Villa dei Centroni, located on the modern via Anagnina, lay at the ninth mile of the ancient via Latina. It dates from the first century B.C. onward.

title: Ceres et Faustina, T.
description: The Roman temple dedicated to Ceres and Faustina received patronage from Herodes Atticus. Its remains were eventually repurposed in the construction of the church of Sant'Urbano.

title: Cervara 1
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Cervara 1

title: Cervara 2
description: In the vicinity of Tor Cervara are anio tuff (tufo d'Aniene) quarries.

title: Cessati Spiriti
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Cessati Spiriti

title: Ciciliano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Ciciliano

title: Cimitero Maggiore
description: A major Roman necropolis and catacomb along the Via Nomentana.

title: Cinecittà
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Cinecittà

title: Civitana
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Civitana

title: Clodio
description: Cicero describes the villa of Publius Clodius Pulcher as being located at the thirteenth mile of the Via Appia near Bovillae.

title: Collatia
description: Collatia was an ancient city of Latium located between Gabii and the Anio fl. A colony of Alba Longa, Collatia was one of the most ancient cities of Latium. Subjugated by Rome under the Tarquins, Collatia would decline during the Republican period and numbers among the lost Latin cities by the accounting of Pliny the Elder.

title: Colle Gentile
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Colle Gentile

title: Colle Medico
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Colle Medico

title: Colle Monitola
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Colle Monitola

title: Colle Nocello
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Colle Nocello

title: Colle Rosa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Colle Rosa

title: Colle Rotondo
description: Colle Rotondo was the site of a prehistoric settlement inhabited from the Bronze Age until the early Iron Age.

title: Colle Tasso
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Colle Tasso

title: Colle Vitriano
description: Colle Vitriano is the site of a Roman villa supported on two artificial terraces that utilize megalithic walling in the polygonal masonry technique as well as caementicium.

title: La Colombella
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 La Colombella

title: Compitum
description: A multi-period sanctuary near Anagnia.

title: Cora
description: A Latin center in the Monti Lepini that was already a Roman municipium by 211 B.C.

title: Corniculum
description: An ancient town of Latium connected with the origins of Serivus Tullius.

title: Corzano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Corzano

title: Cremera (river)
description: The Cremera is a small stream in Lazio that played a role in the fourth century BC war between Rome and the Etruscan city-state of Veii.

title: Crepaddosso
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Crepaddosso

title: Crustumerium
description: An ancient town of Latium located at the headwaters of the Allia river, very close to the territory of the Sabines, Crustumerium figures in Rome's early history. The Romans conquered the site in 500 B.C. and formed the tribus Crustumina or Clustumina in 471 B.C.

title: Dea Dia, T.
description: The Arval Brethren cultivated the cult of the Dea Dia.

title: Diana, T.
description: A site sacred to Diana near Lake Nemi, comprised of a Tuscan-style sanctuary and a sacred grove.

title: Ficana
description: An ancient city of Latium that was said to have been conquered by Ancus Marcius, Ficana was located near the eleventh mile of the Via Ostiensis. Excavation at the site has produced important evidence for the urban center beginning from the eighth century BC. Pliny the Elder mentions Ficana as one of the lost cities of Latium.

title: Ficulea
description: Ficulea was an ancient city of Latium situated between Rome and Nomentum.

title: Fidenae
description: Fidenae was an ancient city of Latium.

title: Forte Tiburtina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Forte Tiburtina

title: Fortis Fortuna, T.
description: A sanctuary of Fors Fortuna in Trastevere. Varro ascribes its foundation to Servius Tullius.

title: Fortuna Muliebris, T.
description: A sanctuary dedicated to Fortuna Muliebris along the Via Latina. Tradition holds that it was dedicated in 487 B.C.

title: Forum Appii
description: An ancient road station on the Via Appia located 69 km southeast of Rome.

title: Fosso della Crescenza
description: Ward-Perkins identified the archaeological site at Fosso della Crescenza during the South Etruria Survey. Excavations of a Iulio-Claudian mausoleum were undertaken in 1962. Additional excavation revealed portions of the Via Veientana. Post-excavation work did not occur until the 1980s, by which time Fentress 1983 notes that the the archaeological landscape had been largely eradicated by the burgeoning growth of suburban Rome.

title: Frascati
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Frascati

title: Fregenae
description: An ancient town of Etruria, Fregenae was located between Alsium and the mouth of the river Tiber.

title: Gabii
description: An ancient Latin city located on the line of the Republican Via Praenestina connecting Rome to Praeneste. Gabii is allied to Rome from an early date and flourished during the archaic period, declining by the time of Augustus.

title: Giordani
description: A fourth century A.D. catacomb along the via Salaria at Rome.

title: La Giostra
description: A fortified site on the Via Appia dating to the Republican period.

title: Villa Gordiani
description: A third century A.D. villa complex along the Via Praenestina connected with Gordian I, Gordian II, and Gordian III.

title: Grotta del Mortale
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Grotta del Mortale

title: Grotta di Paris
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Grotta di Paris

title: Grotta Papale
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Grotta Papale

title: Grottaferrata
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Grottaferrata

title: Grottarossa
description: Grottarossa is located at the intersection of key roadways in northern suburbium of Rome, lying along the Via Flaminia as well as at the point where the Via Veientana separated from the Via Cassia and thereby connected Rome with Veii. There is archaeological evidence for tombs, both built tombs and rock-cut tombs in the exposed tuff escarpments, as well as villas.

title: Grotta Oscura
description: The quarries at Grotta Oscura were an important source of high quality tuff located in the territory of Veii.

title: Hernici
description: The Hernici (Hernicans) were an Italic tribe of first millennium B.C. Latium. Their territory was bounded by the Trerus fl. (Sacco) and the Lacus Fucinus (Fucine Lake).

title: Inviolata
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Inviolata

title: Isola Sacra
description: An extensive second and third century A.D. necropolis located between the city of Ostia and Portus.

title: Iuppiter Latiaris, T.
description: An important Latial sanctuary of Iuppiter located on Mons Albanus (modern Monte Cavo).

title: Iuppiter?, T.
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Iuppiter?, T.

title: Labicum
description: Originally a member of the Latin League, the city of Labicum was taken by the Romans ca. 418 B.C. By the time of Augustus, the site was almost certainly deserted and its precise location remains debated today.

title: Ladispoli
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 A2 Ladispoli

title: Laghetto di Colonna
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Laghetto di Colonna

title: Lamnae/Ad Lam(i)nas
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C1 Lamnae/Ad Lam(i)nas

title: Lanuvium
description: Lanuvium was an important city of Latium located south of the Alban Hills. After opposing Rome at the battle of Aricia (504 B.C.) and Lake Regillus (496 B.C.), Lanuvium was captured by the Romans in 338 B.C.

title: Largo Preneste
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Largo Preneste

title: Latium Vetus (region)
description: Latium Vetus is an historical region of Italy. Latium Vetus begins south of the Tiber river and extends as far as Circeo, at which point the boundary of Latium Adiectum is reached.

title: Laurentes
description: Laurentum was an ancient city of Latium located some 16 miles from Rome, between Ostia and Lavinium. Its precise location can no longer be determined. In Rome's legendary history Laurentum is the site of king Latinus' dwelling.

title: Lavinium
description: An ancient city of Latium on the Numicus river that was founded, according to Virgil, by Aeneas.

title: Lepinus (mountain)
description: Lepinus M., a mountain range of central Italy that belongs to the Anti-Apennines.

title: Lolli Paolini
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Lolli Paolini

title: Lorium
description: An ancient town on the Via Aurelia.

title: Lucio Vero
description: A Roman villa located at Acquatraversa on the Via Cassia that is frequently attributed to Lucius Verus.

title: Lucullo
description: Plutarch describes a villa owned by Lucullus near Tusculum.

title: Magliana Vecchia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Magliana Vecchia

title: Marco Pedonio
description: The villa of Marcus Pedonius.

title: Marina di S. Nicola
description: Marina di S. Nicola is located close to Alsium.

title: Marmenia
description: The Domus Marmeniae is a villa located on the Via Appia near the fourth milestone. The villa grounds hosted a pagan necropolis and tradition holds that the matrona, Marmenia, relocated the body of St. Urban to a mausoleum built on the grounds.

title: Mondragone
description: A Renaissance villa (Villa Mondragone) was built atop the platform of a Roman villa dating to the first century B.C.

title: Monte del Grano
description: Monte del Grano is a popular name that was assigned to a mausoleum once thought to belong to Alexander Severus, although that assignation is no longer supported. The archaeological remains are now part of the Parco XVII Aprile 1944.

title: Monte dell'Oro
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Monte dell'Oro

title: Montedoro
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Montedoro

title: Monteroni
description: Monteroni, near Ladispoli, is the site of an Etruscan necropolis.

title: Monte Tosto
description: An Etruscan and Roman site lying 4 km to the west of Caere along the monumental road leading to Pyrgi. Until the early 1960s, the site was known for the monumental tumulus that Mengarelli had excavated in the 1920s. Subsequent excavation revealed other evidence, including an elite compound that served as a sanctuary.

title: Monteverde
description: The hill of Monteverde, a part of the Ianiculum hill to the west of the Tiber river, was a source of a brown, lithoid tuff (tufo di Monteverde) that was quarried for use as a building material from the second century BC.

title: Montioni
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Montioni

title: Munazio Planco
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Munazio Planco

title: Muraccio dell’Omo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Muraccio dell’Omo

title: Naumachia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Naumachia

title: Nemorensis (lake)
description: Nemorensis Lacus (modern Lake Nemi) is a small, volcanic lake in Latium located south of Rome. The lake is known for its adjacent sanctuary of the goddess Diana and for a number of sunken Roman ships of the first century AD that were recovered from it.

title: Nettuno
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C4 Nettuno

title: Nomentum
description: The Latin town of Nomentum and Rome were linked by means of the Via Nomentana. In Livy's history the town, a member of the Latin League, is captured by Lucius Tarquinius Priscus. Nomentum was one of a number of towns captured by Tarquinius. The Romans granted the town civitas sine suffragio after 338 B.C.

title: Norba
description: Norba, located in the Monti Lepini, was a member of the Latin League (ca. 499 B.C.) and became a Latin colony ca. 492 B.C. The city was destroyed in the early first century B.C.

title: Numicus (river)
description: The Numicus flumen was a river of Latium connected with the legendary history of Aeneas. Modern Fosso di Pratica in Italy.

title: Villa of the Octavii
description: The archaeological remains of a Roman villa on the hill of San Cesareo are speculatively identified as belonging to the gens Octavia, according to Della Portella 2004 op. cit.

title: Opimiano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Opimiano

title: Ospedale di S. Camillo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Ospedale di S. Camillo

title: Osteria dell’Osa
description: The site of a major Iron Age necropolis (Latial chronology) composed of over 600 burials.

title: Ostia
description: The port city of ancient Rome located at the mouth of the river Tiber.

title: Pedum?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Pedum?

title: Pianabella
description: A large Christian basilica discovered in 1976 several hundred meters southeast of the Porta Laurentina of Ostia. The original phase dates to the end of the fourth century A.D.

title: Pianelle
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Pianelle

title: Pietra Papa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Pietra Papa

title: Pietralata
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Pietralata

title: Piscina Torta
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 Piscina Torta

title: Plinio
description: The so-called villa of Pliny the Younger, also known as the Villa delle Palombara. The villa's first phases date to the Iulio-Claudian period. It continues in use, and continues to undergo modifications, through the second century A.D.

title: Pometia
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Pometia

title: Pompeo
description: A villa attributed to Cnaeus Pompeius.

title: Pons Mulvius
description: Pons Mulvius (the Milvian Bridge) is a Roman bridge over the Tiber river. The original phase of the bridge dates to the consulship of Gaius Claudius Nero in 206 B.C. The bridge is most famous as the site of a decisive battle between Maxentius and Constantine I fought in A.D. 312.

title: Ponte di Tuscolo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ponte di Tuscolo

title: Ponte Mammolo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ponte Mammolo

title: Ponte Salario
description: The Ponte Salario is a Medieval bridge with Roman origins. It is located at the point where the Via Salaria crosses the Anio, about 3 km north of the Colline Gate.

title: Portus
description: The great ancient maritime port of Rome, located on the right-hand bank of the Tiber river.

title: Praeneste
description: An ancient city of central Italy, the eighth and seventh century B.C. origins of which demonstrate high-level trade contact with the Eastern Mediterranean world. The city withdrew from the Latin League (499 B.C.) and opposed Rome in the Latin war; Cincinnatus eventually subdued Praeneste. Sulla founded a new colony there in the first century B.C.

title: Prati Fiscali
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Prati Fiscali

title: Prima Porta
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B1 Prima Porta

title: Priscilla
description: A Christian catacomb within an ancient quarry on the Via Salaria that was in use from the second until the fourth centuries AD. The Catacomb of Priscilla was likely named for Priscilla, a member of the gens Acilia, and contains the oldest known Marian painting (third century AD).

title: Quadraro
description: A Roman villa near the line of the Aqua Claudia located in the modern Via del Quadraro. The villa is dated to the first century B.C. or first century A.D. Following remodelling in the third century, the villa's occupation ends in the fourth century.

title: Quintilii
description: A suburban villa built by Sextus Quintilius Maximus and Sextus Quintilius Condianus (consuls in A.D. 151).

title: Quintilio Varo
description: A villa located near the sanctuary of Madonna di Quintiliolo (Tivoli) that is traditionally associated with Quintilius Varus. The remains of the basis villae may date as early as the third century B.C.

title: Redicolo
description: The Tomb of Annia Regilla (vix. A.D. 125-160), the wife of Herodes Atticus. The tomb is also erroneously known as the "Temple of the God Rediculum" and was used in the Middle Ages as a hay barn.

title: Regillus? L.
description: An ancient lake in Latium that was the site of a Roman military victory in 496 BC; the precise location of the lake cannot be determined, although some scholars place its location at Pantano Secco near Frascati, Italy.

title: Robigo?, T.
description: The sanctuary of the god Robigus, located at the sixth mile of the Via Cassia. The Romans celebrated the festival of Robigalia on 25 April.

title: Roma
description: The capital of the Roman Republic and Empire.

title: La Rustica
description: La Rustica was a Latin site located along the Via Collatina.

title: Sabina
description: The one-time territory of the ancient Sabine people of central Italy.

title: Sacer Mons
description: Sacer Mons is a hill on the banks of the Anio river and is connected, traditionally, with the episode of the secession of the Roman plebs of 494 BC.

title: Sacro Speco
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 E2 Sacro Speco

title: Salinae
description: Salt pans located to the east of Ostia and to the north-east of Portus around the Tiber river estuary.

title: Salone
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Salone

title: S. Agapito
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 S. Agapito

title: S. Agata
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 S. Agata

title: S. Agnese
description: A titular church on the Via Nomentana, S. Agnese houses the remains of the eponymous saint. The present church was built by Pope Honorius I in the seventh century AD, on the site of a fourth century basilica built by Constantine I.

title: S. Alessandro
description: The basilica and catacombs of S. Alessandro are located at the seventh milestone of the Via Nomentana.

title: S. Antonio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 S. Antonio

title: S. Callisto
description: A large catacomb on the Via Appia south of Rome notable especially for its so-called 'Crypt of the Popes'. The catacomb covers approximately 15 hectares.

title: S. Carlo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 S. Carlo

title: S. Cesareo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 S. Cesareo

title: S. Clemens
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 E2 S. Clemens

title: S. Ermete
description: S. Ermete is the site of a Paleochristian basilica and catacomb; the catacombs are also referred to as the Catacombs of Bassilla, and both names occur in the documentary sources.

title: S. Felicita
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 S. Felicita

title: S. Ippolito
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 S. Ippolito

title: S. Laurentius
description: The Papal Basilica of Saint Lawrence outside the Walls (Basilica Papale di San Lorenzo fuori le Mura) is one of the Seven Pilgrim Churches of Rome. The basilica serves as the shrine and tomb dedicated to Saint Lawrence and its earliest phases likely belong to the fourth century AD.

title: S. Lidano
description: The so-called "Archi di San Lidano" are the remains of a Roman stone bridge in the Pontine plain, near the modern locality of Sezze Scalo. The bridge likely dates originally to the second century B.C.

title: SS. Marcellino e Pietro
description: The church of Saints Marcellinus and Peter is a Roman Catholic church located on the Via Merulana in Rome. Pope Siricius built the original church in the fourth century A.D., close to the catacombs of Marcellinus and Peter. The relics of the saints were deposited in the church in 1256.

title: S. Maria di Galeria
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B1 S. Maria di Galeria

title: S. Martino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 S. Martino

title: S. Passera
description: S. Passera is a Christian church on the Tiber river in Rome, opposite the Basilica of Saint Paul Outside the Walls. The current church dates to the ninth century and incorporated the remains of a Roman tomb. The church is traditionally connected to a community of local miners.

title: S. Paulus
description: One of Rome's four major papal basilicae, S. Paulus was founded by Constantine I in the early fourth century A.D. and expanded by Valentinian I in the 370s.

title: S. Petrus
description: The Basilica of St. Peter in Vatican City; currently a Renaissance edifice standing on the site of Old St. Peter's Basilica, a church built by Constantine I between AD 319 and 333. The holy site is located on the Mons Vaticanus in connection with the purported site of the burial of the Christian Saint Peter. (cited: BAtlas 43 B2 S. Petrus)

title: S. Rufina
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 S. Rufina

title: S. Scholastica
description: A convent founded within the area of the Villa Neronis (BAtlas 43 E2 S. Scholastica)

title: S. Sebastianus
description: S. Sebastianus (San Sebastiano fuori le mura) is a Christian basilica outside the walls of Rome; the earliest phase belongs to the fourth century AD.

title: S. Sinforosa
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 S. Sinforosa

title: S. Valentino
description: A Christian catacomb along the Via Flaminia dedicated to S. Valentino.

title: S. Vincenzo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D1 S. Vincenzo

title: Satricum
description: An ancient settlement on the right bank of the river Astura, Satricum has a mixed heritage of Latins and Volscians. In 499 B.C. Satricum was a member of the Latin League, but was under Volscian control in 488 B.C. The site is noted for its sanctuary of Mater Matuta.

title: Saxa Rubra
description: Saxa Rubra (modern Grottarossa) is the name of a road station on the Via Flaminia nine Roman miles from the center of ancient Rome. It was at Saxa Rubra that Constantine I defeated Maxentius in A.D. 312.

title: Scalzacane
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Scalzacane

title: Sep. C. Maenius Bassus
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D1 Sep. C. Maenius Bassus

title: Mausoleum of Caecilia Metella
description: A tomb on the Via Appia south of Rome belonging to Caecilia Metella, a daughter of Metellus Creticus. She was born ca. 100 BC. In 1303 the tomb was incorporated into the Castrum Caetani, serving as the main tower of the fortification.

title: Sep. Geta
description: A Roman tomb along the Via Appia that is traditionally believed to be that of Publius Septimius Geta, the younger son of Septimius Severus.

title: Sep. Plautii
description: The Mausoleum of Plautii dates to the first century B.C.

title: Serrone di Bove
description: The small hill known as "Il Poggio di Serrone di Bove" is located in the hinterland of ancient Norba and was the site of settlement activity. Architectural remains on the site include those of a polygonal masonry substruction or platform as well as an ancient roadway.

title: Setia
description: A Volscian settlement of the fifth century B.C. that became a Latin colony in 382 B.C.

title: Sette Bassi
description: A large, suburban villa complex on the Via Tuscolana. The villa was in use from the reign of Antoninus Pius until the fourth century A.D.

title: Settebagni
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Settebagni

title: Settecamini
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Settecamini

title: Signia
description: A city of Latium Adjectum established as a Latin colony ca. 494 B.C.

title: Simbruina Stagna
description: A series of three artificial lakes created along the river Anio.

title: Solforata
description: At Solforata along the Via Ardeatina activity related to the extraction of sulfur has been identified.

title: La Storta
description: A station on the Via Cassia attested in an inscription dated to A.D. 379-383.

title: Sublanuvio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 Sublanuvio

title: Sublaqueum
description: An ancient settlement, located at modern Subiaco in Italy, Sublaqueum was located in the territory of the Aequi that was annexed by Rome in 304 B.C.

title: Tiberis (river)
description: The Tiber river is the third-longest river of the Italian peninsula, flowing 406 km (252 mi) from the Apennine Mountains to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

title: Tibur
description: A Sabine town, 30 km east-north-east of Rome, Tibur was the seat of the Tiburtine Sibyl.

title: Tomba degli Orazi e Curiazi
description: A Roman tomb near Albano Laziale connected in tradition with the story of the contest between the Horatii and Curiatii.

title: Tomba di Marco Plauzio Lucano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Tomba di Marco Plauzio Lucano

title: Tomb of Vibius Marianus
description: An imperial Roman tomb of Publius Vibius Marianus, erroneously identified as the Tomba di Nerone (Tomb of Nero) by G. B. Piranesi.

title: Il Tondo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Il Tondo

title: Tor Angela
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Tor Angela

title: Tor de’ Cenci
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Tor de’ Cenci

title: Tor Marancia
description: The modern toponym Tor Marancia is claimed to derive from the Praedium Amaranthianus, a villa belonging to the second-century A.D. freedman Amaranthus.

title: Tor Paterno
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 Tor Paterno

title: Torraccia dell’Inviolata
description: A Roman tomb, known as the Torraccia dell’Inviolata. This tomb has a cruciform plan that is inscribed within a circular structure. Based on masonry techniques the tomb dates to the later first or second century.

title: Il Torraccio
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Il Torraccio

title: Il Torraccio
description: A circular mausoleum dating to the Late Republican period along the Via Praenestina.

title: Il Torraccio
description: The so-called "Il Torraccio (1)" is the cement core of a Roman tomb located at the twelfth milestone of the Via Appia Nuova, on the left side.

title: Torre Caldara
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C4 Torre Caldara

title: Torre del Monumento
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C4 Torre del Monumento

title: Torre del Padiglione
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 Torre del Padiglione

title: Torre di Palidoro
description: A coastal Roman villa that is succeeded by a Medieval coastal tower.

title: Torre Pascolaro (settlement)
description: A Final Bronze Age settlement of four to five hectares in South Etruria.

title: Torre S. Angelo
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Torre S. Angelo

title: Torre Sessano
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Torre Sessano

title: Il Torrino
description: An Iron Age settlement in Latium.

title: Trebula Suffenas
description: An ancient Sabine city.

title: Tredici Altari
description: A Latin federal sanctuary at Lavinium, consisting of a series of altars that range in date from the sixth to the second century BC and a sacred site (or heroon) connected with the hero Aeneas.

title: Trerus/Tolerus (river)
description: A river of central Italy and a right tributary of the Liris.

title: Tres Tabernae
description: A statio at the point where the Via Appia crosses the Via Ninfina.

title: Troia?
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 Troia?

title: Tusculum
description: Tusculum was a Latin city of the Alban Hills in central Italy. After 381 BC Tusculum became the first "municipium cum suffragio".

title: Valerio Messala Corvino
description: An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Valerio Messala Corvino

title: Valvisciolo
description: An Iron Age settlement and necropolis located in the Monti Lepini near the abbey of Valvisciolo, characterized by polygonal masonry terrace walls. While the ancient name of the site is unknown, various proposals have been raised, including Sulmo (Savignoni, Mengarelli) and Pometia (Ogilvie). The settlement corresponds to the Latial II B phase and occupation ends ca. the late sixth century B.C.

title: Varia
description: Varia (modern Vicovaro) was a settlement of the Sabines.

title: Veii
description: An important city of South Etruria located north-northwest of Rome, Veii was eventually sacked by the Romans in 396 B.C. The ancient city covered some 180 ha.

title: Velitrae
description: Velitrae (modern Velletri) was an ancient Volscian settlement. In the Roman Republican period, Velitrae was attacked by Marcus Furius Camillus (379 B.C.) and again by Cincinnatus (377 B.C.); the Romans controlled the site by 365 B.C. The gens Octavia hailed from the city and a youthful Octavian spent time there.

title: Agora of Athens
description: The marketplace of the ancient city of Athens in Greece.

title: Stoa of Zeus (Eleutherios)
description: The Stoa of Zeus Eleutherios was built on the west side of the Agora of Athens between 430-425 BC, in honor of Zeus "of Freedom"; the stoa, Doric in its external order, housed the shields of Athenians who had died fighting for the city.

title: Theater of Dionysus Eleuthereus
description: Theatre on the south slope of the Acropolis in Athens.

title: Caerleon Roman amphitheatre
description: Amphitheatre of the legionary fortress at Caerleon

title: Altar of Hieron II
description: A monumental altar built around the third century B.C. that was probably dedicated to Zeus Eleutherios. Remains of the altar are located in the archaeological area of Neapolis in Syracuse, Sicily.

title: Sanctuary of Monte Sant'Angelo
description: A Catholic sanctuary on Mount Gargano, in northern Apulia, Italy. Listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011.

title: Santa Sofia
description: A Longobard church in Benevento, Italy, listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011.

title: Tchogha Zanbil
description: An ancient Elamite complex founded ca. 1250 BC by the king Untash-Napirisha. Tchogha Zanbil was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 1979.

title: House of Meleager
description: The so-called "House of Meleager" (VI.9.2) is a domus in Pompeii of the "Samnite" type that was excavated first in 1829, then again in 1836 and 1966. The interior boasts rich painted decoration corresponding to Mau's first, third, and fourth styles.

title: Thodasa
description: An unlocated community which was close to, and eventually entered into sympolitiea with, Kildara.

title: Banbhore
description: Banbhore is located 65 km east of Karachi. Its sequence of occupation stretches from the first century BC to the thirteenth century AD.

title: Great Dam of Ma'rib
description: The Great Dam of Ma'rib dates originally to the eighth century BC and was connected with the Sabaean and Himyarite kingdoms around Ma'rib.

title: Temple of Zeus Lepsinos at Euromus
description: The Temple of Zeus Lepsinos at Euromus is located southeast of the ancient settlement. The well-preserved Corinthian temple dates to the reign of Hadrian.

title: Via Triumphalis necropolis
description: A segment of an imperial necropolis preserved along a portion of a consular road on the Vatican Hill. The Via Triumphalis necropolis was uncovered during the construction of a parking structure in the Via del Pellegrino.

title: Monjukli Depe
description: Village in southern Turkmenistan located near the Altyn Depe site, inhabited in the late Neolithic and Aeneolithic periods. The finds at the site have been dated from 6200-4350 BCE, with a hiatus in settlement from 5600-4800 BCE.

title: Libraries' Courtyard at Hadrian's Villa
description: The Libraries' Courtyard belongs to the republican period and is one of the most ancient gardens at Hadrian's Villa. It is enclosed in a large peristyle 48 m wide, 72 m long, and is located at the northern end of Villa Adriana.

title: Ionian League
description: An Ancient Greek confederation originally formed in the sixth century BCE by twelve Ionian cities, with religious festivals celebrated at Panionia.

title: Sikani
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources that is generally identified with Tell Fekheriye (Tell Faḫārīya).

title: Til-Tūri
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources that has been identified with Tell Tūrin and Thiltauri of the Tabula Pentingeriana.

title: Porte de France, Nemausus
description: A first century B.C. city gate of ancient Nemausus.

title: Erroneous Duplicate: Al-Hijr (Madâin Sâlih)
description: This place was published as an unintended duplicate of https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/814675/.

title: Scarborough Castle
description: The ruins of a medieval castle built ca. A.D. 1135 by William le Gros, Earl of Albemarle. Now an English Heritage site.

title: Roman signal station at Scarborough
description: A Roman signal station dating from ca. A.D. 370. Comprising a ditch, an inner wall with bastions, and a signal tower, it was used until the early fifth century.

title: Tell Mohammad Diyab
description: An archaeological site in northeastern Syria inhabited in the Early Dynastic through post-Akkadian period (ca. 2750-1800 BCE).

title: Wadi al-Jarf
description: Site on the Red Sea Coast in Egypt, used in the Fourth Dynasty as a port for importing turquoise and copper from Sinai. The oldest surviving papyrus from Egypt, dated during the reign of Khufu (26th century BCE), was found at the site.

title: Byrsa
description: Walled citadel in Carthage built in the early first millennium BCE. The site was destroyed during the Third Punic War in 146 BCE by the forces of Scipio Aemilianus. The hill became the site of the city's forum in the Roman period.

title: Theater at Telmessos
description: The ancient theater at Telmessos (Fethiye) dates to the reign of Augustus.

title: Büyükkale
description: The royal citadel of Hattusa.

title: Theater at Cyrrus/Hagioupolis
description: The Roman theater at Cyrrus dates ca. A.D. 100 - 220.

title: So-called Temple 1 at Hattusa
description: Temple 1, also referred to as the "Great Temple", is located in the lower city of Hattusa. It dates to the thirteenth century B.C.

title: Temple of the Severan family
description: Near a complex of baths built under Commodus a Severan complex that included a plaza, porticoes, and a temple dedicated to the Severan family was added.

title: Macellum of Sagalassos
description: The Roman Macellum of Sagalassos.

title: Roman theater at Italica
description: The Roman theater at Italica could accommodate 3,000 spectators. It predates the Hadrianic rebuilding of the city.

title: Maiden Tower (Baku)
description: A twelfth-century monument in the Old City, Baku, Azerbaijan.

title: Lyceum
description: The seat of Aristotle's Peripatetic school of philosophy at Athens founded in 335/4 B.C. The Lyceum was destroyed by Sulla in 86 B.C.

title: Walls of Caerwent (Venta Silurum)
description: The city walls of Venta Silurum (modern Caerwent) are among the best-preserved Roman period city walls in Britain. The walls were constructed around the 3rd century CE, augmenting an earlier earthwork defense system, with external towers added in the mid 4th century.

title: Porte Noire (Besançon)
description: A Gallo-Roman triumphal arch dedicated to Marcus Aurelius.

title: Jewry Wall
description: The so-called "Jewry Wall" is a substantial segment of surviving Roman masonry at Ratae.

title: Aldborough Studforth Hill
description: Archaeological remains at 'Aldborough Studforth Hill' site may be the location of possible Roman amphitheater.

title: Cardiff Castle
description: Cardiff Castle incorporates remains of the antecedent Roman fort.

title: Roman temple of Vic

description: The temple on the Sacra Via dedicated to the deified Iulius Caesar, authorized in 42 B.C. and built by Augustus, with its dedication occurring on 18th August, 29 B.C.

title: Çatalhöyük west mound
description: Human settlement on the West Mound of Ҫatalhöyük began later than its eastern counterpart and continued longer. The mound is commonly associated with the Early Chalcolithic period, ca. 5,900-5,600 B.C.

title: Necropoli delle Pianacce
description: An Etruscan necropolis with tombs ranging in date from the sixth to the second centuries B.C. In 2003 the fourth-century painted tomb of the 'infernal quadriga' was discovered.

title: Oppidum de Sermuz
description: The oppidum of Sermuz, Switzerland, is an archaeological site that preserves the remains of an Iron Age murus gallicus that originally stretched some 130 meters.

title: Mont Vully oppidum

title: Tell ej-Judeideh

title: Tanakun

title: Pavlopetri

title: Kasku (region)

title: Til-karme

title: Paqarhubuni (settlement)

The city and its surrounding region were between the kingdoms of Gurgum and Kummuhu.

title: Usian
description: A fortress in the vicinity of Til-garimmu fortified by the Assyrian king Sargon II (r. 721-705 BC) against Musku (Phrygia).

title: Ashur/‘Lamban’?/‘Liba(nai)’?
description: Aššur, modern Qal'at Sherqat, is an Assyrian city on the western bank of the Tigris River. Named after its enigmatic tutelary deity, it was the original capital, ancestral home, and burial place of the Assyrian royal family. From the late third millennium B.C. until 614 B.C., when the city was captured and destroyed by the Medes, Aššur was Assyria's most important religious center. It was also Assyria's principal administrative center until the beginning of the ninth century, when Ashurnasirpal II (883-859) moved the capital to the newly constructed Calah.

title: Nimrud
description: In the ninth century BC, Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883-859 BC) built himself a new administrative center. Kalhu (biblical Calah) — modern Nimrud, a site identified as Larissa, a city mentioned in Xenophon’s Anabasis — became the capital of the Assyrian Empire, replacing Ashur, which had served as Assyria’s capital since the third millennium BC. The city — which is located twenty miles south of the modern Mosul and which occupied a strategic position six miles north of the point where the Tigris River meets the Greater/Upper Zab — served as Assyria’s capital until the reign of Sargon II (r. 721–705 BC). Although Kalhu never again became the primary residence of Assyria’s kings, that city remained a vital administrative, military, and religious center until the fall of the Assyrian Empire.

title: Lago di Monterosi

description: A Bronze and Iron Age archaeological site in Gilead in the eastern valley of the Jordan river

title: Torre Ciega
description: A Roman tower-type tomb of the first century B.C.

title: San Vitale
description: The basilica of Saints Vitalis, Valeris, Gervase and Protase, commonly known as the Basilica di San Vitale, is a titular minor basilica church in Rome. The church was built ca. AD 400 by Pope Innocent I.

title: Van Fortress
description: Van Fortress is an ancient citadel of Urartu built during the ninth through seventh centuries BC.

title: Stadium at Epidaurus
description: This stadium, constructed in a natural depression near Epidaurus, was part of the sanctuary of Asclepius, the god of medicine and healing, and housed athletic contests in honor of the god. It dates to the fourth century B.C.

title: Bizye Roman amphitheater
description: A Roman amphitheater in eastern Thrace.

title: Samshvilde
description: Fortified settlement in southern Georgia. The Samshvilde site is one of the oldest cities in Georgia, with remains from the Bronze Age Kura-Araxes Culture. Samshvilde was an important city in the late antique and medieval periods until it was sacked in 1440 by Jahan Shah; it went in decline but was inhabited as late as the 18th-19th centuries. The site includes a number of structures, including an 11th-13th century citadel, several early medieval churches, homes, and burial grounds.

title: Southwark
description: An extensive Roman settlement located on the south bank of the river Thames opposite Londinium.

title: Wickham Bushes Romano-British settlement
description: The Romano-British settlement at Wickham Bushes is located due south from Caesar's Camp. A range of archaeological material was recovered, including numismatic evidence that ranges in date from Agrippa to Valentinian II.

title: Bronze Age Barrow at Old Winchester Hill
description: A number of Bronze Age barrow tombs are found within the general area of the Iron Age hill fort.

title: Civitavecchia di Arpino
description: The fortified acropolis of the ancient city of Arpinum.

title: Roman bridge of Saint-Vincent

title: Beaumont-sur-Oise amphitheater

title: Baths of Caracalla (Albano Laziale)

title: Aridi
description: A town in the province of Guzana that is mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources. Aridi is identified as modern Tell ʿArāda.

title: Padakku/Fadak
description: Ancient Padakku/Fadak is an oasis town in the Arabian Peninsula that is idenified with the modern city al-Ḥā’iṭ.

title: Wadi Bastura Tunnel Inscription
description: Several stone blocks forming the entrance to a tunnel make up part of an aqueduct that Sennacherib had built to divert water from the Bastura River (a tributary of the Upper Zab) to Arbela, a principal cult city of the goddess Ištar. One ashlar block bears an eight-line inscription recording the construction of a (subterranean) watercourse.

title: Temple of Athena Skiras at Phaleron
description: This sanctuary, reported in Phaleron by Pausanias, is thought to have been located near the modern "old town" of Phaleron in Attica. It is not to be confused with the Temple of Athena Skiras on the island of Salamis, reported by Herodotus.

title: Hordiivka necropolis
description: A Bronze Age burial site located near the modern town of Hordiivka on the southern Bug River.

title: Zabala
description: This Sumerian/Babylonian city (also known as Zabalam, now as modern Tell Ibzeikh) was a cult centre of the goddess Inanna/Ishtar. It was located near the Iturungal and Ninagina canals.

title: Barbarano Romano
description: Barbarano Romano is a Medieval town in the province of Viterbo that has produced substantial archaeological evidence of Villanovan and Orientalizing habitation.

title: Tower of Seneca
description: The Tower of Seneca is a sixteenth century castle in Corsica built atop the remains of a Roman watchtower.

title: Roman Forum at Syracuse
description: The area, roughly situated between the island of Ortygia and the district of Acradina, was used as an agora and, in later years, as the forum of the city of Syracuse. It is now a public park where ancient ruins are still visible.

title: So-called Roman Gymnasium at Syracuse
description: A monumental complex in the ancient city of Syracuse, probably built around the first century AD. It was initially identified as a gymnasium or a thermal bath; it includes the ruins of a theatre, a quadriporticus, and a temple.

title: Salvatoretto
description: The remains of a Roman villa and cistern.

title: Caer Gai
description: The site of a Roman fort in Wales occupied during the late first and early second centuries A.D.

title: Gallaberry Camp
description: A Roman temporary marching camp that was identified via cropmarks in June 1939. The camp covered 1.33 acres and measured 64 x 110 meters.

title: Qalaat al-Madiq
description: A town and medieval fortress in northwestern Syria adjacent to the site of ancient Apamea.

title: Rabati Malik
description: An eleventh-century caravanserai along the Silk Road, now located in Uzbekistan. Rabati Malik Caravanserai was built under Karakhanid Shams-al-Mulk Nasr, son of Tamgachkhan Ibragim who ruled in Samarkand from 1068 to 1080. The site was added to the UNESCO World Heritage Tentative List in 2008.

title: Gard (river)
description: Tributary of the Rhodanus (Rhone)

title: Andalucía (region)
description: The region of Andalucía (Andalusia in English), located in the south of Spain, is the second largest and the most populous region of modern Spain. At one time it belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Much of the modern region is coincident with the extent of ancient Baetica.

title: Almonaster
description: A Spanish village located in the northern part of the province of Huelva that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X.

title: Teiada
description: A Spanish place located in the northwest of the province of Huelva that belonged to the kingdom of Alfonso X. Known today as Tejada, Tejada la Nueva or Aldea de Tejada.

title: San Demetrio ne' Vestini
description: A settlement that was an important center of the Vestini in the Abruzzo.

title: Maa
description: A fortified settlement on Cyprus dating to the thirteenth and twelfth centuries B.C.

title: Porte d'Auguste of Nemausus
description: A first century gate of Nemausus, also known as the "Porte d'Arles".

title: Sissû
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources. It is identified with modern Kozan (formerly Sis) and classical Sision.

title: Zamahu
description: A town mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources that is identified with modern Tell ar-Rimāḥ.

title: Temple of Augustus et Livia
description: The so-called Temple of Augustus et Livia dates ca. 10 B.C. and was originally dedicated to Roma and Augustus. The temple was located on the ancient forum of the city. By the fifth century the temple had become a Christian church. It was extensively restored in the nineteenth century.

title: Basilica of Sant'Apollinare in Classe
description: A basilica begun in the sixth century AD by Bishop Ursicinus with financial support from the Greek banker Iulianus Argentarius.

title: Temple of Amphiaraus
description: The Temple of Amphiaraus is an oracular temple dedicated to the hero/god Amphiaraus, located within the sanctuary of the Amphiareion. The site was believed to have healing powers and was particularly important in the Late Classical and Hellenistic periods (fifth to third centuries BCE).

title: Les Mesnuls
description: In the 1960s an imperial Roman villa was excavated at the La Millière locality, located on the edge of the Rambouillet forest.

title: Bryn Celli Ddu
description: A Neolithic mound site on the island of Anglesey.

title: Via Claudia Augusta
description: The Via Claudia Augusta was a Roman road that traversed the Alps, connecting the Po river valley to Rhaetia. It was begun by Claudius in AD 46/7.

title: Cattigara
description: Cattigara was a port city of the Sinae, located south of Thinae near the mouth of the river Cottiaris. Ptolemy considers the city to be the extreme southeastern-most point of the known world.

title: Kenan Tepe
description: Ancient site on the Tigris river in Turkey

title: Nuraghe Goni
description: Nuraghe Goni is located atop a plateau overlooking Lake Mulargia.

title: Porta Aurelia
description: A gate in the Aurelian Wall at the summit of the Ianiculum through which the Via Aurelia passes.

title: Forum granary
description: Roman granaries of the forum in Pompeii. (VII,7,29).

title: tribus Lemonia
description: An older rural tribe of ancient Rome.

title: tribus Menenia
description: The gens Menenia was an ancient patrician line that lent its name to the tribus Menenia.

title: tribus Papiria
description: The tribus Papiria is one of the earliest rural tribes of Rome.

title: Stabian Baths
description: The Stabian Baths (VII, 1, 8) and (VII,2) are located at the intersection of the Via Stabiana and the Via dell'Abbondanza. They are the oldest baths in Pompeii.

title: Porta Latina
description: A city gate in the Aurelian Wall that was substantially modified under Honorius in the fifth century A.D.

title: Santa Venera al Pozzo
description: An archaeological area in Sicily, near Acireale, possibly related to the ancient settlement of Acium.

title: Urartu
description: An eastern Anatolian kingdom on the eastern shore of Lake Van. Originating from a regional collection of principalities first mentioned in the 13th century BCE, it had become a single political entity by the 9th century BCE. Urartu was a powerful rival to the Neo-Assyrian Empire. It ceased to exist sometime in the late 7th or early 6th century BCE.

title: Lepti Minus Roman amphitheater
description: The Roman amphitheater of Lepti Minus.

title: Gallo-Roman theater at Alba Helviorum
description: A third and fourth century theater at Alba Helviorum.

title: Adab
description: Bismaya, ancient Adab, is a major archaeological mound in southern Iraq. The site is located in the present-day Wāsiṭ Province about 65 kilometres south of al-Kūt. Excavations by E.J. Banks from 1903-05 uncovered extensive remains of the ancient city of Adab, predominantly dating to the 3rd and early 2nd millennium BCE. In its day, Adab was renowned especially for its temple, the Emaẖ, dedicated to the goddess Ninẖursag.

title: Magidû
description: Magidû or Megiddo (modern Tell al-Mutesellim, "The Tell of the Governor") is an ancient settlement mound located in northern Israel near Kibbutz Megiddo, about 30 km southeast of Haifa. Bronze Age Megiddo was an important Canaanite city-state and during the Iron Age, it was a royal city in the Kingdom of Israel. The site is mentioned in Neo-Assyrian sources.

title: Toora-Dash
description: Archaeological site at the interfleuve of the Yenisei and Khemchik Rivers in Tuva. The site, which flooded by the construction of the Sayano-Shushenskaya power plant in the mid-1980s, contained artifacts from the Neolithic through the Medieval periods.

title: Teleutskiy Vzvoz-I
description: Mound site on the Ob River in Altai Kray, Russia with burials from the Early Bronze Age Elunin culture.

title: Kaymakçı
description: A large Bronze Age settlement on the western shore of lake Marmara in western Anatolia, overlooking the central Gediz river valley. The site is composed of an 8 hectare fortified citadel situated on a ridge, with evidence for a larger lower town below on the surrounding plain.

title: Porticus Pompei
description: A porticus built in 55 B.C. in connection with the Theater of Pompey. The Curia Pompei, site of Iulius Caesar's assassination in 44 B.C., was likely located within the portico.

title: Hexamilion wall
description: The Hexamilion wall is an ancient defensive wall built across the Isthmus of Corinth that protected the only land route into the Peloponnese from mainland Greece.

title: Arrone (river)
description: The Arrone flows from Lake Bracciano to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

title: Etruscan altar of Grotta Porcina
description: A rock-cut altar dating to the first half of the sixth century B.C.

title: Punta della Vipera Etruscan temple
description: A coastal Etruscan sanctuary that dates ca. 540-530 B.C. with additional architectural phases dating to the fourth through second centuries B.C.

title: Vetralla
description: The origins of Vetralla proper, located some two kilometers from Forum Cassii, lie in the early Middle Ages, but Etruscan and Roman remains are abundant in its territory.

title: Ponte Camillario
description: A Roman bridge on the Via Cassia.

title: Huntingdonshire Monument 97
description: An Iron Age and early Roman farmstead located near Orton Longueville, Cambridgeshire. Salvage excavations were conducted in 1974 prior to highway construction that destroyed the site.

title: Orton Longueville
description: The site of Orton Longueville has evidence for multi-period human activity. A large timber building is built in the second century A.D., followed by a Romano-British villa dating from the third to fifth centuries.

title: Cetona
description: The present town of Cetona grew around the rocca (fortress) of the tenth century A.D., although occupation at the site reaches back to the Paleolithic when a number of caves show evidence for human activity. There are also indications of an Etruscan phase of occupation.

title: Ploutonion at Hierapolis
description: The Ploutonion at Hierapolis is a walled sanctuary dedicated to Pluto and Kore.

title: Viminal Hill
description: The Viminal Hill, located between the Quirinal and Esquiline hills, is the smallest of the so-called seven hills of Rome.

title: Passo delle Capannelle
description: The Capannelle pass is an Apennine pass located in the Abruzzo.

title: Via Rovigno d'Istria catacombs
description: A small catacomb on two levels was discovered excavated in the tuff bedrock in 1953-1954 near the tract of the modern Via Prenestina in the Via Rovigno d'Istria.

title: Via Taranto columbaria
description: Two early imperial columbaria were discovered in 1932 along the Via Taranto.

title: Le Caldane
description: Ancient thermal baths in use from the Etrusco-Roman period onward.

title: Villa delle Terme degli Stucchi Dipinti
description: An imperial villa, perhaps abandoned in the late first century A.D., located near Tor Vergata.

title: Enkomi
description: Enkomi is the site of an important Middle Bronze Age settlement in eastern Cyprus.

title: Greta Bridge
description: A Roman fort and associated vicus at modern Greta Bridge (UK).

title: Radlett
description: A Roman villa and bath building, dating between the second and fourth centuries AD.

title: Oldbury Camp
description: An Iron Age hillfort located in Kent that dates to the first century A.D. and shows signs for at least partial reorganization following the Roman invasion of Britain.

title: Šuruppak
description: An ancient Sumerian city located about 35 miles south of Nippur on the banks of the Euphrates river. A place from the TAVO index.

title: Great Orme
description: The Great Orme is a prominent limestone headland located in Llandudno on the north coast of Wales.

title: Grimes Graves
description: Grimes Graves is the site of a Neolithic flint mining complex near Brandon in England that was in use from ca. 3000 to 1900 BC.

title: Sweet Track
description: Sweet Track is an ancient timber causeway of Britain built at the end of the fourth millennium BC.

title: Flag Fen
description: Flag Fen is a Bronze Age ritual site near Peterborough, England, comprised of 60,000 timbers arranged in five rows that connect Whittlesey Island with Peterborough. Dendrochronological evidence has dates the site to ca. 1365–967 BC.

title: Cheddar Gorge
description: The Cheddar Gorge is a limestone gorge in the Mendip Hills, near Somerset, England. The gorge and its many caves are the site of human activity dating back to the Upper Paleolithic.

title: Wansdyke (earthwork)
description: Wansdyke is a series of Medieval defensive linear earthworks in the West Country of England.

title: Ruborough Camp
description: Ruborough Camp is a triangular-shaped promontory fort, comprised of double bank with a medial ditch.

title: Barbury Castle
description: Barbury Castle is an Iron Age hill fort in Wiltshire, England.

title: Ham Hill Hillfort
description: Ham Hill Hill fort is an 85 hectare hillfort in Somerset, England.

title: Cadbury Castle
description: Cadbury Castle is a hill fort located in South Cadbury, Somerset, England.

title: Scratchbury Camp
description: Scratchbury Camp, Wiltshire, England, is the site of a 15 hectare hill fort.

title: Figsbury Ring
description: Figsbury Ring Hill fort, Wiltshire, England, is a univallate hill fort that covers 15.5 acres.

title: Kokino
description: Kokino is a Bronze Age archaeological site located in the Republic of Macedonia. The earliest occupational evidence belongs to the early second millennium BC.

title: Kissonerga-Skalia
description: Kissonerga-Skalia is an archaeological site dating to the Early Middle Cypriot Bronze Age (EM-MC ca. 2400-1650 B.C.) located north of Paphos, Cyprus.

title: Villa near Wadi Ghirza
description: An ancient villa near the Wadi Ghirza

title: Mesaoria
description: A broad plain located in north-central Cyprus.

title: Suburban Baths
description: A first century BC bath complex in Pompeii built against the walls near the Porta Marina

title: Nuraghe Domu Beccia
description: A nuragic complex near Uras, Sardinia.

title: Nuraghe Ruggiu
description: A nuragic site located near Pozzomaggiore, Sardinia.

title: Forum Boarium (at Rome)
description: Rome's so-called "cattle market", the Forum Boarium is a key area of commercial and ritual activity on the east bank of the river Tiber. It is flanked by the Capitoline, Palatine, and Aventine hills.

title: Ara Maxima Herculis
description: An early cult center connected with Herakles located in Rome's Forum Boarium.

title: Aedes Herculis Pompeiani
description: A temple of Hercules located near the Circus Maximus.

title: Aedes Hercules Custos
description: The temple of Hercules Custos was located near the Circus Flaminius in Rome.

title: Vicus Nediensis
description: A Roman vicus, attested by name in inscriptions discovered in the 19th century. Based on the reported findspots of the inscriptions, the vicus seems to have been located in the vicinity of modern Spechbach, located southeast of Heidelberg, Germany.

title: Roman theater at Salona
description: The Roman theater of Salona.

title: Shara Temple at Umma
description: Large temple at Tell Jokha/Umma dedicated to the Sumerian god Shara. The temple was constructed by king Šu-Suen of the Third Dynasty of Ur (2035-2027 BCE), and was used during the Ur III-Old Babylonian periods.

title: Villa of Manlius Vopiscus
description: A villa site near Tivoli that has long been associated Manlius Vopiscus, who is mentioned by Statius. Excavations were begun in 1825. In 1835 Pope Gregory XVI began construction of his eponymous Villa Gregoriana on the grounds of the Roman villa.

title: Tomb of Cossinia
description: A Roman tomb on the right bank of the Anio discovered in 1929. The tomb dates to the first century A.D. and is associated with Cossinia, a priestess of the cult of Vesta.

title: HaBesor Stream
description: The largest stream of the southern Negev, the HaBesor Stream (Hebrew: נחל הבשור‎, Nahal HaBesor) is a wadi that flows from Mount Boker into the Mediterranean Sea near Al-Zahra in the Gaza Strip, where it is known as the Wadi Ghazzeh.

title: Lake Matese
description: Lake Matese is a glacial lake located in the Matese mountains at the foot of Monte Miletto and Monte Gallinola.

title: Bathampton Down
description: Bathampton Down is a limestone plateau near Bath, England, with evidence for human settlement dating from the Mesolithic Period.

title: Bindon Hill
description: Bindon Hill is the site of extensive Iron Age earthworks on a coastal hill area in Dorset, England.

title: Uffington White Horse
description: The Uffington White Horse is stylized prehistoric hill figure dating to the later prehistoric period in England.

title: White Castle hillfort
description: White Castle hillfort is an Iron Age fort located in Scotland.

title: Broch of Mousa
description: The Broch of Mousa is a drystone broch in Scotland, dating ca. 400-200 BC.

title: Black Ball Camp
description: Black Ball Camp or Gallox hill fort is an Iron Age hill fort in Dunster, Somerset, England.

title: Grabbist Hillfort
description: Grabbist Hillfort is an Iron Age hill-fort located west of Dunster in Somerset, England.

title: Worlebury Camp
description: Worlebury Camp is the site of an Iron Age hill fort in Somerset, England.

title: Amphitheater of Alba Fucens
description: A first century A.D. amphitheater at Alba Fucens built during the reign of Tiberius.

title: Corinth Roman Amphitheater
description: The small Roman amphitheater at Corinth was located northeast of the Temple of Apollo. It has been suggested that it dates to the early days of the Roman colony, perhaps placing its construction in the first century B.C.

title: Domus, M. Tullius Cicero
description: The house of the Roman statesman and orator M. Tullius Cicero was located on the north-eastern corner of the Palatine Hill in Rome.

title: Santalla de Bóveda
description: The Roman sanctuary of Santalla de Bóveda dates to the second through fourth centuries A.D. It is located in the parish of Santalla de Bóveda de Meralocated near Lugo. Discovered in 1926, the site is a protected national monument.
